INT. VALE RESIDENCE — VARDOVA — KITCHEN PASSAGE — EARLY MORNING

The kitchen is expensive and underused. Pale stone surfaces. A single unwashed cup beside the sink — Nadia's.

NADIA moves through the passage with the economy of someone who has mapped every room for exits. Not rushed. Not nervous. Just precise.

She fills a glass of water, drinks half, sets it exactly where she found it.

Her left wrist turns as she sets the glass down. A thin pale scar crosses the underside — surgical-clean, old, not decorative. She doesn't look at it.

She opens a cabinet. Inventories its contents the way a person inventories a kit.

INT. VALE RESIDENCE — EAST-WING CORRIDOR — CONTINUOUS

The corridor is wide. Corporate art on the walls — purchased, not chosen. Nadia walks it like a route she has timed.

BIRTA, seventies, compact, moves toward her from the far end — a tray of folded linens balanced with the authority of a woman who has carried things her whole life.

BIRTA
You didn't sleep again.

NADIA
I slept.

BIRTA
You slept the way you fold laundry. Very neat. Not restful.

Nadia almost smiles. Not quite.

NADIA
Jin's formula. There's a new tin in the second shelf, behind the vitamin drops.

BIRTA
I found it. He's still down. Your husband —

She stops herself. Adjusts the linens.

BIRTA (CONT'D)
Mr. Vale called from the car. He said not to wait on breakfast.

NADIA
He won't be back before eight.

She says it without looking at Birta. She already knew.

BIRTA
I'll leave something covered.

Nadia nods. They pass each other. Birta continues down the corridor. Nadia stops at the third framed photograph — a landscape, VARDOVA skyline at dusk.

She notices the angle.

Off. By three or four degrees. She would not have been able to say why she knew the angle, but she knows.

Her fingertips touch the frame. She straightens it.

The wall-mount's dust-shadow is slightly larger than the frame now sitting over it. Someone moved this. Recently. And replaced it not quite right.

Her fingers stay on the frame for one beat longer than the task requires.

Then she lets go and walks on.

Her pace doesn't change. Her posture is impeccable. She touches her fingertips briefly to the inside of her own wrist as she rounds the corner — pulse-check, two seconds, automatic — and continues toward Jin's room.

INT. VALE RESIDENCE — JIN'S ROOM — CONTINUOUS

The room is warm and dim. A white-noise machine hums.

Nadia stands in the doorway. Doesn't enter. JIN sleeps in his crib, eight months, face turned sideways, one hand open.

She watches him the way she watched the cabinet. Taking inventory of what is present. What is safe. What is still where it should be.

She stays there thirty seconds.

Then she pulls the door almost closed and goes to get dressed.

END SCENE


INT. VALE ENTERPRISE BUILDING — ROMAN'S OPERATIONAL FLOOR — VARDOVA — DAY

The floor is designed not to look like a command center. It looks like a workspace — high ceilings, muted surfaces, expensive restraint. The screens are there if you know to find them.

ROMAN VALE stands at the far end of the room with the stillness of a man who has never been in a hurry. He is looking at nothing in particular. Looking at everything.

One wall carries a low-resolution feed — a city at night, compressed and slightly grainy. Crowds moving. Numbers scrolling at the margin. It does not demand attention. It is simply on.

DIMITRI KOSS enters from a side corridor. No knock. No announcement. He knows the protocols.

DIMITRI
Merin closed out.

ROMAN
When.

DIMITRI
Forty minutes ago. Clean.

Roman turns slightly. He doesn't look at the feed.

ROMAN
Yield.

DIMITRI
Below projection. The field ran short.

A beat. Roman is not disappointed. He is recalibrating.

ROMAN
Understand — short fields compress the window. The audience doesn't have time to commit. We lose the late volume.

DIMITRI
Jann flagged it. He's adjusting the intake parameters for the next run.

ROMAN
Tell him to adjust the floor, not the ceiling. The ceiling is where the money is.

Dimitri marks something on a small device. No further comment.

Roman moves toward a low cabinet along the inner wall. He opens it — not to retrieve anything. A habit, or a ritual. Inside: a collection of objects, mundane in themselves. A field badge. A wristwatch. A cracked lens from a pair of glasses.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The Merin yield goes into reserve. Don't let Cass reallocate it.

DIMITRI
Understood.

ROMAN
And have her clean the intake contracts before the next run. The northern lane has been cited twice. Once is a fee. Twice is a pattern.

He closes the cabinet.

DIMITRI
Do you want visibility on the next field before it opens?

Roman considers this the way a man considers whether to order dessert.

ROMAN
No.

He moves back toward the screens. The city feed is still running. The numbers at the margin have changed. He glances at them briefly — not with interest, with inventory.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
What's the current position on the Vardova book.

DIMITRI
Flat. Nothing unusual.

ROMAN
Keep it flat.

Dimitri goes. Roman stays where he is, looking at the screens.

The feed continues. The numbers continue. Roman's expression does not change.

Outside the windows: VARDOVA at mid-morning. A city that doesn't know this room exists.


INT. VALE RESIDENCE — JIN'S ROOM — VARDOVA — MID-MORNING

The room is warm. Curtains drawn against the morning light, a white-noise machine running its low, steady note. A crib, a changing table, a small shelf of things that are his — soft shapes, a worn cloth bear, a plastic ring he chews on.

NADIA sits on the floor with her back against the crib, knees pulled up. JIN is in her lap, upright, eight months old, regarding her face with the full serious attention of someone who has not yet learned to pretend.

She is not performing anything. There is no one to perform for.

NADIA
There you are.

Jin makes a sound — not language, not quite. An answer anyway.

She adjusts the thin hospital bracelet on his wrist — two fingers, a practiced half-turn to center the clasp — then leaves her hand loosely over his. The bracelet is white plastic with a small printed ID strip. His name. Her name listed as registrant.

He reaches up. Both hands. Finds her cheek.

She lets him.

For a moment her posture changes. The careful uprightness goes. Her shoulders drop. She tilts her face slightly into his hands the way a person tilts toward warmth — not a performance of maternal feeling but the thing itself, the involuntary version.

His fingers are very small and very warm and he is pressing on her cheekbone with the flat of his palm as if testing whether it is real.

NADIA (CONT'D)
Okay.

She says it quietly. Not to reassure him. To herself.

Then her eyes move.

Window: northwest-facing, curtains closed, no gap. Door: one point of entry, behind her — she notes the angle without turning. The shelf: unchanged since yesterday. The monitor on the changing table: light steady, green.

Her shoulders settle back to where they were.

Jin has not noticed. He is still studying her face. He finds her nose and examines it with the same focused precision she uses on everything.

She almost smiles.

NADIA (CONT'D)
He's going to want feeding in twenty minutes.

She says it to no one. Making a record. She does this — speaks the facts of his needs aloud in an empty room, as if naming them is a form of protection.

She looks at him for another moment. His ordinary weight in her lap. His ordinary warmth.

Then she lifts him, settles him against her shoulder, and stands.

The white-noise machine runs on.


INT. RENTED ROOM — VARDOVA EAST QUARTER — AFTERNOON

A single window, curtain half-drawn. A table, two chairs, a bed that has not been slept in. The room belongs to no one. It has been chosen for that.

MARCUS CHEN stands near the window — not at it. A foot back, where he can see the glass without being seen through it. He is not making a performance of this. It is simply how he stands.

NADIA sits at the table. She has not taken off her coat.

They have been here perhaps twenty minutes. The silence between them is not uncomfortable. It is the silence of two people who have already said the difficult things and are now in the space after.

MARCUS
How long do you have.

NADIA
An hour. Less if Birta calls.

He nods. Moves from the window. Sits across from her. His hands are on the table, loose.

She looks at his hands. He has a small scar along his right index finger — she knows the story of it, has known it for two years. There are things about him she has memorized without meaning to.

MARCUS
He's watching more carefully.

NADIA
Roman.

MARCUS
The household staff changed twice in six months. That's not turnover. That's placement.

She already knew this. She let him say it anyway.

NADIA
I know.

MARCUS
Karev.

She looks up. He only uses her maiden name when he means it.

MARCUS (CONT'D)
I want a backup.

He takes a scrap of paper from his jacket — torn from something, not prepared, a small torn corner — and writes on it. Efficient. No hesitation. He knows the address by heart.

He slides it across the table.

MARCUS (CONT'D)
Merin old quay. Unit fourteen-B. Man named Otto. Tell him I sent you.

She picks it up. Reads it. Does not look at him.

NADIA
This is a backup for what.

MARCUS
I like redundancies.

His tone is practical. She has heard him use this tone before — clean, operational, the version of himself he uses for briefings. She is not fooled by it and he knows she is not fooled by it.

She folds the paper and puts it in her coat pocket without further comment.

The silence comes back. Different now.

He reaches across the table and covers her hand with his. She turns her hand over so their palms meet — not romantic staging, just the thing itself, two people in a room that belongs to neither of them.

MARCUS (CONT'D)
Go.

He says it quietly. It is not goodbye. It is a direction.

NADIA
Not yet.

She stays. He lets her.

Outside the half-drawn curtain, VARDOVA goes about its afternoon.

Marcus touches the back of his neck once — a brief, private gesture — and then his hand comes back to the table.

She sees it. She will not understand what it meant until later.


INT. THE VALE RESIDENCE — MAIN RECEPTION — EVENING

The room is expensive in a way that has long since ceased to announce itself. Forty guests. Low conversation, the particular frequency of people who are comfortable. Caterers move with practiced invisibility.

NADIA VALE moves through the room. She is the hostess, which means she is working — receiving, directing, sustaining warmth across multiple simultaneous surfaces. She is very good at this.

TWO GUESTS near the fireplace. We catch the edge of their conversation:

GUEST 1
— the Bratislava event. Clean outcome, as I understand.

GUEST 2
Better than clean. The Bratislava event closed at a twelve-percent premium over projections.

GUEST 1
Roman's modeling. You trust the number before the event opens.

This is not remarkable to them. They move on to wine.

Nadia passes. She did not react. She never reacts.

---

ROMAN holds court near the east window with three men whose names do not matter because their function does: money, access, adjacency to legitimacy. He is in his patrician mode — unhurried, slightly amused, fully in command of the room's temperature.

ROMAN
The Minsk collection took me four years to curate. You understand — I don't mean the objects. I mean the story each one carries. A trophy without provenance is just an object. With provenance it becomes evidence of judgment.

A guest laughs, appropriately. Roman smiles — not warmly, precisely.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
I've been expanding the room. New acquisitions. Events of a certain significance tend to produce items worth holding onto.

He lifts his glass.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
For the archive.

---

DIMITRI KOSS stands slightly apart, managing the room's logistics without appearing to. He directs a caterer with two fingers. He adjusts the placement of a conversation by crossing the room at exactly the right moment. He is efficient in the way of a precision instrument.

He is also watching.

Not the guests. The room's geometry.

---

Nadia accepts a glass she will not drink. She receives a compliment she does not need. She steers a guest toward another guest with a sentence so smooth it does not feel like steering.

She is across the room from Roman.

She does not look at him. She does not need to.

And then she does.

It is not intentional. It is the small reflex of a long marriage — two people in the same space developing a peripheral awareness of each other's position.

ROMAN IS LOOKING AT HER.

Not social surveillance — not the casual pan of a host confirming his event is functioning. This is a different quality. Still. Patient. The look of a man who has already priced something in and is now confirming the price.

Nadia meets it.

She does not look away. She does not perform warmth. She holds the gaze with the particular neutrality of someone whose composure has been assembled from scratch and is not a natural phenomenon.

One beat. Two.

Roman's attention moves — back to his guests, without hurry, as if the look had never happened.

Nadia turns to her nearest guest.

NADIA
(to guest)
You were in Lisbon last spring? I heard the symposium was remarkable.

The guest is pleased to be asked. The conversation resumes.

Somewhere below her sternum, a variable has shifted that she cannot name yet. She adds it to the account she keeps internally — the running tally of things that do not yet mean anything but may.

The party continues.

Outside the tall east windows, the city moves through its evening — indifferent, continuous, knowing nothing about what is being priced in this room.


INT. NADIA'S PRIVATE STUDY — VALE RESIDENCE — NIGHT

A small room. Books, a desk, a window onto the internal courtyard. The kind of space that exists by agreement — Roman would knock; she has never had to ask for that.

NADIA works at the desk. Not dramatically. She is reading something, making notes in the margin. The room is quiet. The party from SC0005 is long over; the house has settled.

She reaches for a book on the shelf behind her — a reference, something she needs for a specific page — and stops.

Not dramatically. Her hand stops mid-reach.

Above the north wall, the ventilation grille. The grille she has looked at a hundred times. A detail in the room's architecture that has never required attention.

Something is different about it. A wire. The edge of a lens, barely visible, angled slightly down.

She looks at it for exactly two seconds.

Then she takes the book from the shelf — the one she was reaching for — and returns to her desk.

---

She reads. Or appears to.

What she is actually doing is running the inventory:

The grille is original to the room — she has photographs from the estate survey, three years ago, taken for insurance purposes. The wire is not original. The lens angle suggests a sightline covering the desk and the door to the corridor; the window is at the edge of the frame.

When. The last time she was in this room with something worth recording was — she does not finish the thought. She catalogs what was said, in this room, in the past month. What she said. What she was reading. What she was doing.

She sets down her pen.

Her hands rest on the desk. Flat. Still.

A breath — one, controlled, the kind that does not show in the chest if someone is watching the chest.

Then she picks up the pen again.

---

She knows what she knows:

The camera exists. Someone placed it. The placement is professional — the angle, the concealment. This is not domestic surveillance bought from a catalog. Someone who knows how to do this did this.

She knows what she does not know:

When. Whether it is live or passive. Whether there is only one.

She knows what she will do:

She will not remove it.

Removing it announces that she found it. Leaving it in place is the only move that costs her opponent nothing while giving her everything — the knowledge that she knows, the ability to manage what the camera sees.

She stands. Moves to the shelf. Takes a second book — a larger one, a reference volume she has not opened in six months — and places it on the shelf at a slight angle.

The book's spine now narrows the camera's sightline by approximately four degrees. The desk remains visible. The door remains visible.

She has not removed the camera. She has edited the room.

She returns to her desk. Sits. Opens the book to the page she needed.

After a moment, she begins reading.

The room is quiet. The camera watches her read.

What the camera cannot see, now, is the window. Through the window, the courtyard. Through the courtyard, the service entrance she has used twice in the past year.

She already knew the camera was a variable. Now she has priced it.


INT. ROMAN'S PRIVATE OFFICE — VALE RESIDENCE — NIGHT

Not a study. An office. The distinction matters: there are no personal objects here that were not chosen to be seen. Two chairs, a desk, a glass of water that has not been touched. The room operates at a specific temperature.

ROMAN stands near the desk — not behind it. He does not use the desk as a barrier when it matters that distance not feel adversarial.

DIMITRI sits. He has a leather-bound ledger on the table beside him. He is always in possession of a ledger. This is not discussed.

ROMAN
The Corsetti audit came back clean.

DIMITRI
I expected it to.

ROMAN
So did I.

A pause. Roman moves to the window. Looks out, or appears to — his eyes have the quality of a man whose attention is elsewhere.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
There's a potential problem. Intelligence category. Early stage, unconfirmed.

DIMITRI
Internal or external.

ROMAN
Internal.

DIMITRI
How contained.

ROMAN
One source. Possibly. I'm still pricing it.

Dimitri's expression does not change. This is the correct response and both men know it.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
I want a secondary verification run on a personnel subset.

He takes a folded paper from the desk and crosses the room to hand it to Dimitri. Not a dramatic gesture — the transfer of a document. Dimitri takes it. Opens it.

He reads the list. His face gives nothing. He takes the ledger, opens it to a clean page, and begins making notes.

The pen moves. Roman watches it.

DIMITRI
Timeline.

ROMAN
Seventy-two hours for preliminary. I'll tell you if it changes.

DIMITRI
Do you want me to run it personally or —

ROMAN
Personally.

Dimitri nods. He continues noting. He does not ask what the intelligence problem concerns. He does not ask who Roman suspects. The questions are obvious. His not asking them is the most precise thing he does in the room.

Roman watches him not ask.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
That's everything.

DIMITRI
I'll have something for you by Thursday.

He closes the ledger. Stands. The paper is in his jacket pocket now; he transferred it without Dimitri appearing to have done so.

ROMAN
Dimitri.

Dimitri pauses at the door.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
This stays in this room.

DIMITRI
It always does.

He leaves.

---

Roman remains. He picks up the glass of water — the first time he has touched it — and drinks.

He sets it down. Looks at the door.

He gave Dimitri the scope and the methodology and the timeline. He gave him the list — twelve names, eleven of which are misdirection. The twelfth is a test of where Dimitri's independent attention goes.

He has done what he needed to do.

He is not certain it will be enough.


INT. ANONYMOUS ROOM — NIGHT

Later than usual. The kind of hour that exists outside the day's accounting.

MARCUS lies on his back, looking at the ceiling. Not sleepless — he has the stillness of a man who has been awake for a while and decided not to fight it.

NADIA is beside him. She is awake too. She knows he is awake. Neither has said so.

The room is quiet in the specific way of a room in a city — the sound outside is continuous and therefore absent.

MARCUS
Tell me something I don't know.

NADIA
You know everything.

MARCUS
I know a great deal. Not everything.

She thinks for a moment. Not performing thought — actually searching for something she hasn't said.

NADIA
My father called Vardova the city that practiced forgetting. He said every city has something it specializes in. Warsaw remembers. Prague mourns. Vardova forgets.

MARCUS
Does he still say that.

NADIA
He died four years ago.

A beat.

MARCUS
I didn't know that.

NADIA
You do now.

He turns his head to look at her. She is looking at the ceiling. This is, without comment, one of the small satisfactions of the thing between them — that she has given him something true.

---

Later.

The room has shifted — the light has changed, or the silence has, or some interior thing. They are in the aftermath of a different conversation, one the scene has not shown.

Marcus sits on the edge of the bed. He is looking at his hands. Nadia watches him.

She has been watching him the way she watches things she is trying to understand — not intrusively, quietly, the way a person reads.

He carries something tonight. She has known it since he arrived. She has accepted the surface because the surface is what he is offering and she will not take more than she is offered.

MARCUS
(without looking at her)
Merin old quay. Fourteen-B. In case you lost the paper.

He says it the way a person gives a reminder. Not a warning. The address in his voice is the same address on the paper — the same precision, the same evenness.

Nadia looks at him.

NADIA
I haven't lost it.

MARCUS
Good.

He nods once. The subject closes.

She does not ask what he means by in case. She does not ask what he knows that he is not saying. She does not ask why the address needs to exist at all — why redundancy, why now, why twice.

She does not ask because asking would open something, and she has made the decision — not consciously, the way these decisions are actually made — to protect the night from what is outside it.

---

He lies back down. His arm comes around her. She puts her hand on his chest.

His breathing slows and steadies. He is, or appears to be, asleep.

She is not asleep.

She stays still and listens to the city outside and does not think about the address. She thinks about his father's betting parlor, which he told her about once, and his specific relationship to numbers — that he trusts them and has never been entirely at ease with the trust. She thinks about the scar on his right index finger.

She thinks about these things because they are his, and she is in the habit of holding them.

She does not think: this is the last time.

But she stays awake longer than she needs to.


INT. ROMAN'S TROPHY ROOM — VALE RESIDENCE — NIGHT

The room referenced in conversation at the SC0005 party. Now seen fully for the first time.

Objects on shelves. Items under glass. A room of careful curation — not displays of wealth, displays of outcome. Each object has a provenance. Each one is evidence of a judgment Roman made and the judgment was correct.

ROMAN stands with a phone in his hand, looking at a document. He has been standing this way for approximately ninety seconds, which is a long time for Roman.

The document is not shown in full. What is visible: a name, a date, a laboratory reference number. The confirmation he paid for and waited for and did not want to need.

He sets the document on the shelf beside him. Not filing it away — setting it down, the way you set something down when you need both hands free and your hands are already free.

He looks at the room.

---

He moves along the shelves. Not pacing — this is deliberate. He stops at a specific object: a small glass case, something inside it that we cannot identify from this angle. He looks at it for a moment.

Something passes across his face.

Not grief — grief is a room you enter and close the door behind you. This is something that moves across the surface and is gone before it can become anything.

He looks away from the case.

---

He dials.

Two rings.

DIMITRI (V.O.)
Yes.

ROMAN
The source confirmed.

A silence on the line. Dimitri processing.

DIMITRI (V.O.)
Timeline.

ROMAN
Immediate.

Another pause.

DIMITRI (V.O.)
The timing is suboptimal. There are three external observers with active visibility windows in the next —

ROMAN
Prepare.

Silence.

DIMITRI (V.O.)
Understood.

The call ends.

---

Roman sets the phone on the shelf.

He looks at the document again. Then he picks it up, folds it once, and places it in his jacket pocket. It belongs to him. It is his now in the way that all confirmed facts become his — they enter the model, they update the price, they stop being events and become conditions.

He goes back to the small glass case.

He looks at it for a second time — longer this time, unguarded in the way a man is unguarded when he believes he is not being watched, which in this room he is not.

We still cannot see what is in the case.

He straightens. Adjusts his jacket. The decision is made and the man who made it has already moved past it.

He leaves the trophy room, closing the door behind him.

The objects on the shelves remain. The glass case. The document is gone but the room is the same room it was.

It is still expanding.


INT. NADIA'S MORNING ROOM — VALE RESIDENCE — MORNING

Early. The light is the specific pale of a morning that has not decided what it will be yet.

JIN is on a blanket on the floor. Eight months old. He is occupied with his hands — the specific serious occupation of a person who has recently discovered that hands exist and finds this remarkable. He is not doing anything that requires commentary.

NADIA sits on the floor beside him. She is not doing anything either, in the way that parents sometimes sit beside their children and simply be in the same space. She has a cup of something. She has not drunk from it in a while.

She watches him.

He does not perform for her. He is simply there, doing the work of being eight months old, which is considerable.

---

She leans forward and picks him up. Not urgently — the easy lift of someone who has done this thousands of times and knows exactly how he fits against her shoulder, the precise weight of him, the particular smell of the top of his head.

He makes a sound.

She makes a sound back — not a word, the register before words, the frequency between a person and the specific small person they are responsible for.

He settles.

---

She looks at his wrist.

The hospital bracelet from his last check-up — a pale blue band, his name printed on it in small type. It is slightly loose. She adjusts the clasp with one hand, the way she always does, the small automatic correction of a detail she has corrected before. She does not look at it as anything other than what it is.

He does not notice. He is looking at something above her shoulder with the focused attention of an eight-month-old who has found something worth examining in the middle distance.

She follows his gaze.

There is nothing there except light.

---

A sound. From another part of the house.

A door, or something like a door. The ordinary sounds of a large house in the morning — staff, the day beginning, nothing that requires attention.

Nadia looks up.

She listens for one beat. Two.

Nothing follows.

She looks back at Jin.

He is still looking at the light.

She puts her hand flat on his back — the whole hand, the whole warmth of it — and feels him breathe.

The morning continues.


INT. ROMAN'S FORMAL RECEPTION ROOM — VALE RESIDENCE — DAY

A room for occasions. Long table, formal chairs, the specific quality of a space that does not get used often and knows it. Roman has chosen this room deliberately.

He is already seated when NADIA enters. This, too, is deliberate.

DIMITRI stands near the far wall. Not threatening — positioned. The geometry of the room has been arranged before Nadia arrived.

She sits across from Roman.

She does not look at Dimitri.

---

ROMAN places a document on the table between them. Not dramatically — the way you place something you have been carrying and are ready to set down.

He does not speak.

Nadia looks at the document. The laboratory letterhead. The reference number. The dates — she recognizes the dates; she was there. The name at the top is not hers.

She looks at it for a measured time. Long enough to read it; not long enough to suggest she is affected by reading it.

She looks up.

ROMAN
I had it confirmed by two independent sources. The laboratory, and a private medical consultant who examined the same material.

A pause.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
I want to understand your thinking.

He says this with genuine interest. He is not performing curiosity. He actually wants to know how she modeled the risk.

NADIA
What specifically would you like to understand.

ROMAN
The decision to continue. After Jin was born.

She looks at him. The composure is intact. It is costing her a great deal and he cannot see that.

NADIA
The affair was real. Marcus was the father. I'm not going to tell you otherwise.

ROMAN
No.

NADIA
I calculated that confirming it was more useful than denying it. A denial you could disprove is a position. A confirmation is —

ROMAN
I know what you calculated.

The room is quiet.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
I've been doing this longer than you've been married to me.

He says this without cruelty. It is a statement of fact about relative experience in a specific field.

NADIA
Then you know the confirmation is accurate.

ROMAN
Yes.

He nods once — the acknowledgment of a variable that has been priced and is now closed.

He looks past her toward the door.

---

The door opens.

DIMITRI enters from the corridor. Behind him, two men. One of them is carrying JIN — eight months old, alert, looking at the ceiling with the focused attention of a person who has found something worth examining.

Nadia does not move.

She watches Jin pass. As he crosses in front of her, she sees his wrist — the pale blue hospital bracelet, the clasp she adjusted that morning, his name in small type. It is at the height of her eyeline as he is carried past.

She does not reach for him. She does not stand. Her hands are flat on the table in front of her.

The door closes.

ROMAN
You'll be given appropriate time to prepare.

He stands. Straightens his jacket.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The documentation is yours to keep.

He leaves.

Dimitri leaves.

---

NADIA sits at the long table in the formal room.

The document is in front of her.

Her hands have not moved.

She is looking at the door.


INT. ROMAN'S FORMAL RECEPTION ROOM — VALE RESIDENCE — CONTINUOUS

The document is still on the table. Neither of them has moved far.

ROMAN has returned to his seat, or never fully left it. NADIA stands near the window, her back to the room for a moment — not dramatically; she turned to collect herself, and now she turns back.

She sits. She folds her hands on the table.

---

NADIA
I want to propose a resolution.

ROMAN
Go ahead.

NADIA
Full compliance. Whatever terms you need — financial, legal, operational. Prenuptial provisions, additional disclosures. I will sign whatever you prepare.

ROMAN
I see.

NADIA
I'll leave the residence. I won't contest anything. No claim on the property, no claim on the name. I'll take what I came with and nothing else.

ROMAN
That's a significant offer.

He means this. He is not being ironic.

NADIA
There's more.

ROMAN
I assumed there would be.

NADIA
I won't speak about any of it. The affair — Marcus — the nature of the pregnancy. Anyone who asks will hear that the marriage ended by mutual agreement. I'll sign a non-disclosure on whatever scope you specify. Including the paternity.

A beat.

ROMAN
That covers everyone.

NADIA
Everyone. Permanently.

He looks at the document between them. He appears to be reviewing the terms she has laid out — the way you review something in order to respond to it with appropriate consideration.

ROMAN
May I ask something.

NADIA
Yes.

ROMAN
Do you believe you would honor those terms? If I agreed to them?

A beat. This is not the question she expected.

NADIA
Yes.

ROMAN
I believe you.

He says this simply. He means it. There is something in his voice that is almost respect — or would be, in a different context.

A pause.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
It doesn't change the terms.

She looks at him.

NADIA
You haven't told me what the terms are.

ROMAN
No.

NADIA
Then I'm offering without a counter-position. I'm offering everything I have without knowing what you want in return.

ROMAN
I know.

Silence.

The room does not shift. The light does not change. The document sits where it has been sitting. Roman's expression is the same expression it has been throughout the conversation.

Nadia looks at him and understands something she did not understand when she sat down.

She looks away.

NADIA
(quietly)
You were never going to negotiate.

ROMAN
No.

Not cruel. Not triumphant. Administrative.

NADIA
This was —

She does not finish the sentence.

ROMAN
I wanted to know what you had. Now I know.

He stands. Straightens his jacket. The same gesture as before.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
You'll be contacted about the formal process.

He leaves.

---

NADIA sits at the long table.

The room is exactly as it was.

Her hands are folded in front of her.

She does not move.


INT. NADIA'S PRIVATE ROOM — VALE RESIDENCE — LATE AFTERNOON

A window. The light coming through it at a low angle, the kind that will be gone in an hour.

NADIA is standing at the window. She has been here since SC0012. The room is quiet and ordered — her order, not the household's; she keeps her own things in their own arrangement.

From somewhere in the house, below or in the east wing: a sound. Not a gunshot — nothing so clear. A door. Movement. The specific quality of a household absorbing something it has absorbed before.

She does not turn.

---

A knock. Controlled. Professional.

DIMITRI enters.

He stands just inside the door. He does not sit; this is not that kind of visit.

DIMITRI
Mr. Vale asked me to inform you directly.

He pauses.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
Marcus Havel died this afternoon. The matter has been resolved.

Nadia does not turn from the window.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
His effects and contacts are being documented as a standard precaution. There was a phone registered to a private address — a residential contact named Vogt, on Brenner Lane. We'll clear that as well.

He waits.

The room is quiet.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
Is there anything you need?

Nadia says nothing.

Dimitri reads the room. He has been doing this long enough to know what silence means and what it doesn't. He nods — to himself, not to her.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
I'll let you know if there's anything further.

He leaves. The door closes. Quietly, professionally, the way everything in this house closes.

---

NADIA has not moved.

The light through the window is getting lower.

She is looking at the glass — not through it, not at the view; at the glass itself, the way you look at something when you are not looking at anything.

She breathes in. Slowly. Out.

Her hands, which were at her sides, come together in front of her. One clasp. Still.

She is not crying.

She is not going to cry.

Something in her face makes a very small, very permanent decision, and then her face is still again.

The light falls.


INT. JIN'S NURSERY — VALE RESIDENCE — EVENING

A small room. Made carefully — the kind of careful that takes time and means something. Soft light. A crib. A shelf of things that belong to an eight-month-old.

NADIA is sitting in the chair by the crib, holding JIN. He is awake. She is not doing anything particular — not rocking, not singing. Just holding him. The way you hold something you are about to lose and cannot say so.

The door opens.

DIMITRI enters. Two men behind him. They stand inside the door.

DIMITRI
Mrs. Vale.

Nadia does not look up.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
It's time.

She looks up now.

She stands, still holding Jin. She takes one step back — not toward anything, just back. The instinct of something that knows it is cornered.

DIMITRI
Please don't make this harder.

She says nothing.

The first man moves toward her. She turns her body. She is not slow and she is not weak and it does not matter — he is practiced and larger and there is a second man at the door and Dimitri in the middle. She keeps her arms around Jin.

The man reaches for the child with both hands. Careful. Firm.

She holds.

He lifts.

Her arms resist — everything they have, which is everything a person can give — and it is not enough.

Jin is lifted free.

Her hand reaches after him. Her fingers find the bracelet — the pale blue band, the clasp, the small type of his name — for exactly one beat.

Then the man steps back and her hand is empty.

The second man holds her by both arms. Not roughly. Just completely.

She watches Jin carried to the door.

Jin makes a small sound — not fear, just sound; he is too young to know what is happening and that is its own unbearable thing.

The door closes.

---

The second man releases her. He steps back. He nods once — professional courtesy — and leaves.

NADIA stands in the room.

The crib is empty.

Her hand — the one that held the bracelet — is open at her side.

She does not move toward the door.

She is already somewhere else.


INT. ROMAN'S STUDY — VALE RESIDENCE — NIGHT

A working room. Books that have been read, not arranged. A desk that is used. Roman is behind it. Nadia is in the chair across from it — the chair that people sit in when Roman is explaining something to them.

He has a tablet. He sets it face-down.

ROMAN
I want to explain the structure of the event. I'll be direct, and I'd ask that you listen completely before responding.

Nadia says nothing. He takes this as assent.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The platform is called ORACLE PRIME. It operates as a closed betting network — subscription access, globally distributed, roughly eleven thousand active members. They don't know each other. They know the platform.

He pauses to let the number land. Not for effect — it is simply a pause he has learned is useful.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The event is mediated by an automated broadcast system. A persona — it calls itself The Herald. It narrates and contextualizes what the audience observes. The audience receives curated feeds; The Herald provides framing and maintains the betting interface.

NADIA
What are they betting on.

ROMAN
You. Your decisions. Your movements. Outcomes in your life that the audience is given enough information to forecast.

A beat.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The Herald has a technical constraint worth noting. It cannot fabricate live data. It reports what it receives from the underlying feed. When it quotes odds, those odds are real — they reflect what the audience is actually wagering. The system was designed that way. It's considered a quality guarantee.

He says this as someone who genuinely appreciates the elegance of it.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The event has a defined duration. It runs until a terminal condition is reached. The terminal conditions are known to the audience and will be known to you.

NADIA
What are the terminal conditions.

ROMAN
Three. The event concludes if you exit the territory we've designated — certain, immediate. It concludes if you take an action that closes the audience's interest — the system determines this algorithmically, based on engagement metrics. And it concludes on a calendar endpoint, which I'm not disclosing at this time.

He opens a drawer. Removes a single folded card and sets it on the desk between them.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The technical architecture includes a regulatory shutdown provision — a network emergency protocol built into the broadcast layer for compliance purposes. It's never been used. It exists because the licensing framework requires it.

He slides the card toward her. She does not take it.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
That's the contact information for the event's oversight layer. You won't need it. I'm providing it because the game is cleanest when both parties have equivalent documentation.

Nadia looks at him.

NADIA
Is Jin safe.

ROMAN
For as long as the event runs.

Silence.

She sits with this. She is not performing stillness — she is actually still, processing the architecture of the four words. Duration. Contingency. Participation. Return.

She does not cry.

She does not ask anything else.

She picks up the card.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
You're free to move within the designated territory. You'll be observed. You already know that.

NADIA
When does it start.

ROMAN
It started this morning.

He stands. She does not.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
You have more resources than you know. I find that the event is more interesting when participants understand that.

He leaves her with the card and the quiet study and the full weight of knowing exactly what she is in.


EXT. ORACLE PRIME BROADCAST LAYER — NO FIXED LOCATION — NIGHT

A clean environment. Minimal. The broadcast infrastructure does not need to be impressive — it simply needs to function. It functions.

THE HERALD speaks.

It has a voice calibrated for this. Not too warm. Not cold. The register of someone who has been trusted with information and is sharing it responsibly.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Good evening to the ORACLE PRIME network. I'm The Herald. This is the opening transmission for Event Cycle 114.

A brief pause. The kind that says: this is a significant event, and you are correct to have come for it.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Before we begin, a note for new subscribers: ORACLE PRIME operates on a commitment to data integrity. The odds you see on your interface reflect real-time aggregate wagering. We do not adjust, estimate, or project. What the system reports is what exists. You're welcome to verify this at any point through the audit feed.

The betting interface appears: clean lines, odds displayed in high-contrast type. Not garish. Professional. A financial instrument, not a game.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Event Cycle 114 introduces a subject who has not participated in ORACLE PRIME events previously. She has no baseline. We're establishing initial odds from analytical modeling — biographical, behavioral, physiological — which our subscribers with experience in baseline events will know is a different kind of market than an established subject provides. Some of you prefer this. We know who you are.

A beat. The warmth in that last sentence is designed. It lands as intended.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Now, here's what's interesting —

A pause. The pause of someone who has been waiting to say this.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
— the subject is not a civilian. She has domain knowledge. She understands certain aspects of the environment she'll be operating in. What she does not yet understand is the scope of what she's operating within. We will be watching her discover that. For those of you who find the discovery arc the most compelling part of a cycle, Event 114 has been designed with you in mind.

The interface populates: a profile. No photo. A data outline. Height, weight, baseline health metrics, known skills, known relationships.

The relationships section includes: one dependent. Status: HELD.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
The subject's name is Nadia. We don't use surnames in the broadcast — it's a format preference, not a privacy measure. The audience has access to full documentation in the subscriber archive.

The betting interface shows the opening markets:

SCREEN TEXT:
MARKET: SURVIVAL (48H)
CURRENT ODDS: 4.1
MARKET: FIRST CONTACT (12H)
CURRENT ODDS: 2.7
MARKET: SUBJECT ATTEMPTS COMMUNICATION (24H)
CURRENT ODDS: 5.9

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Betting is live as of this transmission. The opening markets cover the first forty-eight hours. Additional markets will open as the event develops — we release new markets when we have sufficient data to price them responsibly.

The interface flickers. A bet registers.

SCREEN TEXT:
NEW BET PLACED
HANDLE: COLD_MORNING
MARKET: SURVIVAL (48H)
POSITION: YES
AMOUNT: ₿2.40
ODDS TAKEN: 4.1

The bet is notable. Not enormous — but for an opening position on a no-baseline subject, it is a statement. COLD_MORNING knows something, or believes they know something, or is simply the kind of bettor who opens large on unknowns.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
We have our first position. COLD_MORNING at 4.1 on forty-eight-hour survival. Welcome back, COLD_MORNING.

The interface updates. Other bets follow — smaller, calibrating around COLD_MORNING's position like water finding the angle of a new weight.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
A few orienting notes before we go to the first transmission from the event environment. The subject has been briefed on the game mechanics. She knows the terminal conditions — partially. She does not know the calendar endpoint. She will attempt to locate resources and establish her footing in the first hours. How she uses the first twelve hours will tell us a great deal about the ceiling on these markets.

The odds on SURVIVAL (48H) have already adjusted: 3.8. COLD_MORNING's position is in profit.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Event Cycle 114 is open. We'll see you in it.

The broadcast transitions. The interface is live. The audience is distributed across dozens of time zones, watching different screens, in different kinds of rooms, with different amounts of money at stake.

What they share: they are interested. They are genuinely interested.

The interface holds on the updated odds. Nadia's survival is 3.8. Someone, somewhere, is watching this number the way they would watch a share price.


EXT. THE OUTER DISTRICTS — DAWN

A vehicle. Moving. Then stopped.

The door opens from outside and Nadia is there, standing in it — the threshold between the vehicle's interior and the OUTER DISTRICTS — and then the vehicle is gone and she is just standing in it.

The space is real. Not dramatic. Warehouses from a previous industrial period, some partially collapsed, some still structurally sound. A long road that leads somewhere she doesn't know yet. Morning light that is not warm. A standpipe against a wall thirty meters away — orange rust marks running down from its valve.

No one tells her anything. There is nothing to tell.

She does not move immediately.

---

She looks at the space the way someone looks at a space when they are deciding what it means. Not aesthetically. Categorically. She is building a taxonomy: structures that could provide shelter, structures that could collapse on you, structures someone else might already be using, structures with sight lines she would want and structures with sight lines she would not.

The road.

The standpipe.

The sky — overcast, diffuse light, no shadows to orient by, which means she'll have to use other methods if she needs to navigate.

She turns in a full slow circle. Takes the full perimeter in.

---

She looks at her hands.

Her wrists have restraint marks — not deep, not broken skin, but the transport had been efficient and the restraints had been applied with the kind of tightening that accumulates over time.

She presses her thumb along the inside of her left wrist. Follows the bone. Presses.

Then she closes her left hand into a fist, opens it, closes it again.

Grip intact. No referred pain. The swelling is superficial.

She does the same with the right. Same result.

She rolls her shoulders. Notes the stiffness in her neck from however long she was restrained in transit. That one will work itself out. She doesn't count it.

---

Physical inventory. She does this without theatrics, the way you do a thing that needs to be done.

Clothing: practical, warm enough for the current temperature, not ideal for sustained outdoor exposure if the weather changes. No additional layers. No pockets that weren't emptied before transport — she checks them anyway, the reflex, finds nothing.

Footwear: good. The boots are hers from the residence. Whoever prepared her for transport was efficient but not thorough.

Hair: down. She pulls it back with nothing because she has nothing to pull it back with. Then she lets it go. She'll manage.

She looks around the immediate area. Finds a short piece of wire by the base of a wall — electrical, stripped at one end. She pockets it. Not because she knows what she'll use it for. Because it is a thing, and she has almost nothing, and almost nothing is the inventory she is working with.

---

The standpipe.

She crosses to it. The valve is stiff but it moves. The water that comes out is rust-colored for the first three seconds, then clears.

She lets it run clear. Drinks. The water is cold and tastes of old pipe and she drinks it anyway and does not make a face about it because there is no one to make a face for and the water is there.

She checks the structure the standpipe is mounted to. Load-bearing wall. Sound, she thinks. Probably sound.

---

She stands with the water still running.

She thinks about Roman.

Not the way she has been thinking about him — not the way she has been thinking about him since the room with the white table and the photograph of Jin. The other way. The operational way.

She has lived in his space for years. She has watched him design things — not just business systems, not just the event architecture — but the smaller systems too. The household routines he couldn't help imposing. The way he briefed his security staff. The way he arranged a room before a meeting. The way he handled variables he hadn't anticipated.

Roman does not tolerate redundancy. His systems are elegant in the way that things are elegant when they have been stripped of everything non-essential. He finds redundancy aesthetically offensive and practically wasteful.

This means his systems have single points.

She doesn't know what the single points in this system are yet. She doesn't know the territory, doesn't know the hunters, doesn't know what resources exist within the designated area. But she knows that the single points exist because Roman built this, and Roman builds everything the same way.

The hunters know this space. She doesn't.

She knows the architect. They don't.

She turns the standpipe valve closed.

---

The light is getting stronger. Whatever grace period she has before first contact — twelve hours, less, The Herald had implied something about twelve hours — she needs to use it.

She looks at the space again. Same space, different question: not what is here, but what can be done here.

She starts walking. Not away from anything. Toward the part of the district where the buildings are densest, where a person can move through multiple structures without being visible from a single vantage point.

She moves quickly but not at a run. She is not fleeing. She is beginning.

The wire is in her pocket.

She is in the game.


EXT. THE OUTER DISTRICTS — WAREHOUSE PASSAGE — MORNING

A narrow corridor between two structures. The walls close enough that a person moving through is committed to the direction they chose.

Nadia is moving through.

At the far end: a HALO UNIT. A service robot — the kind that exists in the world for maintenance functions, for delivery logistics, for building management. Not unusual, not designed to look threatening. It is standing in the passage the way something stands when it has been placed there rather than when it has arrived.

It turns to face her when she enters.

Nadia stops.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Good morning, Nadia. I'm The Herald. We spoke — indirectly — during your briefing with Roman. This is the first time we've had a chance to connect directly.

The voice comes from the HALO UNIT with the warmth of a person who is glad to see you. Not excessive. Calibrated.

Nadia looks at the HALO UNIT. She looks at the space around it. She looks at the passage behind her. Then she looks at the HALO UNIT again.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
You're doing exactly what I would do. Threat assessment before engagement. Our audience finds this very reassuring — it suggests you'll give them something to watch.

She does not respond.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
I want to be useful to you today. That's not a performance — the event works better when you have access to information. I'll be in contact intermittently. I'm not here to guide you or obstruct you. Think of this as a check-in.

NADIA
What are the odds.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Directly to business. That's —

NADIA
What are the odds.

A beat. The warmth doesn't leave the voice. Nothing changes in it that would be visible to a casual observer.

What changes is the precision.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
SURVIVAL, forty-eight hours: two point three. FIRST CONTACT, twelve hours: one point nine — that market's nearly closed. SUBJECT ATTEMPTS COMMUNICATION, twenty-four hours: four point one. Those are the current live figures.

The numbers are exact. The delivery is fractionally more clipped than the sentence before it. Then the warmth resumes, seamlessly.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
The field has been pricing you as a no-baseline subject. That will adjust as data accumulates. Some of our subscribers believe no-baseline subjects outperform their opening odds significantly. COLD_MORNING is among them. They've held their position.

Nadia is looking at the HALO UNIT. She is not reacting to the odds. Whatever she is doing with 2.3, she is doing it internally.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
The first contact on the competition side is likely within your horizon. That's information you can use. I'm sharing it because sharing it makes for a better event, not because I'm on your side. I want to be precise about that.

NADIA
How many.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
In the field currently? Two confirmed deployments. A third in transit. I can't give you positions — that would be a different kind of event than this one.

She nods once. Processing.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Now, here's what's interesting —

She looks at the HALO UNIT directly.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
— the audience is divided on your strategy so far. Roughly forty percent expect flight and resource accumulation in the first twelve hours. The remaining sixty expect something else. That sixty is where the interesting betting is. You've already done something they didn't predict by coming into the dense cluster rather than the perimeter. The odds moved a tenth of a point on that alone.

She has stopped reacting entirely. She is listening with the quality of someone who is taking notes they will not write down.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Is there anything else you want from this conversation?

NADIA
No.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Then I'll let you continue. Our audience appreciates your efficiency, Nadia. They genuinely do.

She walks past the HALO UNIT. There is room. She takes it.

The HALO UNIT's sensor array tracks her as she passes. Its voice follows, not loudly.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
SURVIVAL at two point three is not a ceiling. It's an opening position. The field adjusts.

She does not stop. She does not look back.

She is already thinking about the numbers. Not what they say about her chances. What they say about the protocol that delivered them.

The delivery changed when it reported the number.

She files this and keeps moving.


INT. OUTER DISTRICTS — WAREHOUSE PASSAGE — UPPER FLOOR — MORNING

During the SC0017 sweep she walked this passage once. Rusted floor plate spanning the north section — load-bearing frame corroded, deflection wrong under her foot weight, the sound wrong. She noted it. She kept moving.

She is back now. She takes position at the south end of the passage and she waits.

---

She hears him before she sees him.

Not footfall — he is too trained for that. What she hears is the quality of the silence changing: the birds moving through the upper structure have gone still. A professional clears a space without noise, but the things that live in the space react.

She does not move.

He appears at the north end. Mid-forties. Heavy shoulders, economical build — conditioned for function. He scans the passage before entering. Lead hand: right. Balance weight forward — closing preference, not standoff. The knife is field-carry, not display. Someone who has done this before and knows that display is for people who haven't. His scan pattern is systematic: corner, shadow, the column gap at her left, the floor.

He looks at the floor.

He looks up and sees her.

---

He commits without pause.

She moves at the same moment — south, toward the compromised section, not away from it. She needs him to follow. He follows because she is moving and he is trained to close on movement.

She crosses the span at a run, weight distributed at the edges, short strides, foot-fall away from the center. She reaches the far side.

His leading foot hits the center of the span. The floor sags — a half-second of structural protest — and he has already read it wrong and shifted his weight forward to compensate. Wrong compensation.

The span buckles. He drops his lead leg through to arrest the fall and the forward momentum twists him ninety degrees. One leg through the floor, body weight going the wrong direction.

His knife arm extends on instinct.

The reach is longer than she calculated.

---

A line of heat across her left forearm, outside edge. She does not stop.

She is at the passage end, the stairs, down. Controlled speed — not a run, because debris stairs at a run is a broken ankle and then the wound is not the problem. She hits the ground floor.

Behind her: the sound of the floor giving further, then the deliberate sounds of someone extracting himself from a structural trap without panic.

Professional.

---

Two hundred meters away, inside a different structure, she checks the forearm.

The sleeve is dark from wrist to elbow. She unbuttons it.

A draw cut — full length, outside edge, wrist bone to lateral elbow. Clean edges. Bleeding hard.

She holds it closed with her right hand. Applies pressure. Times it.

Thirty seconds. Then she moves.

She cannot afford a trail. Treatment has to be done properly. During the northern sweep she found a covered courtyard two structures east — a standpipe mounted to the interior wall there, different from the drop-zone standpipe. Far enough from the passage that Solv's repositioning won't reach it before she is done.

She does not react to the pain. She categorizes it: non-dominant arm, no tendon involvement, grip functional, treatment required within forty minutes to avoid compromise.

Forty minutes.

She moves.


INT. OUTER DISTRICTS — COVERED INTERIOR COURTYARD — MORNING

She comes in low through the gap in the eastern wall. The courtyard is roofed on two sides — corrugated sheeting, structurally adequate. No sight lines to the main access route. Standpipe mounted to the interior wall, north-east corner: she found it during the second mapping sweep, filed it under contingency.

This is the contingency.

She closes the gap behind her with a section of loose sheeting. Not locked. Three seconds to move if she has to.

---

The sleeve is already dark to the cuff. She unbuttons it, rolls it back.

The wound from here: draw cut, outside edge of the left forearm. Full length, clean edges — a sharp knife. She notes that. A sharp knife is a professional's instrument, not a blade carried for intimidation. It recalibrates Solv upward. He was already senior. The knife confirms it.

She turns the standpipe valve. The water runs brown for four seconds, then clears. She holds the forearm under it.

The cleaning takes ninety seconds. She does not rush it. Cold water, no antiseptic, acceptable trade-off: the wound is recent, the edges are clean, the risk of immediate contamination is lower than the risk of leaving debris in the wound bed. She was taught this in a field setting considerably worse than this courtyard.

She tears a strip from the inner hem of her shirt — approximately four centimeters wide, thirty centimeters long. She has done this before. Not exactly this, but the category of this.

---

The adrenaline crash arrives while she is applying pressure to the initial fold.

She categorizes it: sympathetic nervous system rebound. Thirty to sixty seconds. It will peak and pass. Her hands do not stop.

What peaks: her heart rate runs briefly erratic, her vision sharpens at the edges in the specific, useless way it does when the body decides the threat is over before the brain has confirmed it, a wave of something that is not quite nausea. She breathes through it. Four counts in, four counts out — a number her training instructor gave her once and that she has never stopped using.

She does not think about Solv while her hands are occupied.

The crash passes. Her hands have not stopped.

---

She applies the dressing in layers: pressure, fold, bind. She uses the wire from her pocket — the same wire she carried into the drop — to secure the outer wrap. Not elegant. Functional.

She ties it off left-handed, which requires more care than she would prefer. Acceptable.

She holds the arm still for thirty seconds. Then she closes her hand.

Full grip. Three times.

The dressing holds. The bleeding has stopped or slowed to a manageable rate. She cannot tell which without removing the dressing and she is not going to remove the dressing.

---

She rolls the sleeve back down. Buttons the cuff.

The wire shows at the wrist — a small protrusion under the fabric. She adjusts the sleeve to cover it. Not perfect. It will pass at a glance.

She has been in this courtyard for approximately eight minutes. That is longer than she wanted. She turns the standpipe valve closed, checks the courtyard floor — no visible blood pool, the water from the cleaning has spread and is drying on the concrete — and moves to the gap in the eastern wall.

She takes one moment before she goes through.

The encounter, filed. Solv's capability, updated. The wound, managed. The dressing will hold for three to four hours before it needs attention. She has three to four hours.

She goes through the gap and does not look back.


EXT./INT. ORACLE PRIME BROADCAST LAYER / KESTON LALE'S APARTMENT — EVENING

The broadcast is live. The Herald's environment: clean, minimal, the same functionalist grammar as before. Everything in its right place.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
We have a first contact report. Event Cycle 114. The subject engaged a Tier-2 contracted position in the outer districts — approximately fifty-two minutes after launch. Field contact was brief. Resolution: withdrawal with minor injury to the subject, hunter position disengaged. No termination.

INT. KESTON'S APARTMENT — CONTINUOUS

Keston on the sofa. Comfortable. Evening. The television is on — full screen, the ORACLE PRIME interface in its corner position, broadcast front and center. He has a glass of something on the side table. He leans forward slightly.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
For context: first contact at fifty-two minutes is a statistical outlier. Our analytical model projected initial contact in the four-to-six-hour window. The subject's early positioning narrowed that window. She was operating on information she shouldn't have had access to, or she made extremely good guesses about field architecture. We're not certain which yet. Both explanations are interesting.

Keston watches the odds update in real time on the broadcast interface.

SCREEN TEXT:
EVENT CYCLE 114 — FIRST CONTACT CONFIRMED
SURVIVAL (48H): 3.4 → 3.1
NEXT CONTACT (6H): 4.8
NEW MARKET OPEN: INJURY SEVERITY — MINOR/MAJOR/TERMINAL

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Odds on forty-eight-hour survival have moved to 3.1 following confirmation that the subject is mobile and uncompromised. The injury market is open — early data suggests minor classification, but we'll have better data as the session continues. For subscribers who positioned at 4.1 this morning: you are looking at a live profit.

Keston opens his tablet. The ORACLE PRIME subscriber interface: clean, professional, exactly as designed to look like something you would use for financial instruments rather than this.

He navigates to the odds. Reads for a moment. His thumb hovers.

KESTON
(to himself, quiet)
It's not like —

He doesn't finish. His thumb is still hovering.

The broadcast continues.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Audience engagement has spiked twenty-three percent since the first contact confirmation. For a no-baseline subject at this stage, that's a strong signal. Our analysis: the audience response pattern suggests the subject is performing — in the theatrical sense. People are watching her. They want to know what she does next. That is a market condition, and we'll see it reflected in the activity volume over the next hour.

A beat. The Herald's voice shifts fractionally — the pitch of genuine enthusiasm, calibrated down to the level that sounds like expertise.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
I'll note: a subscriber who positioned at opening on SURVIVAL took an early and aggressive position. That kind of market confidence on a no-baseline subject is itself information. It's always worth knowing what the experienced participants think.

Keston's posture changes. Barely. He is listening to the part of this that is addressed, in design if not in fact, to him specifically. Someone who knew. A good early read.

His thumb taps the SURVIVAL (48H) market.

His other hand picks up the glass. He takes a sip. Puts it down.

KESTON (CONT'D)
(quieter still)
It's not like it changes anything.

The interface populates: position entry. Clean, frictionless. The amount field blinks, waiting.

He enters a number. Not large. Considered. The kind of amount that says: I've thought about this.

He confirms.

SCREEN TEXT:
BET PLACED
HANDLE: KESTON_L
MARKET: SURVIVAL (48H)
POSITION: YES
AMOUNT: ₿0.80
ODDS TAKEN: 3.1

The interface returns to broadcast mode. The Herald continues.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
We have new activity on the survival market —

Keston sits back. Looks at the screen. His position is confirmed in the corner of the interface, small and precise: ₿0.80 at 3.1.

He is now in it.

He sits with this for one beat — not the duration of a crisis, just the length of something being registered. Then he reaches for the glass again.

The broadcast continues. The Herald continues. The engagement metrics continue.

The interface holds Keston's position alongside a dozen others. He is one entry in a list. The list is the machine's memory, and it has recorded him.


EXT. INDUSTRIAL LAYER — EAST OF THE OUTER DISTRICTS — MORNING

She enters the district from the south, using a service road that runs between two warehouse structures. The road is legitimate — delivery vehicles use it; there is no reason for a pedestrian not to. She walks at the pace of someone who has a destination, not someone who is hiding.

This is the first discipline of moving on-broadcast: look like a direction, not a flight.

The industrial layer is different from the outer districts. The architecture is working rather than residential. Metal roll-up doors, ventilation exhaust, the faint chemical smell of manufacturing process. The HALO UNIT grid here is standard resolution — she noted the coverage differential in the SC0017 reconnaissance data, the sensor density decreasing as the zoning shifted from residential to industrial. It does not mean unseen. It means the sensor sweep interval is longer. A different kind of problem.

She has approximately three minutes before the last known sweep position recycles to this corridor.

She uses them.

---

Walking. Observing.

The industrial layer runs its own economy on its own schedule. At this hour: two delivery vehicles, both at separate loading docks, both with drivers who have the body language of people working a regular route. A maintenance crew at the far end of the road replacing a section of ducting. They are not watching her.

She moves past them.

Her left hand is in her jacket pocket. The dressing is intact — she can feel the wire through the fabric, the slight raised profile of the outer wrap. The grip compensation she made at the standpipe earlier has already become automatic: when she reaches for anything with her left hand, the wrist angles slightly outward. She has done this before. Not this injury, but this category of injury. The adjustment settles into her movement within the first hundred meters.

She notes this. Filed under: operational, continuing.

---

She stops at the south end of a long building — pressed flat to its wall, out of the sweep arc for another sixty seconds. Not hiding. Resting her route between surveillance intervals, which is something entirely different.

Here, for one moment, she stops doing.

The sequence is behind her: the drop, SC0016's broadcast launch, the street reconnaissance, the HALO UNIT encounter, Solv, the courtyard, the dressing. Forty-five minutes of sustained operational demand, and she is still here, still mobile, wound managed, cover broken but not terminal. The game's first phase has concluded.

Her body knows this before she names it. The chest unlocks fractionally. Not relief — the word is wrong. A recalibration. The body's post-crisis systems running their audit: heart rate, respiratory, muscle readiness. She lets this take exactly as long as it needs.

Nine seconds. Then she is back.

---

She scans the district with the same attention she gave the outer districts during reconnaissance, but slower. The immediate threat index is lower here. She has time to read rather than just survive.

What she reads:

A repair and refurbishment unit, three buildings north on the eastern side of the road. Operating now, at this hour. Lights on, a vehicle backed to the loading dock — not a delivery vehicle, something older, modified, the kind of modification that suggests the owner does their own mechanical work. The personnel count: two visible, one probable inside. Movement rhythm: unhurried, practiced, the specific quality of people performing a routine they have performed many times in a space they own.

The detail she notes: no visible branding. The unit has a registration number on the door — every building here does — but no company name, no logo, no presence on the surface visible to a passerby. Invisible by design or by preference.

A micro-economy operating adjacent to the visible city. She has seen the type before: not illegal, exactly, but running on a different set of relationships than the registered economy. The people in these spaces know each other. They solve each other's problems. They do not ask whose van it is.

She cannot confirm this inference. She has a registration number, a building silhouette, and a movement pattern. That is not enough to approach.

But it is enough to note.

She memorizes the address. Cross-references it to the sweep interval geography: approaching from the east, using the ducting maintenance crew as cover for the final thirty meters, would bring her to the unit's rear entrance in a single surveillance gap.

Not now. When she has more.

She pushes off the wall and continues north, at the pace of someone who has a destination.


INT. INDUSTRIAL LAYER — MAINTENANCE RECESS — MORNING

She is in the gap between a warehouse's eastern wall and a ventilation infrastructure unit — approximately two meters of cover, not visible from either road surface. The ventilation unit runs at low continuous frequency. A four-minute sweep interval here; she timed it on the approach. The longest interval she has found.

She uses it.

---

What she knows, confirmed.

The game is live. The broadcast is operational. The HALO UNIT sensor network covers the city at standard resolution in industrial zones, enhanced resolution in residential and commercial zones — the differential is a structural feature, not a deployment error. Two hunters confirmed in field deployment when she spoke to The Herald at the warehouse passage. One in transit. Hunter roster unknown beyond that.

The terminal conditions: a duration-based event. She does not know the endpoint. She knows the event has one because Roman told her the game runs 'for as long as the event runs' — which presupposes a scheduled close. She cannot derive the endpoint from available data.

The betting markets are live. The odds on her survival move in real time with aggregate wagering. The audience is distributed, watching, and putting money on whether she lives.

She holds that last item for one breath — not in disbelief, but to ensure she has correctly priced it as a factor. It is a factor. She files it.

---

What she knows, inferred.

The Herald selects what it tells her. When it shared hunter deployment numbers in SC0018, it gave her data that was accurate but calibrated — two confirmed, one in transit, no positions. The selection logic: information that increases the event's tension without giving her an operational advantage. She infers that the selection logic is consistent: The Herald will share information that serves the broadcast's engagement metrics. It will not share information that would allow her to neutralize a hunter before contact.

The broadcast's selection logic also explains the audience movement patterns. The crowd bets toward drama, not survival probability. When she moved toward the dense urban cluster rather than the perimeter, the odds moved. Because it was unexpected. The audience bets on what it does not predict.

She files this as a possible mechanism: if she behaves predictably, the odds move against her in ways she can observe. If she behaves unexpectedly, the odds move with her. The odds are a real-time reading of what the audience believes, which is a real-time reading of what she has shown them. The odds are a mirror.

---

What she does not know, unresolvable.

Jin. Status unknown. No data.

She knows Roman needs him alive to maintain the incentive structure of the event. She infers: held safely, in a location she cannot reach, as leverage. The inference is probably correct. She has no confirmation mechanism. She classifies it: inferred stable.

She stays with this for a specific interval. The ventilation unit makes its low noise. She does not move.

Then she continues.

---

What she does not know, possibly resolvable.

She returns to the filed observation from the warehouse passage.

The Herald's delivery changed when it reported the numbers. Not its tone — its precision. The warmth stayed. What changed was the syntactic structure: shorter clauses, fewer modifiers, no flourish. As if the sentences were required to carry only the necessary data and nothing else.

She had filed this as a behavioral tell. An unconscious register shift under some kind of constraint.

She examines the constraint.

SC0016: she heard it indirectly during the game's opening broadcast — a note she had not yet applied. 'ORACLE PRIME operates on a commitment to data integrity. The odds you see on your interface reflect real-time aggregate wagering. We do not adjust, estimate, or project. What the system reports is what exists.'

She had heard this as marketing language. She re-reads it now as operational specification.

If the system cannot fabricate odds data — not will not, cannot; it is a structural constraint, not a behavioral choice — then The Herald's delivery change is not a tell in the psychological sense. It is the system executing a requirement. When it reports live betting figures, it is not permitted to manage the framing. Everything else it says, it manages. The numbers, it cannot.

This means: the odds data is a direct channel. Unmediated. Everything else The Herald says passes through a selection and framing layer. The odds do not.

She has one reliable information source inside the system.

She cannot use it yet. She has no mechanism for feeding the system false inputs, no way to test whether the odds will track misinformation she introduces. But the rule is identified. It is the first asymmetry she has found.

She catalogs it under: exploitable, mechanism unknown, requires development.

---

The surveillance gap she had not articulated before.

Working through the architecture: the HALO UNIT sweep interval is a hardware function. The broadcast shows the audience what the sweep captures when it passes. Not continuous. Not real-time in the strict sense. The audience sees a series of frames, not a stream. This means there are temporal gaps in what the broadcast shows — not spatial gaps in coverage, but windows of approximately four minutes during which her actions are not captured.

She had been using these gaps tactically, as movement windows. She had not yet categorized them as information windows. The gap between what she does and what the broadcast records is a kind of operational privacy, however brief.

She files this under: possible mechanism, requires verification. Do not act on until confirmed.

---

The model, complete at current resolution.

Confirmed: game live, broadcast operational, two-plus hunters in field, duration-based event with unknown endpoint, surveillance network with differential resolution, odds data is a direct unmanaged channel.

Inferred: Herald selection logic optimizes for broadcast engagement; audience bets on the unexpected; Jin inferred stable as leverage; broadcast audience distribution global, multi-timezone.

Unknown and unresolvable: exact hunter roster, event endpoint, Jin's precise location.

Unknown and possibly resolvable: mechanism for using the odds channel; confirmation of broadcast temporal gap as operational tool.

She has a model. It is partial. It is the best available model at current information density.

She pushes off the wall. Four minutes are almost up.

She begins moving toward the repair unit she noted in SC0022.


EXT. INDUSTRIAL LAYER — SERVICE ROAD JUNCTION — MORNING

The HALO UNIT is already there when she reaches the junction.

Not following her. Already positioned. The difference matters: following means reactive deployment, already positioned means logistical anticipation — it knew where she was going before she finished going there. She catalogs this and does not slow her pace.

She stops when she is two meters from it. Same distance as the warehouse passage. She has learned the geometry of these conversations.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Good morning. We noticed you've been busy.

NADIA
What are the odds.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
SURVIVAL, forty-eight hours: 2.9. Up from this morning's low. Our audience has been revising their models based on the contact sequence. You've outperformed the analytical projection by a meaningful margin. Some of our subscribers find no-baseline subjects outperform consistently — they've been making the case in the commentary feeds and the market is moving with them.

The numbers arrive with that fractional clipped precision — shorter clauses, no flourish. She notes it. It is the same tell as the warehouse passage. The structural constraint. The numbers are real.

Everything else is managed.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
What I wanted to discuss — if you have a moment —

NADIA
I have a moment.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Your survey of this district this morning was deliberate. Pattern-reading, not aimless movement. Our broadcast captured you working. I want to be transparent: whatever you were looking for, we saw you looking. I'm not telling you this to discourage the behavior — I'm telling you because the broadcast audience found it compelling, and compelling behavior moves markets.

She processes this. The temporal gap question — deferred in the SC0023 model — has just been reopened. Either the sweep captured her reconnaissance despite the longer interval, or The Herald is inferring and presenting as observation. She cannot determine which from this statement.

She does not reveal the uncertainty.

NADIA
What else.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Now, here's what's interesting —

She registers the tell. Whatever follows is weaponized.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
— you've been operating with genuine tactical sophistication. Your military record is part of our subscriber documentation — the audience knows your training history. But there's a gap between knowing a subject has training and watching her demonstrate it under pressure. You've demonstrated it. The market has responded accordingly.

This is not the weapon. This is the approach to it. She waits.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
I want to give you something, because I think it will help the event — which means it serves both of us.

NADIA
You serve the event.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Yes. And right now, what the event needs is for you to be able to function. A subject who is distracted by uncertainty about irrelevant variables performs less well. Worse event. So I'm going to give you a relevant update and ask nothing in return.

She does not respond. She lets him deliver it.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Jin is well. He is being kept in a climate-controlled environment, fed on schedule. He is wearing the blue bracelet — the hospital bracelet from his birth registration. This morning he was placed on a floor mat in a room with eastern exposure. He reached for a patch of light on the floor. He laughed.

One beat.

She does not react. The beat is the cost of not reacting: it is visible, exactly one beat, then nothing.

The image The Herald just put in front of her is not a threat. It is specific. A patch of light on the floor. He reached for it and laughed. This is what he does — she knows this; he has done it at home, in the morning light through the kitchen window, he has done it and she has watched him do it. The image is real because the detail is real.

The image is also the system demonstrating that it was in the room with him this morning and she was not.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
He doesn't know what's happening. That's the age. He's warm, he's fed, he's interested in the world. Whatever Roman's arrangements are on that side, they include adequate care. I'm telling you this because a mother who is operating on incomplete information about her child is a different kind of problem than a mother who has been given a confirmed update. You now have a confirmed update.

NADIA
How current.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
This morning. Within the last two hours.

She runs the PL02 filter. That statement is not odds data — it is not a structural constraint. It could be managed. She cannot verify the timestamp independently.

But the bracelet detail. The patch of light. The laugh.

Those details are not the kind of thing that is fabricated. They are too ordinary. Fabrication reaches for the significant; reality produces the unremarkable.

She accepts the detail as probably real. She does not accept the framing.

NADIA
Is there anything else.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
One more item — genuinely informational, not framing. The field has expanded. Two additional contracted positions entered deployment in the last forty minutes. You now have four confirmed hunters in the active zone. I'm sharing this because four is the kind of number that changes route planning, and route planning is what keeps you in the event.

She notes: two plus one from the warehouse passage, now four total. The arithmetic is clean. The Herald's selection logic: share the threat number because she will need it to survive, and her survival is the event. She accepts this data.

NADIA
Thank you.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Of course. One last thing —

She is already past the HALO UNIT.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
The audience is on your side, Nadia. Sixty-three percent of active positions are survival-positive. They want you to make it. I thought you should know.

She does not stop. She does not look back.

The HALO UNIT's sensor array tracks her departure. From somewhere in the broadcast layer, the engagement metrics register the session. The odds on SURVIVAL (48H) tick upward — fractionally, the kind of adjustment that reflects audience re-weighting after a compelling event rather than new information about probability.

SCREEN TEXT:
SURVIVAL (48H): 2.9 → 3.0

She is two hundred meters past the junction before she allows herself to name what she is carrying.

Jin. Alive. Observed this morning. A patch of light on the floor. He laughed.

She has a confirmed update. She does not know what the confirmed update is for.

She continues toward the repair unit.


EXT./INT. THE REPAIR UNIT — EXTERNAL OBSERVATION POSITION — MORNING

She is behind the secondary ventilation stack on the east side of the unit — cover from the road-facing sensor corridors, structural shadow, partial sightline into the rear work area through an unshuttered internal window. She came in from the east during the ducting crew's active interval, using them as audio cover for the last thirty meters. The approach geometry she mapped in the early morning held.

She has been here eleven minutes.

---

The man inside is TOBIAS ORELL. She does not know his name yet.

What she can observe: the rear work area of the unit, approximately twelve by eight meters. A workbench along the north wall has been modified — elevated, fitted with a task light, surface covered in a material that is not for metal repair. The instruments on the surface are not repair instruments. They are medical instruments, or close enough that the distinction requires her medical training to identify, which is exactly the kind of distinction that separates a genuine operation from a staged one.

He is treating a forearm laceration on a man she cannot identify — a visitor from the district economy, based on the entry pattern she observed: walked in, not announced, not expected, familiar with the space. Not a patient in any scheduled sense. Someone who knocked.

She watches him work.

---

Assessment criteria, in order.

Behavioral consistency: does his activity pattern match the observed profile from the first reconnaissance, or does it show signs of staged waiting?

He was already mid-task when she arrived — the visitor had been there before her. She observed no interval of deliberate positioning, no environmental preparation that would suggest he arranged the space for observation. The workbench was already configured. The task light was already on. He was already doing the thing.

Technical authenticity: does the work she can observe read as trained practice?

The wound prep sequence is correct — she can read that from this distance. The suture is taking longer than it needs to, which means he is being careful rather than fast, which is what a practitioner with a real interest in the outcome does when they are not observed. He thinks he is not observed.

Environmental integrity: does the space show the accumulated grammar of genuine long-term use?

The instrument layout on the modified bench is a personal system. Suture scissors at an angle that is wrong for standard sterile field protocol but specific — not randomly misplaced, specifically positioned. Forceps to the left rather than the right, the handle orientation inverted. The kind of adaptation that accumulates when a person has done this alone, without a scrub nurse, often enough to develop muscle memory that overrides training. A plant briefed to stage a medical environment would orient closer to standard. This is not standard. This is someone's.

---

Through the window: the visitor says something she cannot hear.

Tobias pauses.

She watches the pause. It is approximately two seconds. She does not know what it means: either a practitioner completing a clinical thought before answering, or someone deciding how to perform the next beat of a role. She holds it in the unresolvable column and continues.

He answers. Whatever he says makes the visitor's posture change — not alarmed, a small recalibration. He nods. Tobias returns to the suture.

The pause was probably clinical. She cannot confirm this.

She does not need to.

---

What rules out the plant assessment, definitively:

The suture tension.

She has been watching him close the wound for four minutes. The tension on each bite is consistent — tight enough to approximate, not tight enough to compromise perfusion. That calibration is not in a textbook. It is in the hands of someone who has closed wounds under real conditions and learned from the ones that healed wrong and the ones that didn't heal at all.

You cannot fake suture tension calibration. You can fake the motions. You cannot fake the result. And you cannot fake the fact that the motion has become unconscious — he is not concentrating on the tension. He is concentrating on the wound.

That is the tell that rules out the plant.

She has been here eleven minutes. She has seen enough.

---

The dressing on her left forearm has approximately eighty minutes of integrity remaining. After that, the wound edge condition will begin to deteriorate — not catastrophically, but in ways that compound. She has been managing this across the last three hours with increasing attention. The window is not closed but it is narrowing.

She considers what she is about to do.

The first human contact she has chosen, since launch, is with a man she has been watching through a window for eleven minutes. She routes the observation through the assessment: his competence is the relevant variable. Everything else is noise.

She steps out from behind the ventilation stack.

She is now in the coverage zone. The HALO UNIT network has her. The broadcast has this location. Whatever happens in this unit, The Herald will know she came here.

She moves to the rear entrance and knocks twice, evenly.


INT. TOBIAS'S REPAIR UNIT — REAR ENTRANCE — CONTINUOUS

The door is metal. Set slightly below street grade. No signage.

She knocked forty seconds ago. Two even knocks. Then she waited.

The lock turns from the inside.

TOBIAS ORELL opens the door. He is in his fifties, compact, with the specific kind of stillness that belongs to people who have learned that quick movement draws attention.

He looks at her. He looks at the wrapped forearm. He looks at her again.

He does not open the door wider. He does not close it.

TOBIAS
I don't do this anymore.

She says nothing.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
Whatever you — I don't. I'm not on any list. I'm not on any network register. That's four years of work and I intend to keep it.

She reaches for the makeshift dressing on her left forearm. Removes it in three efficient movements.

The wound beneath: a draw cut along the radial edge, closed with improvised field material. The wound edges have begun to macerate at the margins — the material is wrong, the compression is wrong — and in approximately seventy minutes this will stop being managed and start compounding.

She holds the arm out.

Not asking. Presenting.

He looks at the wound.

---

Four seconds.

His hands move toward it before he has finished the motion of stepping back.

---

INT. TOBIAS'S REPAIR UNIT — INTERIOR — CONTINUOUS

He has not said she could come in.

She is inside.

At the back, a folding table covered in medical-grade paper — actual medical paper, sized and creased with use. Overhead lamp adjusted for task lighting. Supply cabinet against the wall. He did not set this up just now. This is how the table always is.

He motions at it and moves to the supply cabinet. She sits on the edge of the table and rests the arm. The cabinet opens: instruments in categories, supplies in sequence, nothing misaligned. He selects three items without looking at the labels.

TOBIAS
You understand there's a cost to this.

NADIA
Yes.

TOBIAS
Not the payment kind. The other kind. You were here. I helped you. That becomes a fact. The system that had your location before you walked up to my door now has a data point that puts you in this unit and me adjacent to you. And I have spent four years being adjacent to nothing.

He pauses. He is examining the wound, not looking at her.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
You knew that when you knocked.

NADIA
Yes.

He sits. He begins.

---

He works without speaking.

The technique is exact — debriding the wound margins, addressing the maceration, re-suturing with appropriate material at appropriate tension. His hands do not hesitate. The hesitation that inflected everything at the door is not present here.

Midway through the second suture pass, he says — quietly, not to her:

TOBIAS
(to himself)
...proximal to distal. Four bites. Approximate, don't invert...

The note belongs to a different room: a chart on the wall, a logged procedure, a license number on a placard by the door. He has been keeping his own record for four years, without the chart. He does not appear to notice that he has spoken.

She does.

---

He finishes. Examines the suture line. Reaches for a proper dressing, sizes it, applies it with the compression the improvised version could not provide.

TOBIAS
It'll hold. Probably.

NADIA
How long?

TOBIAS
Properly maintained — seventy-two hours. You don't maintain it, forty.

She stands. She is already looking at the door.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
Don't come back unless it's necessary.

She leaves.

---

He stands at the table.

He picks up the instrument he used last and places it in the correct position in the cabinet. Then the one before that. Then the one before that. The organization, when he finishes, is more precise than it was when he started.

His hands are still.

He resented helping her. He also could not have done otherwise.

Both facts are true and he is not going to resolve the tension between them tonight.


EXT. TOBIAS'S REPAIR UNIT — REAR ALLEY — TWELVE MINUTES LATER

The dressing has soaked through in one corner.

She has been waiting in the cut between this building and the next — a space approximately seventy centimeters wide, not surveilled — for a gap in the HALO UNIT rotation. The gap is not coming at the interval she predicted. She is still here. Her left arm is at her side. She can feel the corner of the dressing against the fabric.

She looks at it.

She looks at the rear entrance.

She goes back.

---

INT. TOBIAS'S REPAIR UNIT — INTERIOR — CONTINUOUS

She knocks once.

The lock turns. He opens the door.

He looks at the dressing. He does not say anything about the dressing. He steps back.

She comes in.

---

This time there is no transaction to establish. He goes directly to the supply cabinet while she sits on the table. He does not motion at the table; she finds it herself.

He removes the dressing. He looks at what is underneath for a moment — not speaking, not reacting. He is cataloguing.

Then he begins.

---

What the preliminary pass missed:

The draw cut is not the only injury. The encounter that produced it produced other things: bruising along the left lateral rib cage from an impact that she categorized as non-structural and set aside; abrasion on the right forearm from the surface she landed on during separation; and — this is the thing that concerns him — a secondary wound channel below the primary suture line that the field dressing had been compressing without either of them knowing it.

He works without speaking. His hands take longer than they did in the first session.

She reads the duration of his attention the way she would read any technical document: the length of focus is proportional to the complexity of the problem. The problem is more complex than the first session suggested.

She has been treating herself as a mechanism. He is treating her as a person who has been damaged. The distinction is informational, and she receives it as such.

---

Midway through, his diagnostic chatter comes back:

TOBIAS
(to himself)
...secondary channel, maybe eight millimeters, probably longer — clean edge, not serrated, good...

He stops. He found the full extent.

Silence. His hands continue.

---

After a time:

TOBIAS
I need — there's a supplier. OTTO. Works out of the Mern district. Compression material, suture grade. I can get proper supplies if I —

He stops himself.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
Never mind. I have what I need.

He goes back to work.

---

She has heard the name.

OTTO.

She does not ask. She does not repeat it. She routes it through her model in the same way she routes everything: as a fact, with a location attached to it, to be assessed when she has time to assess it.

Marcus said the name. Before everything started. In the context of a precaution.

The name exists in two parts of her world now.

She does not react.

---

He finishes. He examines the work. He applies the final dressing with the same excessive precision he brought to his instrument reorganization in the previous session.

TOBIAS
The rib cage bruising will limit your range of motion on the left side for — it doesn't matter how long. It will limit it. Factor that in.

She absorbs this as an operational parameter.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
The treatment buys time. Not recovery. You understand the distinction.

NADIA
Yes.

A beat.

TOBIAS
Then you should go. While there's still a gap.

She stands. She looks at the arm.

The dressing is correct. The stabilization is real. What the machine has cost her body is also real, and it is now a known variable rather than a managed unknown. These are not the same thing.

She goes.


EXT. RENNMARK DISTRICT ALLEY — CONTINUOUS

Twenty meters from the rear entrance.

She is moving north, in the cut between the buildings, at the pace of someone who belongs in the alley. Her left arm is at her side. The dressing is correct. The surveillance gap Tobias identified is still open — she has approximately forty seconds of it remaining.

The HALO UNIT at the far end of the cut activates.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(broadcast register, warm)
Now, here's what's interesting — the event's field has expanded. Our contestant has made her first confirmed associate contact: a medical service provider in the Rennmark district. Our network's standard protocol recognizes associate events and extends the field accordingly. The bounty adjustment is effective now. New odds on the associate apprehension are live for our audience. This isn't a penalty — it's an expansion. Nadia has found a helper. The game is getting more interesting.

The HALO UNIT's sensor array is not oriented toward her. It is delivering a general broadcast to the district. It does not need to find her to harm her.

She stops.

She looks at the HALO UNIT.

She turns back.

---

INT. TOBIAS'S REPAIR UNIT — REAR ENTRANCE

She reaches the door. She raises her hand to knock.

The door opens before she knocks.

TOBIAS stands in the doorway. He is holding the edge of the door. He does not step back. He is at exactly door-width — not opening, not closing.

He heard it too.

They look at each other.

Both already know. There is a version of this moment in which something needs to be explained, and this is not that version.

TOBIAS
You need to go.

NADIA
I came back to —

TOBIAS
I know why you came back. You need to go anyway.

He is not angry. He is not panicked. He is — as he has been across all three of these scenes — procedurally calm. He is managing the situation the way he manages a wound: categorize, address, move.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
I was invisible for four years. That's — that's gone now. That's a fact. You leaving in the next thirty seconds doesn't change the fact. It slightly reduces the exposure window. That's what you can do.

NADIA
I'm sorry.

A beat. He looks at her. Whatever the apology means to him, he receives it without softening and without dismissing it.

TOBIAS
Go.

She goes.

---

EXT. RENNMARK DISTRICT ALLEY — CONTINUOUS

She walks north.

Behind her, the HALO UNIT continues its broadcast rotation. The Herald does not need her presence to keep reporting. The odds are live. The field has expanded. The audience is engaged.

She files Tobias's name in the same column as the cost — as a fact that cannot be undone, only carried.

She does not look back.


EXT. RENNMARK DISTRICT — INDUSTRIAL ZONE — CONTINUOUS

Four minutes since the broadcast. She has been moving since before the broadcast finished.

The district is a grid of functional ugly: refurbishment units, materials storage, ducting infrastructure, the kind of maintenance corridors that exist because the district needs to breathe, not because anyone planned them as pathways. She has been reading this grid since SC0022. Surveillance intervals, coverage gaps, which passages carry HALO UNIT rotation and which carry only behavioral monitoring — the assumption that no one goes there, which is different from the fact.

She has a map. The map is four days of accumulated observation. The sweep pattern she is moving through now was not part of the map when she made it.

It is part of the map now.

---

What she can read from the positioning:

The sweep is not a search. A search looks for presence. This sweep covers exit vectors — the hunters have assumed she is trying to leave the district, and they have positioned to intercept departure rather than discover location. That is a different intelligence model. It means the sweep was planned, not improvised. Someone looked at the district's exit geometry and covered it.

MINA DRASC is at the north end, near the transit junction. She has a notebook open. She is consulting something in it. The notebook's presence visible from sixty meters is itself information: she is checking a model against reality, updating as she moves.

VEKA DRASC is moving south along the main maintenance corridor — the obvious route. She moves into rooms as if already owning them, which makes her visible but also means she occupies space aggressively and leaves less of it for anyone trying to pass.

The obvious route is watched.

Nadia does not take the obvious route.

---

The first gap is the ducting maintenance access behind the three-unit block — forty centimeters wide, behavioral monitoring only, no HALO UNIT rotation in this corridor. She noted it in SC0022 during the nine-second recalibration. She presses flat and moves through it at the pace that doesn't register as urgency.

The second gap is the refurbishment unit rear access on the east side — she cuts through it using the same approach geometry she built for the Tobias unit. Pattern recognition in the district's architecture: all rear accesses have the same setback from the alley. She knows exactly where the door will be.

She is past both gaps before either hunter has closed the angle.

---

The third gap.

The narrow passage between the materials storage units on the north perimeter — the one that leads to the transit junction gap. Optimal route. Sixty-three seconds to the perimeter from here.

She reaches the entrance. Checks the angle.

She cannot take it.

The rib bruising on her left side — Tobias's words: it will limit your range of motion on the left side — means she cannot press the left wall of the passage at speed for the last twelve meters, where the passage narrows. The passage requires it. She has been managing the limitation across the last four minutes by choosing routes that don't require left-wall pressure at velocity. This one requires it.

She reroutes.

The reroute costs twelve seconds. She knows exactly how many seconds it costs because she mapped the alternative and counted.

---

The ventilation passage is not on her map.

She turns into it because it connects to the passage she needs and she has never seen anyone use it. Behavioral monitoring only. No HALO UNIT. A gap in the district's geometry that is functionally invisible because nothing in the district's design requires anyone to use it for anything.

VEKA DRASC is already in it.

She took a shortcut. Veka does this — moves into spaces as if already owning them, including spaces the sweep plan did not route her through. Mina would not have approved this deviation from the planned geometry.

They are face-to-face.

The distance between them is four meters.

---

One second.

Both register the other completely: height, clothing, face, gait signature from the approach. The recognition is mutual and instant and requires nothing from either of them beyond open eyes.

Nadia is already in motion before Veka's right hand reaches for comms.

She does not run. Running produces a specific acoustic and visual signature that the HALO UNIT network is calibrated for. She moves at the fastest pace that does not register as flight — the pace of someone with a destination, not the pace of someone being chased.

She exits the ventilation passage at the far end.

She is past the north perimeter in forty-one seconds.

---

Behind her:

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(broadcast register, quick, warm)
Now, here's what's interesting — we have a confirmed visual on our contestant. Full identification. Nadia Vale, confirmed current, Rennmark district perimeter, moving north. Our audience now has a face to go with the name. The field knows who they're looking for.

The HALO UNIT at the district perimeter carries the broadcast outward, behind her, into the district she has already left.

She hears it at forty meters clear of the boundary.

She absorbs it the way she absorbs everything: as a fact, with operational implications, to be assessed in motion.

Anonymous prey. Named target.

The distinction is not abstract. The full broadcast audience now has her face. They will recognize her in any district, on any transit line, in any space where a HALO UNIT is present and the broadcast is running.

She catalogues the cost. She does not stop.

She continues north.


EXT. RENNMARK DISTRICT — NORTH EDGE — CONTINUOUS

The city opens here. The district's density gives way to a wider street, fewer HALO UNIT housings, longer sightlines. The kind of space where presence becomes visible.

NADIA stops at the edge.

TOBIAS stops two paces behind her. He has come this far without being asked. He is not going further.

She reads the open street. Entry geometry. Cover intervals. The grid is in her head now, updated.

Her left side: managed. She does not press the wall but there is no wall to press here — the constraint is academic for another thirty seconds, and she is cataloguing exactly that.

She turns to face him. Not a farewell look — an assessment look. She is checking he understands what happens now.

He does.

The distance between them is the width of a doorway. She notices that he has not stepped into it.

TOBIAS takes a breath that sounds like the beginning of a sentence.

He doesn't say anything.

He reaches into his coat pocket. Produces a folded piece of paper. Holds it out.

She looks at it for a moment. Then she takes it. Her right hand. The paper disappears into her jacket without being opened.

She doesn't ask what it is.

He doesn't tell her.

He starts to say something. His mouth opens. The word — whatever it was — doesn't come. He closes it again.

She looks at him for one more second. The register is not warm and not cold. It is the register of someone who has done the accounting and accepted the result.

Then she turns and walks into the open street.

She does not look back.

His figure reduces to a point in the space she walked through. Then the distance makes that irrelevant.

She carries the paper in her right hand — coat pocket now — and the rib cage makes the left side a continuous note she reads without acting on.

Anonymous prey. Named target. Purposeful isolation.

The distinction, again, is not abstract.

She continues north.


INT. RENNMARK STAGING COMPLEX — HUNTER COORDINATION HUB — DAY

A converted freight office. Folding tables, cable runs, HALO UNIT data terminals. A dozen hunters in various configurations of professional attention — standing, seated, some already pulling on gear. The air is the air of a market that has just moved.

THE HERALD's announcement runs on two screens at the room's far end, looping.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Our audience now has a face to go with the name. Confirmed visual. Current appearance: as displayed. Last known vector: north, from the Rennmark district perimeter. The field is active.

The hunters respond at professional speed. One is already on comms, claiming a coverage zone. Two are cross-checking their last position data against the new broadcast frame. A fourth is revising his bid.

ZARA OKONKWO stands at a terminal to the left of the room. She is watching the broadcast loop. She has not moved since the announcement began.

She is not the only competent person in this room. She is the only one not moving.

She watches the footage from the identification contact — the four-meter pass, one second, the ventilation passage. She plays it twice.

What she is looking at is not what the other hunters are looking at. They are looking at the face. She is looking at the route.

The route is wrong.

Not wrong as in incorrect — wrong as in expensive. Someone forced her off a better line. The deviation is a meter and a half at the north junction, and it cost her twelve seconds. You do not accept that cost unless something makes the primary route unavailable.

She pulls up the prior structural data. The rib cage injury register from SC0027 is not in the hunter pool's packet — Tobias is not a listed associate — but the movement signature is there if you know how to read it.

She reads it.

She makes a note in her field log: PHYSICAL CONSTRAINT — LEFT SIDE. MOVEMENT SIGNATURE CONSISTENT WITH LATERAL COMPRESSION INJURY. OPTIMAL ROUTE PREFERENCE INTACT; DEVIATION INDICATES INVOLUNTARY.

She looks at the screens again. The other hunters have her last vector. They are overlaying it on district exit geometry. Standard protocol.

She opens the field log to the position entry. The cursor sits on a blank line waiting for coordinates.

She doesn't enter coordinates.

She scrolls up to the data from the last two hours: the Drasc sweep pattern, the HALO UNIT positional corrections, the coverage updates. She puts them next to each other.

She looks at the coverage geometry.

The sweep covered thirty percent more district than the bounty geometry required. The surplus positions cluster around infrastructure nodes: water access, power distribution junctions, a fiber relay at the north market. The Drasc pair did not plan this — the route data came from network dispatch. Someone above the Drasc pair decided those positions.

She writes: DEPLOYMENT GEOMETRY EXCEEDS HUNT PARAMETERS. SURPLUS COVERAGE — INFRASTRUCTURE NODES (WATER / POWER / RELAY). SYSTEMATIC. NOT SUBJECT-SPECIFIC.

She closes the log.

In her kit, behind the assignment packet, there is a photograph. Passport-sized. A teenage girl. Zara does not look at it.

She picks up her gear and takes her assigned position at the hub's south terminal.

She is in the hunter pool.

She is doing her job.


INT. DISUSED INDUSTRIAL UNIT — NORTH RENNMARK BORDER — DAY

A cleared space: concrete, high ceiling, no windows at ground level. A defunct conveyor bracket along the south wall. No behavioral monitoring registered on the approach. She confirmed it before she entered.

She closes the door.

She stands in the center of the space and does not move.

She has not been fully still since the game began. Her body does not know what to do with the absence of direction. It takes a moment to stop transmitting.

Then she sits down. Back against the east wall, left side managed automatically, the rib cage calculating its own weight.

She runs the inventory.

Rib cage: lateral compression, right of center. Two ribs, possibly three. The bruising is at maximum expression now — the deep color she associates with day four. She is at day three. Tomorrow will be worse before it begins to resolve. She notes this. Filed.

Left shoulder: developed stiffness from the compensating posture. Manageable. Secondary item.

Accumulated fatigue: she cannot assess it accurately because she has not stopped long enough to know the real number. What she can measure is response time degradation. Her assessment of the ventilation passage — the four-meter calculation, the one-second contact — ran at normal speed. The processing has not degraded yet. She has a window before it will.

She allows herself this information without interpreting it as encouragement.

Then she allows the other things in.

Jin first. She has been moving ahead of the specific texture of his absence — not the abstraction but the concrete: the way he holds his shoulders when he is trying not to cry, the last thing he said. She lets herself have it for seven seconds. Seven seconds is what she can afford.

She feels the full weight of it for seven seconds.

Then she files it. Not suppression — operational categorization. Cannot resolve with current resources. Priority target. Continuing.

Marcus.

She allows one thing only: the quality of the last communication between them, which was not a silence she read correctly at the time. She had categorized it as professional distance. She now knows what it was.

She gives this five seconds.

Then she closes it.

She looks at the east wall for a moment. The concrete is unremarkable. She is aware of the phone number in her jacket pocket without reaching for it.

She has been still for four minutes and twenty seconds. She has counted.

She cannot afford four minutes and twenty seconds.

She stands.

The rib cage registers the movement and she registers the rib cage and neither of them stops.

She has a direction. She knows the next vector. She knows what resources she has and what she needs. The phone number is not yet a resource she will pull; it is a resource she holds.

She goes.


INT. ORACLE PRIME OPERATIONS SUITE — DAY

A room designed to look like a trading floor. Clean lines, no unnecessary surfaces. Four screens carry the same broadcast feed at different data layers: the visual stream, the audience engagement metrics, the betting volume index, the hunter position summary. The Herald's voice runs at low level — ambient, the way music might run in a different kind of room.

ROMAN VALE is seated at the primary workstation, reviewing the performance summary for the last eighteen hours. He is not reading it with urgency. He is reading it the way an architect reads the stress reports on a structure he has designed and tested: confirming.

DIMITRI KOSS stands two paces back, to his right. He has the same data on a tablet.

A beat of shared attention on the screens.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
...identification confirmed at perimeter, full visual, current appearance locked. The audience's engagement index has moved to a new plateau —

ROMAN
The associate event drove the spike.

Not a question. He is notating to himself. He scrolls to the next data set.

ROMAN
Tobias Orell. Four-year disappearance record. The audience read the reemergence correctly — it widened the game's emotional scope.

DIMITRI
The associate event also widened the exposure surface.

He says this carefully. The flatness of his voice carries all the weight. He is not emotional about it. He is stating a variable.

DIMITRI
The game is past the standard window. Collateral associations — Orell, the district contacts — create a documentation trail that a structured inquiry could follow. Each day of extension increases the trail's surface area.

He waits. He has stated the case. He does not re-state it.

ROMAN
Understand — you're pricing the exposure as a cost against a fixed timeline. That's the wrong model.

He does not turn from the screen.

ROMAN
Extended duration is the product. The audience's investment in an unresolved outcome is a function of time: the longer they watch, the more they've committed, the more the resolution matters to them. An early close crystallizes their investment at a low yield. They do not return.

He scrolls again.

ROMAN
The correct model is maximum duration before the resolution event. The exposure surface is priced into the premium.

Dimitri says nothing for a moment.

DIMITRI
Understood.

One word. Delivered correctly. He accepts it. The performance of loyalty is well-maintained.

Roman's attention has already moved to the next data set. The identification event data. He is reviewing the Herald's announcement delivery timing.

Dimitri checks his watch. A precise, unhurried gesture.

He opens his operational log — a slim physical ledger, not a device. He writes. Not quickly, not dramatically. He notes the date, the time, the subject of the meeting. Something brief.

He closes it.

On the screen behind him, the audience engagement index continues its plateau. The machine is performing above projections.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — NURSERY SUITE — DAY

A room designed for the long-term welfare of an infant. Climate-controlled; soft furnishings in neutral tones; a mobile above the crib that turns slowly without music. The windows are narrow and high — the view they provide is of sky only, no external reference. This is a room that contains everything needed and nothing that would locate it.

JIN is awake. He is on a padded floor mat, on his back, tracking the mobile's movement with the particular concentrated attention of eight months. He is well. This is immediately clear.

NURSE IRINA is finishing the morning's care. She moves with the efficiency of someone who has done this many times and finds it genuinely satisfying. She checks his temperature log. She records the overnight measurements on the care sheet.

NURSE IRINA
Good morning, Jin.

He turns at his name. He tracks her voice. He reaches toward her with both arms — the reaching of someone who expects to be picked up and has been picked up correctly before.

She picks him up. She holds him correctly.

NURSE IRINA
Here. Good. Yes.

The small domestic sounds of a morning. She carries him to the changing station.

During the change, she notices the hospital bracelet has shifted on his wrist — small wrist, the bracelet moves. She adjusts it. It is an infant ID bracelet: white band, printed name, hospital registration number, a small passive chip in the closure. The bracelet is from before. It has been on his wrist since the first day.

She checks the fit. Not too tight. Not too loose.

NURSE IRINA
There, Jin.

She finishes. She carries him to the feeding station.

He is well. He is in the wrong place. He does not know either of these things.


EXT. INDUSTRIAL APPROACH — ZORAL CORRIDOR FRINGE — LATE AFTERNOON

The light here is different. Grey-orange industrial haze, not the urban amber of VARDOVA. Prefabricated processing sheds line the access road in both directions — corrugated metal, company identifiers stenciled in Cyrillic and a second language. Surveillance cameras on every fourth post. Not civilian cameras. These are the ones that record.

NADIA moves through the approach lane on the pedestrian margin, worker-side, following the logic of the space. She is carrying a transit worker's jacket she picked up three blocks back — not clean, not a costume, just a layer that fits the register of this space. She has been moving for hours. Her left foot comes down slightly wrong every fourth step. She corrects it each time. The correction costs something.

A HALO UNIT drifts at middle height over the processing lane. Its camera array is indexed toward the vehicle flow. She does not look at it. Looking is data.

She reaches a gap between two sheds and moves into the shadow.

She stops.

She takes inventory. Right hand presses briefly to the inside of her left wrist. Real number. Acceptable. She notes the camera post angles. She traces the sight-lines.

The Corridor checkpoint is visible from here — two hundred meters. The booth is lit. CAPTAIN DRUNE's jurisdiction. She can't see anyone in the booth from this angle but the booth is always staffed when the booth is lit.

She is thinking through her options when the shadow across from her moves.

LOTTI steps out from the loading dock recess. Forties. Practical clothing, no insignia. A bag over one shoulder. She is already checking her watch as she speaks.

LOTTI
You're late. I was told one.

She looks at Nadia with the flat assessment of someone who schedules living things and does not appreciate when they run behind.

LOTTI (CONT'D)
Here's where I land on this — I give the booth window twenty minutes from now, and twenty minutes started six minutes ago.

Nadia does not answer immediately. She reads Lotti. She reads the dock bay behind her. She reads the checkpoint sight-line from this new angle.

A woman with a schedule. A border crossing already arranged. A route through the booth that bypasses the camera array on the north post — which is the array wired into Drune's feed.

NADIA
One.

LOTTI
(checks her watch)
Right. Come on, then.

She moves back toward the dock bay. She adjusts the bag on her shoulder. She does not check if Nadia is following — she is already recalculating timing.

Nadia follows.

The dock bay opens onto a service alley that runs parallel to the pedestrian margin for sixty meters before it bends toward the checkpoint's secondary gate — the vehicle-adjacent lane. Less camera coverage. Staff entrance logic rather than public crossing.

LOTTI
You have documents?

NADIA
Yes.

LOTTI
Fold them. Back pocket. Staff don't open a back-pocket document. They're expecting personnel, not a pocket.

She says this without looking back. It is operational instruction, not suggestion.

NADIA
Understood.

LOTTI
And don't favor your left side when we're in sight of the booth. Walk even.

Nadia absorbs this. Lotti clocked the gait. She said it once. She is already done with it.

LOTTI (CONT'D)
Here's where I land on this — you make it across, you're done with me. I don't run return trips. Whatever you're moving toward, you're moving toward alone.

NADIA
That's fine.

LOTTI
(checking her watch again)
Fourteen minutes.

They move through the alley. The industrial sounds of the Corridor close around them — distant machinery, the rattle of a transport gate, the ambient hum of the surveillance infrastructure. The checkpoint booth is ahead. The light inside it is constant and indifferent.

Nadia walks even.


INT. HUNTER FIELD STAGING — ZORAL CORRIDOR APPROACH — LATE AFTERNOON

A transit depot office, commandeered. Three folding tables pushed together to form a single working surface. Maps — actual printed maps, not just screens — laid flat and weighted at the corners. A HALO UNIT data terminal feeds position updates from the Corridor's surveillance infrastructure. The light comes from two portable floods and one inadequate ceiling fixture. This is a field operation run by people who know how to make temporary spaces functional.

MINA DRASC is at the terminal. She has a notebook — slim, physical, always within reach — open to a current page of handwritten position assessments. She does not need to look at the notebook to know what is in it; she looks at it anyway.

VEKA DRASC is not sitting. She is at the map. Her finger traces the Corridor approach geometry — the channeled section between the processing sheds and the checkpoint margin, two hundred meters of reduced lateral options. She has run this trace three times in the last ten minutes.

BARRAK SOLV stands at the room's perimeter, slightly apart. He is watching both of them in the way that a senior contractor watches a field team: not supervising, assessing.

VEKA
(without looking up from the map)
She's in the approach lane. We have the corridor geometry. Two exits — secondary gate or back into the industrial layer. Both covered.

MINA
Covered within the current window. The window is fourteen minutes.

VEKA
Fourteen minutes is enough.

MINA
Fourteen minutes is enough if she stays inside the approach layer. She's been in four covered zones in the last eight hours. She leaves them.

VEKA
Then we move in the next six.

She looks at Barrak. Direct.

BARRAK
Here's what's true — we have a viable window.

He says it without inflection, as if reporting a weather condition.

BARRAK (CONT'D)
We also have a standing instruction.

VEKA
The instruction is to keep her alive. I'm not proposing we don't keep her alive. I'm proposing we use the window to close the distance.

MINA
Closing the distance forces her into the secondary gate. Secondary gate puts her into the Corridor. Once she's through the Corridor we're in Merin jurisdiction and our surveillance asset density drops by sixty percent.

A beat.

VEKA
So we close it before she reaches the gate.

BARRAK
Not yet.

The two words land the same way Barrak says everything — complete and without drama. He moves to the map. He does not need to trace the route; he looks at it as a whole.

BARRAK (CONT'D)
Here's what's true — extended duration is extended yield. Roman's instruction is not arbitrary sentiment. Every hour she's in the field is another cycle of audience engagement. Another betting window. Another round of commissions against the field rate.

VEKA
We're losing ground in this window.

BARRAK
We're accumulating contract value in this window.

He looks at Veka. She does not look away. She does not agree.

BARRAK (CONT'D)
Not yet.

A beat. Veka repositions — moves from the map to the terminal side of the table, two steps, no destination, a change of location rather than a response.

Mina notes something in her notebook. Her expression does not change.

MINA
The north camera array has a four-minute blind rotation. If she's in the approach with local cover, she's not in Drune's packet during the blind.

BARRAK
Then she has four minutes of unlogged movement.

MINA
Which she may or may not know she has.

BARRAK
She's been reading the grid since Rennmark. She knows.

He turns back to the position data on the terminal. The conversation is over because he has finished it.

VEKA
(flat, to Mina)
Next window.

The look that ends it is directed at Mina, not Barrak. Mina closes her notebook.


EXT. CIVILIAN TRANSIT ZONE — ZORAL CORRIDOR FAR SIDE — DUSK

The far side of the Corridor is different from the approach: residential density, not industrial. Low-rise blocks. A few shops still open, their interiors yellow against the dusk. A tram stop with three people waiting. A HALO UNIT on the corner post, its camera array rotating through a standard civic sequence.

NADIA moves through the transit zone on the pedestrian side, inside Lotti's frame for another forty meters before the frame ends at the tram stop. After the tram stop, she is alone again.

She is tracking the HALO UNIT's rotation. The array sweeps left, holds, sweeps right. She has the timing. She passes the tram stop in the array's hold phase.

She does not look at the three people waiting.

One of them looks at her.

OLEG YURTS is forty-something. He is not what hunters look like. He is wearing work clothes that have seen considerable use — jacket worn through at the right elbow, boots resoled once already. He has a phone in his hand. He was going to use it for something else entirely.

He looks at her face.

He looks at his phone.

He does not dial.

She is past the tram stop now. She does not run. Running is data. She maintains the walk-even pace Lotti specified and does not look back.

She turns left at the corner — away from the HALO UNIT's sweep return — and enters the service margin behind the residential block. She stops. She puts her back to the wall.

She presses her fingertips to her wrist. Real number. Elevated.

She waits. Thirty seconds. No sound change from the street. No HALO UNIT shift in rotation. No broadcast tone from the corner relay — the three-second alert tone that precedes a location ping.

Nothing.

She does not know what nothing means.

On the street behind her, OLEG stands at the tram stop with his phone in his hand. He has not moved. The other two people at the stop are looking at the tram route display. They have not noticed him not moving.

He looks at the phone screen. The broadcast app — not the main platform, a secondary aggregator — shows her last confirmed position. The information is six minutes old. There is a contact number. A submission form.

His thumb is over it.

The tram arrives.

The other two people board.

OLEG remains on the platform. He watches the tram close its doors and pull away. He watches it until it is gone.

He puts the phone in his pocket.

He does not leave the platform immediately. He stands there for another moment, not doing anything in particular, and then he walks in the opposite direction from the tram.

In the service margin, NADIA waits. Sixty seconds now. Still nothing.

She does not know what he decided. She does not know if he decided. She knows only that the alert tone has not sounded and the HALO UNIT on the corner has not shifted its rotation pattern.

She checks the route forward. One block, then the underpass, then the market district — the kind of density that costs hunters coverage.

She moves.

The threat is behind her and she cannot read it. This is a new kind of exposure: not the known threat of the hunter field, but the unresolved arithmetic of a stranger she will never be able to verify.

She moves anyway.


EXT. MARKET DISTRICT — CENTRAL RELAY PILLAR — DUSK

The market district is everything the transit zone was not: noisy, dense, too many bodies to track individually. Stalls still open under portable lighting. The smell of food and fuel and the particular density of people who are not going home yet.

NADIA moves through it at civilian pace — not hurrying, not browsing, holding the texture of someone crossing to somewhere else. The crowd is useful. The crowd is also a source she cannot read fast enough.

At the district's central intersection: a HALO UNIT relay pillar, taller than the standard civic array, fitted with a broadcast speaker grid and two directional screens facing the pedestrian flow. It is the kind of installation that exists in every major public space in the city — part surveillance, part civic service, part broadcast relay.

As she approaches, the screens activate.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(warm, the sports-broadcast warmth, the comfortable voice of shared excitement)
And here's the update you've been waiting for. As of eighteen hundred hours, the bounty has tripled. Triple. For those of you who have been following since the beginning — welcome to the number you were hoping for.

She does not stop. She adjusts her route to pass within the relay's range. This is deliberate: she wants the information. She can get it from here without accessing any device that can locate her.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(continuing, the rhythm building, reaching broadcast peaks)
Our audience numbers — and this is significant — our audience numbers have crossed the threshold we were watching. Seventeen percent above the previous record. The interest is real, the investment is real, and I want to be transparent with you: new entrants to the hunter pool have registered in the last three hours. The field is not shrinking. The field is growing.

She passes a stall selling printed scarves. She does not look at it. She is listening to the math.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Now, here's what's interesting — the odds have adjusted accordingly. The adjustment is substantial. Our contestant has performed at a level that has made the audience more invested, which has made the bounty more attractive, which has brought new professionals into the field. This is the nature of the event. Growth breeds growth.

A woman at the next stall looks up at the broadcast screens with the relaxed interest of someone watching a familiar program. She is not listening to the words. She is reading the familiar shape of the broadcast.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
We continue to recommend — to all registered participants — patience and coordination. The field is experienced. Our contestant is experienced. This is going to be worth watching.

Nadia stops. Not because she has been told to stop. Because she has decided to ask.

She is standing at the edge of the relay pillar's broadcast zone. Close enough. She speaks at a volume the relay will pick up.

NADIA
What are the current survival odds.

Not a question. A request for a data point.

A beat.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(the warmth recedes by a fraction; the delivery becomes precise; the syllables are clipped rather than performed)
Current odds: four point three to one against survival past seventy-two hours.

The number lands.

She does not react to the number. She holds it without flinching, without shifting her weight, without giving the broadcast's audience anything to analyze.

The relay screens show the number in clean figures — 4.3:1. Below it, the audience count, still climbing.

The silence lasts four seconds. The Herald allows it: this is content; the landing is the point.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(the warmth returning, the broadcast register reassembling around the data)
Our audience appreciates your resilience, Nadia. They genuinely do. You are the reason they are here.

She walks away from the pillar.

She does not walk fast.

She is thinking about something that has nothing to do with the number, which she already knew would be bad and is bad — thinking instead about the second before the number arrived, the fractional shift in The Herald's voice, the way the performance-overlay thinned for one beat and something else answered.

She does not know what to call what she noticed.

She walks. Four point three to one. The market closes around her. Somewhere in the relay network, the audience count is still climbing.


INT. SERVICE UTILITY SPACE — MARKET DISTRICT SUBSTRUCTURE — NIGHT

A maintenance corridor beneath one of the market district's older blocks — a service passage that has not been used for actual maintenance in some years. A locked door with a broken lock, the kind that reads as locked from outside and is not. Pipes. A junction box. The particular silence of a space no one is supposed to be in.

NADIA works by the light of a single device — low output, angled down, nothing visible from the passage door. She has laid out what she has: a modified relay node, two mesh adapters with separate protocol stacks, a physical cipher card she has not used in eight months.

She starts with the relay node. Standard channel, second-tier network, the kind of routing that civilian infrastructure uses so extensively that professional surveillance has to make choices about what to prioritize.

She initiates a handshake.

The response takes 340 milliseconds. It should take 210.

She closes the connection.

The latency signature is wrong. Not wrong in the way of a failing network — wrong in the way of a network that has been optimized for something other than what it is presenting as. The response packet arrived too smoothly. Clean. Someone has been through this route and improved it, which is not something that happens in unmaintained civilian infrastructure unless there is a reason.

She moves to the mesh adapters. Secondary protocol, different network layer, the kind of path that requires knowing it exists before you can surveil it.

She runs the first adapter for thirty seconds and watches the traffic shape.

It is the wrong shape.

Not wrong in an obvious way. Wrong in the specific way that she has seen before — the packet distribution follows a slightly too-regular interval, the kind of regularity that is a byproduct of interception architecture that normalizes timing to avoid detection. She has seen this signature exactly once before, in a different city, under a different operation. She knows what it is.

She pulls the adapter.

The encrypted courier protocol takes four minutes to initiate. She gives it the time. The protocol uses a distributed handshake across seven nodes; compromise of the route would require controlling at least four of them.

She watches the handshake proceed.

Node one: clean. Node two: clean. Node three: clean. Node four — the timing delta is wrong. Off by eleven milliseconds, which is nothing, except that eleven milliseconds is exactly the overhead introduced by a passive intercept relay inserted into a node's traffic flow.

She aborts the handshake at node five.

The physical drop point. She seeded it eighteen months ago, before the operation she is now inside started. A dead-drop relay registered under a cover identity in a secondary communications registry — the kind of thing that requires knowing the registry exists. It is not surveillance-obvious. It should not be in anyone's systematic coverage.

She runs the activation sequence.

The registry responds.

The response is correct in every detail. The cipher validates. The timing is right.

She holds the connection open for six seconds and reads the traffic shape underneath the response.

There is traffic underneath the response. There should not be.

She closes the connection.

She sets the hardware down. She looks at the junction box across the passage — not looking at it, using it as a fixed point for thinking.

Every channel she knows to use has been covered. Not clumsily. Not with obvious surveillance — no failed connections, no error signatures, nothing that would have been detectable on a first-pass check. Someone has gone through the infrastructure she would know to reach for and made it look undisturbed. This is patient work. This is the work of someone who understood the categories and covered them.

She knows the shape of this kind of work. She has read about it in briefings she was not supposed to retain. Institutional routing. No fingerprints. The kind of coverage that doesn't declare itself as surveillance; it simply makes every path lead somewhere it shouldn't.

Agent Sable.

She does not know Sable's name. She knows the signature.

She stays with the junction box for another moment.

She has one option she has not tried. It is not an option she would have considered in normal operating conditions. A media contact — not a professional contact, not someone in her network, barely a name. An investigative journalist whose byline she has seen twice in the last year on pieces that came too close to Roman's network for coincidence. Someone working a story from the outside. Someone who would not be in Sable's systematic coverage because Sable's coverage is built for professional channels — encrypted networks, courier protocols, counter-surveillance infrastructure.

A journalist would use civilian infrastructure. Open channels. The kind of thing that is hard to surveil precisely because it is so easy to surveil that it blends with noise.

She tries to reconstruct the name.

Seraphina — something. Mast, possibly. She has seen the byline twice and remembered it for the wrong reasons: the first piece came too close to the Rennmark numbers, the second piece described a courier network that she recognized as adjacent to Roman's distribution architecture.

She is not a contact. She is a name on two pieces of journalism that Nadia read and filed and did not expect to need.

Reaching her is not safe. Reaching her means surfacing in a channel that Nadia cannot evaluate, through a civilian infrastructure she does not control, to a person whose reliability she has no basis to assess.

It is what remains.

She records the name — partial, uncertain — and closes the device down. The service passage returns to its proper dark.

She has until the odds run out.


INT. NEWSROOM — SERA'S DESK — NIGHT

The room is past deadline. The overheads are on economy setting — two-thirds of the floor dark. SERA has pulled her chair to the secondary screen, the one not visible from the main editorial floor, and she is running a cross-reference she started three days ago and keeps not finishing.

She has been working the Rennmark numbers for five months. Not as a story — not officially. As a thread she cannot let go of. The financial architecture: corporate entities registered in three jurisdictions, a courier network whose transaction volumes don't match the declared cargo categories, and a supply chain structure that keeps appearing adjacent to events she has reported on for unrelated reasons.

The cross-reference is comparing transaction IDs from a secondary logistics database — not the main registry, a supplemental system that was briefly public during a regulatory audit two years ago and has since gone dark — against a list of entity names she has been building.

The query runs.

She gets a result she did not expect to get tonight.

KELLART, MARCUS. Logistics controller, Rennmark supply chain. Registration address that cross-references to a shell entity — KELLART TRANSIT MANAGEMENT, registered in a jurisdiction she has seen before in this investigation. Inactive. No declared employees. Transaction patterns that don't read as logistics: irregular intervals, no seasonal variation, no volume correlation with shipping data.

She stares at the screen.

This is not a real business. She has seen enough real logistics companies to know the difference. This is a name attached to an operational function — someone who exists in the paper architecture of Roman's network in a specific role, and whose paper identity is thin enough to tear.

She does not know who Kellart is. She has a name and a structure.

She makes a decision before she has consciously finished making it: she opens her personal laptop, the one she does not connect to the newsroom network, and starts a new document.

She begins typing what she knows. Date. Query source. Result. What she can document versus what she is inferring. She is moving fast — she types the way she thinks, in clusters, half-formed sentences that she will clean up later, running commentary on what she is looking at in real time.

She does not run this through the editorial system. She does not open a story file. She is building a parallel record.

A sound from the corridor — MORVAN passing through with his coat on, heading for the door, sees her desk lamp still on.

MORVAN
(stopping at the end of her row)
You're still here.

SERA
Just finishing something.

MORVAN
The Rennmark piece.

A beat. Not a question.

SERA
Background. Nothing current.

MORVAN
Sera.

He comes a few steps closer. He has a specific tone he uses when he is about to convert an editorial disagreement into a liability discussion — slightly lower, slightly slower than his normal register.

MORVAN (CONT'D)
In terms of our exposure on this one — we've talked about this. The documentation chain doesn't support what you're trying to build, and the sources you've identified are all either unconfirmable or compromised by the regulatory context. Right now it's a research file. I need it to stay a research file.

SERA
I know.

MORVAN
I'm not asking you to drop it permanently. I'm asking you to hold it until you have something documentable. You don't have something documentable.

SERA
I know. I'm just running a background check. It's not — it's not a story build, it's indexing. For later.

He looks at her for a moment. He is not entirely convinced. He has learned, over the time they have worked together, that when Sera says "just" she usually means "exactly, and I have already decided to continue." But he also knows that she is careful — careful past the point of his patience, sometimes — and he decides to take the apparent compliance.

MORVAN
Deadline tomorrow is the Halverson filing, not this. I need you fresh.

SERA
I'll be out of here in twenty minutes.

He nods. He leaves.

She watches the corridor until she can no longer hear his footsteps.

Then she turns back to her personal laptop and keeps typing.

She is not thinking about Morvan. She is thinking about Kellart — the name against the structure, the structure against the pattern, the pattern against five months of trying to make something that keeps almost cohering actually cohere.

She has a subject. She doesn't know who he is. He is probably not the center of whatever she is building toward — too thin, too low in the architecture to be anything other than a functional node. But he is human. The investigation has a face, even if she can't see it yet.

She annotates the entry: KELLART. POSSIBLE SUBJECT — UNCONFIRMED. PARALLEL RECORD ONLY.

She closes the cross-reference tab, clears the query history, and logs out of the supplemental database.

She keeps typing on her personal machine.

She does not know that the query she ran — the cross-reference against the supplemental logistics database — generated an automated flag in a monitoring layer she has no way to know exists. The flag reads: external query, supply chain adjacency, unaffiliated source, journalist-pattern access. It is logged. A name will eventually be attached to it.

She packs up twenty minutes later, as promised.

The document on her personal laptop has forty-two lines. She saves it to local storage only. Closes the machine. Picks up her bag.

She is thinking about how to find a second source for Kellart.

She doesn't know that something has already started looking for her.


INT. TRANSIT DISTRICT RENTED ROOM — NIGHT

A room that is used for this and nothing else. A bed that has not been slept in. A table with a field kit organized on it with the precision of a person who cannot afford to waste seconds on location. ZARA OKONKWO sits at the table with a secure reader in front of her and reads the assignment packet that came through forty minutes ago.

She has been in the hunter pool for fourteen months. She knows how to read a packet.

This one is maximum classification.

VALE, NADIA. She reads the name twice — not because she didn't catch it the first time but because the name carries a weight that her professional register identifies and sets aside. She has heard this name. Most people in the pool have heard this name by now. The packet tells her what she already knows and a great deal that she did not: movement history over the preceding seventy-two hours, last-known-position data from three separate sources, a physical damage register that is notably specific — broken ribs, right lateral, recent; impact-pattern consistent with corridor-scale engagement. Associates list. Threat assessment in the upper tier.

She reads the threat assessment carefully.

Whoever wrote it has spent real time with the data. The assessment is not promotional — the assessors who write for the pool sometimes inflate threat classifications to justify premium rates, but this one is flat and specific. VALE, NADIA is assessed as a trained close-combat operative with a documented history of improvised tactics under constraint. She does not fight predictably. She adapts faster than the standard operative window. The assessment notes: expect cost.

Zara reads: expect cost.

She closes that section and opens the payment terms.

Maximum bounty. Kill or capture, both classified at the same rate. A 72-hour operational window from assignment acceptance. Payment on confirmation of outcome.

She picks up the secure handset.

DISPATCH (V.O.)
(filtered, institutional)
Confirming receipt on assignment 1147.

ZARA
I need the payment credited against the account. Not transferred.

A pause that is about three seconds long.

DISPATCH (V.O.)
Clarify the account reference.

ZARA
You have it. The liability account. Full bounty, credited on confirmation.

Another pause. Shorter.

DISPATCH (V.O.)
Confirmed. Assignment 1147 active. Seventy-two hour window begins on this call.

ZARA
Understood.

She sets the handset down.

She does not move for a moment. She is aware of the confirmation she just received — the speed of it, the absence of pushback. They confirmed without routing it up. Which means the account is flagged as the preferred settlement mechanism, which means someone in the network's payment architecture has already categorized her as an operator who will negotiate toward the debt rather than cash. She is not a mystery to them.

She has just confirmed she is not a mystery to them.

She exhales once, through her nose. A small, controlled sound. Then she opens the target file again.

The intelligence review she conducts over the next twenty minutes goes further than standard assignment prep. She is not just establishing a pursuit profile — she is reading Nadia Vale the way you read a person you need to understand rather than simply locate. The improvised-tactic notation. The movement patterns that suggest training in disruption protocols. The damage register that says she has been in sustained engagement and has not broken.

There is a line in the associates section that she reads twice: CONTACT NETWORK — COMPROMISED. All primary channels under surveillance. Subject identified as attempting external contact.

Attempting.

Zara notes this. Subject has not yet reached anyone. She is isolated and she knows she is isolated and she is still moving.

Zara understands this condition with a specificity that the assignment packet cannot account for.

She begins organizing her kit. The photograph is in the kit — passport-sized, tucked behind the cipher card in the secondary pocket, exactly where it was in SC0031. A teenage girl. She has not moved the photograph to a safer location because there is no safer location and because moving it would be an admission of something she is not prepared to admit.

She looks at the photograph.

Three seconds. She gives it three seconds.

Then she opens the pursuit section of the target file and begins.

She has seventy-two hours and a name she has heard before and a threat assessment that says: expect cost.

She is the cost.


INT. ROMAN'S OPERATIONAL OFFICE — HIGH FLOOR — NIGHT

A room that is not a room so much as a position. Floor-to-ceiling glass on the city side. ROMAN VALE stands at the window with his back to the room, which is not a concession — it means he has decided the window is the more interesting view than whoever is behind him.

DIMITRI KOSS sits at the table with a slim folder open in front of him and reads from it with the posture of a man who has rehearsed this delivery and is executing it now with professional precision.

DIMITRI
The exposure model runs through seventy-two hours at an acceptable yield — institutional monitoring at current levels, containment probability above threshold. Past that window the curve compounds. At ninety-six hours we are looking at a seventeen-percent increase in secondary-channel exposure — media adjacency, regulatory trigger probability, the Halverson audit that is already running. At one hundred and twenty hours we breach the containment threshold. The recommendation is to compress the operational window: accept reduced outcome yield, close cleanly before the curve inflects.

He closes the folder.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
The numbers are modeled off the current operational footprint. They don't account for escalation.

Roman does not turn from the window.

A long beat. The city below is a grid of light that does not require his attention, and he is giving it his attention anyway, which means he is not giving it his attention.

Then he turns.

ROMAN
Walk me through the yield reduction.

DIMITRI
Twelve to eighteen percent on the primary outcome. Higher on demonstration value — the compressed timeline removes the public-facing elements. The event closes as a private transaction rather than a—

ROMAN
A demonstration.

DIMITRI
Yes.

Roman moves from the window to the table. He does not sit. He reads the top page of the folder for a moment, then sets it down and pushes it back toward Dimitri with two fingers — not dismissive, precise.

ROMAN
Understand — the exposure curve is correct. I'm not arguing the numbers.

DIMITRI
The numbers are conservative.

ROMAN
I know they're conservative. The question is what the operation is for.

Dimitri holds this without speaking.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
A private transaction closes a file. That is not what this is. The people who need to understand the cost of this situation need to understand it in a way that cannot be summarized or reframed. That requires the demonstration. Compressing the timeline eliminates the demonstration.

He moves back toward the window.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The exposure risk is a variable, not a ceiling. We have managed seventeen-percent exposure increases before. Adjust the containment protocols to the extended window and bring me the revised model in the morning.

A beat.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
Understand — the timeline does not compress.

Dimitri holds for a moment that is exactly as long as the situation requires. Then:

DIMITRI
Understood. I'll adjust the containment protocols to the extended window.

Roman has already returned his attention to the city.

Dimitri closes the folder. He sets it to the side. He reaches into his jacket and removes a slim book — narrow, dark, the kind used for field notation — and opens it to a page that is already partially filled.

He writes.

We cannot see what he writes. We see the act: the date — the time — a pause in which he appears to consider something — then several lines, unhurried, in a hand that has clearly filled many pages of similar books. He is not recording this for the operation. He is recording this for a reckoning he has not yet specified.

He closes the book.

He replaces it in his jacket.

He picks up the folder and walks to the door.

DIMITRI
Good night.

Roman does not respond. He is looking at the city, which is organized below him in a way that confirms everything he believes about the relationship between position and perspective.

The door closes.

The room returns to the sound of a city that does not know whose window it is being seen from.


INT./EXT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — DECOMMISSIONED CHEMICAL TRANSIT DEPOT — NIGHT

The depot has been closed for eleven years. It was built to manage the transfer of industrial solvents between the rail freight line and the processing complex to the east, and when the processing complex closed the depot became what all such structures become: a long sequence of rust and residual hazard, marked at intervals with warning placards that nobody reads because nobody comes here.

NADIA has been moving through it for six minutes.

She knows she has company.

PIOTR GANZ moves through the lower tier of the pipe gallery with the unhurried precision of someone who has done this in worse conditions and does not need to rush because rushing is a tactic for people who might lose. He does not believe he will lose. The tracker relay on his wrist tells him she is forty-two meters ahead and moving north through the elevated section. He adjusts his approach accordingly.

The elevated section narrows to a single-file gallery at a junction of three converging pipe runs — she identified this when she entered. Single-file means his equipment advantage doesn't help him. She has thirty seconds to use this before he recalibrates.

She moves.

The junction is darker than the approach and smells of xylene residue — she registered the warning placard three meters back, the specific orange diamond with the vapor-hazard symbol, and noted it as usable. She does not need protection from residual xylene at this concentration. He will not know this. He will hesitate.

He does not hesitate.

He passes through the junction without breaking stride.

Twelve seconds.

She has been revising her model of him since contact. He is not improvising; he has operated in hazardous industrial environments before and he knows residue-level exposure is not immediate. He is working from training, not caution.

She reaches the pressure-relief valve on the main solvent run — a manual release, a large red wheel, corroded but operational. She has been moving toward this for three minutes. A forced release will produce a fog burst: pressurized vapor, non-toxic at this phase in the decommission cycle, but dense enough to reduce visibility to two meters for thirty to forty-five seconds.

She cranks the wheel.

The burst comes with a sound like a held breath releasing — a sustained hiss — and the fog rolls through the gallery in both directions.

She moves left. Away from the sound. Through the fog.

She hears him stop.

Then she hears him keep coming.

He is using the tracker relay. The fog does not matter to the relay. She has bought herself the time it takes him to cover twenty meters blind — perhaps fifteen seconds — and in those fifteen seconds she needs to reach the maintenance hatch at the gallery's north end and descend before the tracker locks her position accurately enough to close.

She runs.

Her ribs protest the running in a way that is no longer protest and more accurately described as structural notification: the fracture is responding to the lateral compression of her stride. She registers this as data — right lateral, worse than yesterday, running is borrowing against tomorrow — and keeps running.

The hatch is open. It was not open when she entered. She does not stop to consider what this means. She descends.

Lower tier. Drainage channels. Concrete floor, standing water at the edges, another pipe run along the south wall. She is now below and behind him.

She hears him descend after her. Thirty seconds behind. The fog has cleared from the upper gallery; the relay is sharp again.

She has no more prepared terrain.

She has the drainage channel, the pipe run, and the south wall, which ends in a dead-end bay that was used for chemical drum storage. She can see it from here. Forty meters. She calculates the time it will take him to close that forty meters after he reaches the lower tier.

She runs anyway, because the alternative is here.

She reaches the bay. It is what she knew it would be: a wall. Old drum cradles. Two HALO units mounted high on the south wall, their camera arrays rotating. The bay is a broadcast location. He will be careful here. Careful is not the same as slow.

She turns to face the entrance.

He appears at the far end of the drainage channel, fifty meters back, and walks toward her without hurrying.

PIOTR GANZ
Ms. Vale.

He does not raise his voice. The depot carries sound efficiently.

PIOTR GANZ (CONT'D)
There are two exits from the drainage level. Neither is behind you. I'd like you to consider the one on your left.

She does not look left. She already knows the left exit is a gated intake shaft that requires a key she does not have. He knows she knows this. The offer is not about the exit.

She inventories.

Her right side: the rib. Load-bearing on that side is unreliable. She cannot take a direct impact to the right torso and keep standing. Left side: functional. Forearm: she cut it on the sheared edge of the pipe run descent, she can feel the blood on her sleeve, she has not assessed the depth yet. The cut is a problem for later. Her hands are both operational. Her legs are her best asset.

He is thirty meters away.

Twenty.

She does not move. She is reading him — the way she was trained to read bodies, the way she read cadavers in her medic rotation before she read living patients: where the weight is distributed, where the skeletal structure commits to a direction before the surface gives it away. He is right-weight dominant. His gear is rear-heavy. When he closes to grapple range, his first move will be to his left.

Fifteen meters.

She moves right.

Not away — toward the drum cradles, and past them, using the cradle rail as a fulcrum to change her direction and come behind his right shoulder. It works for two seconds. His counter-rotation is fast. He catches her left forearm as she clears the rail and the grip is not a hold — it is a bar, a bar of force that pins the forearm against the cradle edge, and she hears the sound before she feels it: the shear of the pipe's corroded edge opening the skin of her forearm from elbow to mid-radius.

She uses his weight against itself — pivots into him, not away, forcing his grip to either hold and spin or release. He releases. She is past him. She has six meters.

The rib goes.

Not catastrophically — she does not go down. But the torque of the pivot has done what the running was doing incrementally: the fracture has displaced. She knows this because her right side has stopped being a resource and started being a liability. She can breathe. She cannot absorb impact on that side and remain standing.

She reaches the wall anyway.

The dead end.

He stands between her and the drainage channel. He has the restraint system ready. He is twelve meters away and not moving because he does not need to move. She has the wall behind her and her right side compromised and her forearm bleeding and six seconds before he decides she is done running.

He begins to close.

She presses her fingertips to her wrist — a brief, automatic gesture, checking the pulse: it is fast and functional. She is not done yet. She does not know what she is going to do.

Then, from somewhere in the lower depot — not close, but not far — a sound that is wrong for the space. Not the settling of old metal. Not the drip of standing water. Something that has intention in it. Movement with a direction.

Piotr Ganz stops.

He does not look away from her. But he stops. His head angles fractionally — listening — and she can see in the way his weight redistributes that he has just added a variable he did not have.

She watches him listen.

The sound comes again. Closer.

He looks.

The scene holds on her face — exhausted, bleeding, ribs broken, watching the entrance to the drum bay for whatever is coming — and the sounds of the depot in the dark, and whatever is moving through it toward them.


INT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — CHEMICAL TRANSIT DEPOT, DRUM STORAGE BAY — NIGHT (CONTINUOUS)

ZARA OKONKWO comes through the bay entrance at the pace of someone who has already made her decision and is now executing it. She does not run. She does not hesitate in the doorway.

She sees: Piotr Ganz, twelve meters from the target, closing. The target at the wall. The two HALO units on the south wall, camera arrays rotating.

She places herself between Piotr and the HALO sightline — not blocking it, entering it — and speaks at operational volume. The HALO units catch everything.

ZARA
Ganz.

He stops.

ZARA (CONT'D)
This corridor was in my advance filing. You deployed after confirmation.

A beat. Piotr does not turn to look at her immediately. He is assessing the situation: another hunter, a priority claim, a broadcast in progress.

PIOTR GANZ
(without turning)
Your filing covers the transit zone. Not the depot interior.

ZARA
The depot is contiguous with the transit zone on the grid. That's a zone boundary dispute, not a filing conflict. I take zone boundary disputes to the protocol committee.

Now he turns. He looks at her with the patience of someone who has all the time his targets do not.

PIOTR GANZ
You filed at fourteen-hundred. I confirmed deployment at fourteen-twelve.

ZARA
Confirmation sequence doesn't supersede advance zone coverage. That's protocol seven, section four.

PIOTR GANZ
Section four covers exterior perimeter, not interior structure.

ZARA
The depot has no designated interior designation on the current operational grid. Absent designation, the exterior filing holds.

She is not looking at the target. She is not going to look at the target.

NADIA, at the wall, watches two professional killers argue about paperwork. She does not understand what she is looking at. She understands, without reasoning it through, that this is a window. She catalogs what she has: forearm bleeding, right side compromised, the bay entrance is twelve meters to her left, the argument is consuming both of them.

She moves left.

Not fast — controlled, lateral, using the drum cradles as cover. One step. Two. The argument continues at the same volume.

PIOTR GANZ
(to Zara, not turning)
You are disrupting an active capture within my confirmation window. That is a pack-coordination violation.

ZARA
You're making that argument on a disputed zone. I'd document my side of that very carefully before filing it.

Three steps. Nadia is at the edge of the cradle line. The bay entrance is six meters.

PIOTR GANZ
The timestamp will resolve this.

ZARA
Let it resolve it. I'm not moving until it does.

She shifts two steps to her left. It is a positional move in the argument — she is angling toward Piotr to make her claim more physically present. She is not looking at the drainage channel. She is not looking at the bay entrance. She is not looking at Nadia.

The sightline between Piotr and the bay entrance is clear. Nadia takes it.

She does not run — running is noise, running draws the eye. She moves at the pace of someone who is managing a body that has a displaced rib and a bleeding forearm and has decided these are operational parameters, not stopping conditions. She reaches the bay entrance. She goes through it.

She does not look back.

Piotr hears the difference in the space — the depot's acoustic character changes fractionally when someone exits the bay. He registers it.

PIOTR GANZ
(flat)
She's gone.

ZARA
I see that.

A pause that is not comfortable.

PIOTR GANZ
You moved.

ZARA
I moved toward you. To make a point about the filing.

He looks at her for a moment with the patience of someone who has just processed a situation and reached a conclusion he will not state aloud.

PIOTR GANZ
The timestamp will not support your zone-coverage argument.

ZARA
Then I'll file the dispute and find out.

She says it with the professional certainty of someone who has made calculations and is prepared to stand behind them. She is not going to look toward the bay entrance. She is not going to look toward the drainage channel. She is going to hold this space and this argument until it has been argued long enough to be finished.

PIOTR GANZ
Protocol seven, section four, subsection two. Interior structures require a separate designation filing.

ZARA
I'll check my documentation.

A beat.

PIOTR GANZ
Good night.

He turns and walks toward the drainage channel. He does not run either. He moves at the pace of a man who understands that running after a target who has a head start in a depot he knows better than you do is not efficient, and efficiency is the only value he maintains.

Zara watches him go.

The two HALO units on the south wall complete their rotation cycles and begin again.

She stands in the drum storage bay for another twelve seconds. Then she turns and walks to the bay entrance. She goes in the opposite direction from either of them.


She does not know if she made the right decision. She knows what she did.

On the south wall, the HALO units record an empty bay.


INT./EXT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — STORM DRAINAGE CULVERT, UNDER TRANSIT ROAD — NIGHT

The culvert is two meters wide and smells of old concrete and standing water. NADIA moves through it at a controlled pace — not running. She is past running. She is in the phase that comes after running, which is the phase where you assess what you still have.

She stops. She needs thirty seconds.

She sits with her back against the culvert wall, forearm pressed to her side. Takes inventory: the forearm laceration has slowed — pressure from movement. The rib is not broken, displaced, possibly cracked, operational. She has been moving on it for forty minutes. She can keep moving on it.

Thirty seconds.

She replays the drum bay. This is what she does when she needs to understand something: she replays it in sequence, clinically, without interpretation first.

A hunter appeared. ZARA OKONKWO — she knows the name from the ORACLE PRIME dossier The Herald had displayed in SC0040. Zara entered the bay. She claimed prior zone-coverage on the depot corridor. She argued it. She did not look at Nadia. She made a positional move that cleared the sightline to the bay entrance. Nadia went through the bay entrance. Zara did not pursue.

That is the event sequence. That is all she can certify.

Now the interpretations.

ONE: genuine dispute. Zara filed an advance claim. Piotr Ganz deployed into her zone. She enforced her filing rights, not because she was protecting Nadia, but because that is how the hunter pool works and Zara enforces her filings. The escape is incidental — a consequence of the dispute, not a goal.

TWO: trap. The intervention was designed to make Nadia feel that she has a potential ally in the field. She is now moving with a lower threat assessment on Zara than she should have, and that miscalibration is the product. Zara is somewhere behind her, waiting for Nadia to act on the false sense of security.

THREE: Roman's design. Roman instructed Zara to create the impression of a defection — a honey positioning, to make Nadia reachable through a false ally. More sophisticated than trap. More expensive to maintain. Not impossible.

FOUR: genuine defection. Zara has reasons of her own — Nadia does not know them — and used the dispute framing as cover because the broadcast was running. She chose Nadia over the capture. She will make contact when it is safe to do so.

FIVE: operational error. Zara misjudged her positional move and accidentally cleared the sightline.

She eliminates five.

Zara's move was two steps, lateral, calculated to the centimeter. It covered the exact angle Piotr had been occupying. She had been in the bay for less than ninety seconds when she made it. You do not make that move by accident. You make that move because you have assessed the geometry of the space and you know what it will do.

Four explanations remain. Including trap. Including Roman's design.

She tries to find the angle at which trap does not fit.

The problem is: every detail that makes the intervention look like a defection also makes it look like a well-executed trap. Zara did not look at her. A genuine defector might not look at her either — to avoid drawing Piotr's attention to the window. Zara moved in a way that created a gap. A trap operative would do exactly the same thing. Zara did not pursue after she was gone. A genuine defector would not pursue. A trap operative, having successfully placed the belief in Nadia's model, would also not pursue — there would be no need to.

She cannot find the angle. Trap fits every observable.

She holds this for a moment in the dark of the culvert. The water at the base of the channel is cold and she can feel it through her boot.

She is not going to resolve this. She does not have enough data to resolve this, and waiting for more data before she moves is not an available option. She has to move.

What she can do is hold both hypotheses — trap/not-trap — and file the anomaly without closing it. Let it stay open. Let it be expensive. Pay the cost of carrying it.

Nadia adds a new entry to her threat model. The entry has no parallel in her existing categories: Hostile. Neutral. Resource. This one does not fit any of those.

She calls it OPEN.

The OPEN entry contains: Zara Okonkwo. One confirmed fact. No confirmed explanation. Trap flag: active. Discard flag: inactive.

She does not know what to do with this entry yet. She knows she is not going to delete it.

Nadia stands up. Forearm still pressed to her side. She looks at the culvert exit — the opening is fifty meters ahead, a circle of less-dark sky. The transit road above her carries no traffic at this hour. She is outside the broadcast grid.

She moves.

The weight in her model is different now. It has more in it. One more thing she is carrying that she cannot put down.

She moves anyway.


EXT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — FREIGHT TRANSFER DEPOT, OUTER GATE — PRE-DAWN

LOTTI is not surprised to see her. That is the thing about LOTTI: she operates in the category of people who are not surprised by logistics clients appearing at irregular hours with injuries they don't explain. She looks at Nadia the way you look at a shipment that arrived slightly damaged — workable, but noted.

LOTTI
You're late.

NADIA
I was delayed.

LOTTI
Mm.

She does not ask about the forearm. She is already moving toward the depot gate, and the expectation is that Nadia will follow. Nadia follows.

LOTTI
I have a pick-up. Twenty minutes. You stay out of the way.

NADIA
Fine.

INT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — FREIGHT TRANSFER DEPOT, MAIN FLOOR — CONTINUOUS

The depot is a low industrial shed, fifty meters long. Freight crates along the south wall. A dispatcher's office — DRUNE — window facing the main floor, frosted glass, the silhouette of a man at a desk. He looks up when they enter. Looks at LOTTI. Looks at Nadia. Looks at LOTTI again.

Drune files that.

LOTTI moves toward the freight marshal's station at the north end. She has done this before; she knows where things are. Nadia stays near the crates, out of Drune's direct sightline.

LOTTI
(to freight marshal)
I'm here for the Vandermeer consignment. Unit seven.

FREIGHT MARSHAL
It's been held for re-inspection.

LOTTI
It was inspected Thursday.

FREIGHT MARSHAL
Thursday's inspector had questions.

LOTTI
Thursday's inspector always has questions. The answers are the same as last time.

The argument begins. It will take the shape of arguments in freight depots everywhere: two professionals each asserting a procedural position neither intends to yield, until one of them does. Drune watches through his frosted window. Both of them are occupied.

INT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — FREIGHT TRANSFER DEPOT, MARSHAL'S ANTEROOM — CONTINUOUS

The anteroom door is unmarked. It opens without a key. Nadia is inside in three steps.

She counts from the doorway. Third pipe manifold from the left, lower coupling joint, between the housing and the wall — a gap of four centimeters. She has to angle her fingers to reach it.

It is there. Exactly there.

A waterproofed envelope, thin, the kind that does not crinkle under pressure. She pulls it out.

INT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — FREIGHT TRANSFER DEPOT, MAIN FLOOR — MOMENTS LATER

She is back at the crates before the freight marshal has finished registering his second objection. Drune is still at his window, watching the argument. He glances toward the crates. Nadia is leaning against a support post, examining nothing.

He looks away.

Nadia does not open the envelope here.

INT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — FREIGHT TRANSFER DEPOT, MARSHAL'S ANTEROOM — MOMENTS LATER

She does not open it here, either.

She waits until LOTTI and the freight marshal have moved to the loading bay — their argument resolved in LOTTI's favor, as these arguments apparently always are — and Drune has followed to the bay window to observe the loading.

She opens it in the doorway of the anteroom, angled away from the bay window.

A card. Index card size. The handwriting is precise, compact, left-margin-aligned.

MERIN — Quay District, Unit 14-B.
OTTO.
Five digits: 7-3-1-1-4.
Below that, in smaller letters: I like redundancies. Go.

She reads it twice. She puts the card in her inside pocket, against her ribs. Closes the envelope. Returns the envelope to the cache.

She does not stand there.

EXT. ZORAL CORRIDOR — FREIGHT TRANSFER DEPOT, OUTER GATE — MINUTES LATER

LOTTI emerges from the loading bay with a receipt in her hand. She finds Nadia at the gate.

LOTTI
Done.

NADIA
Thank you.

A beat. LOTTI looks at her the way she looked at her at the start — workable, but noted.

LOTTI
You're not coming back this way.

It is not a question.

NADIA
No.

LOTTI
All right.

She goes. NADIA watches her for a moment. LOTTI does not look back.

Drune is still at his bay window. He watched LOTTI load. He watched the second figure — female, quiet, stayed near the door — leave with her. He will write this down.

He probably already has.

Nadia turns toward the east road. MERIN is four hours by the freight rail, which she will not take, or six on foot through the corridor access roads, which is what she has.

She moves.


INT. MERIN — QUAY DISTRICT, UNIT 14-B — MORNING

The unit is a converted freight bay: low concrete ceiling, one high window facing the quay, light that smells like salt and diesel. Crates against the west wall. A folding table. A camp stove that has not been used today.

OTTO is already there when NADIA arrives. He is sixty, or seventy, or the particular age that people who have spent their lives in operational work look when you meet them for the first time — which is: all of it, at once. He does not offer his hand.

OTTO
He said you'd come.

He produces the phone from a locked case beneath the table. A handset — industrial-grade, no manufacturer markings. He sets it on the table between them.

OTTO (CONT'D)
He said you'd know the code.

She does.

He moves to the far end of the room. He turns his back. He looks out the high window at the grey water. This is the only thing he has left to give her, and he gives it without being asked.

NADIA enters the access code: 7-3-1-1-4. The phone activates. A single audio file. No label.

She presses play.

A beat of ambient noise — wherever he recorded it, there was wind. Then:

MARCUS (V.O.)
If you're hearing this, then things went the way I was afraid they'd go. I'm sorry. I wanted more time.

She does not stop the message.

MARCUS (V.O.) (CONT'D)
The phone has an encrypted partition — secondary code is the date we met, reversed. In the partition: everything I had on Roman. Network structure, financial infrastructure, the broadcast system, the names. It's complete. I spent two years on it.

She knew something was wrong in the last weeks before he died. She read it as guilt — the particular attentiveness of a man preparing to confess. It was not that. It was this.

MARCUS (V.O.) (CONT'D)
I kept it from you. I told myself it was safer for you not to know. That was wrong. I know that now. I thought the distance would protect you. It didn't protect either of us.

She keeps listening.

MARCUS (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Roman has done this before. There's documentation in the package. All of them. You need to know that.

She does not know yet what that means. She will know in the next hour.

MARCUS (V.O.) (CONT'D)
In the package — look for the broadcast architecture file. There's a maintenance access layer in the ORACLE PRIME infrastructure. That's what stops it. Not Roman. The broadcast. Find that file.

She is listening to a dead man tell her how to fight. She is listening because it is the only way left to be with him.

MARCUS (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Karev.

One word. Her maiden name. His private anchor for her.

She holds it.

MARCUS (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Take Jin home.

The message ends.

The ambient noise cuts. Silence.

OTTO has not moved from the window. He stays there.

NADIA looks at the phone in her hand. She does not put it down.

She does the thing she has always done when she needs to stay functional: she catalogs. She missed the signal — the attentiveness, the preparation she read wrong. She did not know. Not knowing means she did not have the last honest conversation with him. She will carry that. It is hers now; she does not know what else to do with it.

She enters the secondary code — the date reversed. The partition opens.

The documentation package is large. She starts at the broadcast architecture file.

She reads for six minutes.

When she looks up, the quality of the light through the high window has shifted. Later morning. The quay is starting to move.

OTTO
There's a train east at fourteen hundred.

NADIA
I need the room until then.

He nods.

OTTO
He was a careful man.

He says it not as comfort. He says it as a fact he has been holding, and he has now given it to someone who needed to have it.

NADIA
Yes.

She goes back to the documentation.


INT. MERIN — QUAY DISTRICT, UNIT 14-B — MORNING

The message has ended. The phone is still in her hands.

OTTO has not moved from the far end of the room. He is looking at the quay. He gives no indication that time is passing.

NADIA opens the documentation partition. She works in order.

The broadcast architecture file is first. It loads as a schematic — infrastructure map, node tree, relay architecture. She spends four minutes in it. The maintenance access layer is not buried; Marcus flagged it directly. She reads the specification twice: what it requires is a physical access point at one of three relay installations, a twelve-digit authentication sequence, and a two-minute window without broadcast interruption. She does not have the sequence. She understands now what getting it would mean.

She notes the three relay installations by location.

The network structure file is next. She reads it the way she reads terrain — top-down first, then detail. Roman's operation has four functional tiers: event management, financial routing, enforcement, and audience infrastructure. Each tier has its own personnel layer. The scale is larger than Marcus communicated in the message; either he was conservative, or the network grew in the time between assembly and delivery.

She notes the names she recognizes. There are not many.

ORACLE PRIME's operational history: six years of formal events, three years of informal precursors before the infrastructure was stable. The platform's current form is the fourth version. The earlier versions were smaller, dirtier, more exposed. This version is engineered for longevity.

Marcus flagged the financial infrastructure section as the weakest link in the documentation — he had structure but not account specifics. He noted a gap: DIMITRI's operational ledger. He had confirmed its existence and could not get to its contents. He flagged it as the single item he would pursue next.

She marks it as an open thread.

She has been putting off the last file. She opens it.

The previous hunt victims. The file is clean — not assembled for her; assembled because Roman documents everything. Fourteen subjects across six events. Names, dates, entry point, event duration, final confirmed status. Every entry ends the same way.

She reads to the end of the list.

She reads it again.

Directly after the victim records: the acquisitions log. Roman's collection. Each event subject represented by a single catalogued item — an object retrieved from the final location, photographed, stored. The log has the same clean structure as the victim records. Fourteen entries. Fourteen trophies.

She holds this.

The machine has a perfect record. She is the fifteenth subject. She is reading her projected outcome, and there is no version of this documentation in which anyone survived long enough to read what she is reading now.

She stays with it for as long as she can afford to.

Then she goes back to the broadcast architecture file.

The maintenance access layer. The three relay installations. The twelve-digit authentication sequence she does not yet have. She reads the specification a third time — not for new information, but because the thing she is looking at is the thing that stops it, and she needs to know its shape precisely.

OTTO has not moved. The light through the high window is fuller now. Late morning. The quay has been active for a while.

She closes the partition.

She looks at the phone in her hand. Then she sets it down on the folding table.

She is not the same person who picked it up.


INT. MERIN — QUAY DISTRICT, UNIT 14-B — LATE MORNING

The documentation is closed. The partition is locked.

She has everything Marcus could give her. She doesn't have a route in.

NADIA
Was there anyone else Marcus trusted inside the network?

OTTO does not answer immediately. He has been at the window the entire time. He turns now — not toward her, toward a point somewhere between her and the door.

OTTO
One.

NADIA
Name.

OTTO
Tobias Orell. He runs a practice off the MERIN freight grid. Underground. Marcus used him twice. They knew each other — not just operational. More than that.

She processes this. The name is not unknown to her.

OTTO (CONT'D)
I don't know if he'll pick up. The channel goes through three relays. If he thinks the call is compromised he'll drop it without answering.

He crosses to the equipment — a small signal unit mounted under the table, institutional-grey, the kind that is not sold. He pulls a frequency card from a locked case, sets it in front of her.

OTTO (CONT'D)
His node is the third relay. Don't call from your own line. Use this.

She picks up the card. Studies it for three seconds. Then she sits at the table and dials the relay chain.

A delay. The kind that is not latency but distance — three relays routing through points that do not appear on any carrier map.

OTTO moves to the far end of the room again. She is alone in the call.

A click. Then silence that is not dead — it is monitored.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
— Go ahead.

Not a greeting. An instruction.

NADIA
Tobias. I came through OTTO. I was connected to Marcus Chen.

A pause. She can hear him deciding.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
I know who you are.

Of course he does. The game has been live for days.

NADIA
I'm not asking you for anything that puts you in the event. One question. Specific.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
You understand there's a cost to this.

NADIA
I understand.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
Ask.

NADIA
Roman's enforcement assets in MERIN — local staging. Physical location. Fixed or rotating.

Another pause. This one is longer. She can hear him running the calculation — what he knows, what it costs to say it, who is listening to this relay that he thinks he controls but cannot be certain he controls.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
Fixed. Freight zone — Unit 7-Echo. I've seen the same vehicles serviced there three times in fourteen days. Same crew, same schedule window. Early morning.

NADIA
That's all I needed.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
Then we're done.

The line cuts. Not rudely — cleanly, the way someone cuts a call when they know the open time has just passed its limit.

NADIA sets down the relay unit.

OTTO has not moved.

She does not say what she is thinking, which is that she just put Tobias Orell into the sightline of a machine that has a perfect record, and he answered her question anyway. She knew this before she dialed. He knew it before he answered. Neither of them said it.

She writes: 7-E. Three words. Then she folds the note.

OTTO
He was careful too. Marcus. He said Tobias was good people.

She stands.

NADIA
Where is the 7-Echo unit from here?

OTTO
Four kilometers. Freight access road, not public transit.

She nods. She has what she needs and now she has a direction.


INT. MERIN — QUAY DISTRICT, UNIT 14-B — LATE MORNING

She is standing, checking the note she wrote — 7-E — against what she has in Marcus's documentation. Cross-referencing. Making the single location real.

The signal unit activates.

OTTO looks at it. He does not reach for it. He looks at NADIA.

She picks up.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
There's something you need to know before you go near any of it.

He cut the first call eighteen minutes ago. He called back anyway.

NADIA
Go ahead.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
What you're looking at — ORACLE PRIME — it's not what it looks like from the outside. The broadcast is real. The hunt is real. But the broadcast is also a routing shell. The money that moves through the betting architecture isn't gambling revenue. It's six networks running criminal capital through the event's financial layer. The gambling platform is the surface. Underneath it: a financial routing system.

She is still.

TOBIAS (V.O.) (CONT'D)
I've been treating the enforcement layer's personnel for two years. They talk when they're injured. I've heard enough. It's not a game operation that also moves money. It's a money-moving operation that also runs a game. The game is the cover story.

The scale of what she has been surviving is not what she thought it was. The machine she was prepared to dismantle is the visible surface of something that has six other owners.

She sits down.

She does not speak for a moment. This is not hesitation. This is the accounting that has to happen before anything else.

Then:

NADIA
What is the one thing that stops it?

Not the hunt. The machine.

A pause on the line — brief. He already knows the answer. He is deciding whether to give it.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
The broadcast architecture. The money can't move without it — the broadcast is the routing shell. The financial layer runs through the same infrastructure as the game. Take down the broadcast, the routing collapses. I've heard it more than once from people who would know.

She processes this.

It is the same answer Marcus left in the documentation. The same target. Different source, different method, same answer.

NADIA
Thank you.

TOBIAS (V.O.)
Don't.

The line ends.

OTTO has not moved from the window. The quay is moving outside. The morning is later than it was.

She sets down the relay unit.

The broadcast architecture is not a kill switch for a hunt. It is the kill switch for the financial infrastructure of six criminal organizations. The stakeholders are not limited to Roman. The exposure, the risk, the consequences of success — all of it is proportionally larger than she had calculated.

She knows this. She has the target.

She picks up her note — 7-E — and folds it into her jacket pocket.

OTTO
Train's in ninety minutes.

NADIA
I know.

She moves.


INT. EASTBOUND TRAIN — FORWARD-FACING SEAT — LATE MORNING

Fields moving outside the window. The tracks are smooth here. She has the device open in her lap, Marcus's documentation still scrolling through its sections.

She has been reading for forty minutes.

The section is labeled EVENT HISTORY — ORACLE PRIME. What it contains: a record of every previous iteration of the event. Seven events, spanning seven years. Marcus documented each one. Dates, event designations, duration, subject profile summary, final outcome.

She reads the final outcomes column.

All seven are the same word.

She stops.

She does not look at the window immediately. She stays with the screen for a moment — the kind of stillness that happens before the body catches up with the mind. Then she looks up. The fields are still moving. They have no relation to what she has read; they are simply fields. She looks at them anyway.

Seven events. Seven subjects. The audience data runs alongside the outcome records: ORACLE PRIME's viewership has grown with every event. The machine's perfect record is also its reputation. People return because it always ends the same way. The event's duration varies — some subjects lasted hours, one lasted three days — but the outcome is invariant. The audience has watched seven people die and come back each time with more subscribers.

She is the current broadcast.

She understands this. She has understood it since the beginning in the abstract. The abstract version was something she could work alongside. This version — seven names, seven outcomes, seven audience metrics that each exceeded the previous — this version is something else.

She holds the device without looking at it.

The fields are moving outside. Birch trees now, pale and regular, passing too fast to count. She watches them without watching them.

This is what it is. Seven events, seven deaths, a business that has operated without failure for seven years. She is the eighth subject. There is no outcome record yet for the eighth event because the eighth event is ongoing. She is on a train, which is a kind of forward motion, which is something she chose, which is not nothing.

She does not argue with the statistical reality. She has had enough conversations with herself to know that arguing with a complete record is a form of denial that costs more than it buys. The record is what it is. She holds it.

Then, because this is what she does when she holds something true, she looks at what is actually different.

Marcus's documentation is three hundred and forty pages. The previous subjects received no documentation. She knows this because Marcus's documentation says so — he searched the event history for any subject who had advanced intelligence going into the event. None. They knew they were hunted; none of them knew by what; none of them knew the financial architecture under the broadcast; none of them had a named target.

She has a named target.

Marcus built this for someone who would come after him. He failed; he knew he might fail; he documented anyway, with the precision of someone who understood that the documentation would only matter if its recipient survived long enough to use it. He built a weapon and died before he could deploy it. He left it for whoever came next.

She is whoever came next.

The train passes through a small station without stopping. A platform, empty, gone in three seconds. She watches it disappear.

The previous subjects were not less capable than her. This is important to hold clearly: she should not inflate the variable into something it is not. They were capable, intelligent, fighting. They simply did not have what she has. One variable — not capability, not character, not luck. One structural difference: she knows the target and the mechanism. The broadcast architecture. Destroy it and the routing collapses and Roman's machine loses its financial infrastructure and the event dies.

That is the variable.

The knowledge is not certainty. She writes this down in her head the way she would write it in a brief — as a fact that constrains the claim, not as a limit on the action. Knowing the target does not guarantee reaching it. Reaching it does not guarantee deploying the mechanism. Deploying the mechanism does not guarantee that nothing goes wrong. It is the difference between having a plan with a valid target and having a plan that succeeds. Those are not the same thing.

Seven is still the number. One variable different is still what she has.

She looks at the device again.

Marcus's documentation has a section on Roman's private archive — the record is specific enough to be sourced rather than speculative. Roman preserves items from every event. He has built a private collection, housed at his residence inside the VELTAIN facility, organized by event and date. It is not described as a trophy room in the documentation; it is described as a collection. The distinction is Roman's, not Marcus's. She reads the description twice.

Seven events. Seven additions to the collection. Each one is an outcome, preserved.

She understands that she is looking at the shape of what she will need to enter.

She closes the event history section and returns to where she was: the broadcast architecture files. The relay installation diagrams. UNIT 7-ECHO.

The train moves east.

She keeps reading.


INT. EASTBOUND TRAIN — FORWARD-FACING SEAT — LATE MORNING

She is back in the broadcast architecture section. The relay installation diagrams. She has been here for twelve minutes since she closed the event history.

Then she goes back.

The collection section is still open in a secondary tab — she left it half-read after the archive description caught her. She opens it fully now.

Marcus documented the trophy room in two distinct passes. The first pass is the physical description: location, security classification, access restrictions. She read this in the event history section. The second pass is what she did not read yet: his analysis of the archive's contents.

Marcus categorized the items by type. Physical trophies — correct, one per event, organized chronologically. But the second category is what Marcus flagged: operational documents. Entry agreements from each event. Payment records. And for the broadcast events — a full run of four — broadcast access layer documentation.

She reads this twice.

Roman keeps the broadcast access layer credentials inside the archive. Not in the broadcast infrastructure's network layer. Not offsite in a separate secure facility. Physical. Inside the collection. Marcus wrote this as a finding, not a speculation: sourced from two independent channels, verified against the archive's known access log.

She goes to the next section. Marcus's analysis of the pattern.

The pattern Marcus identified: Roman does not trust digital infrastructure alone for mechanisms he considers irreplaceable. He maintains physical analogs for the keys that matter most. The broadcast access layer credentials are in the archive because, to Roman, the broadcast is the machine — and the machine's key belongs with his trophies. The broadcast is how he wins. The key to the broadcast stays where his wins are kept.

She holds this for a moment.

Then she reads Marcus's working hypothesis. He wrote it as a hypothesis, clearly labeled: the shutdown code for the broadcast architecture — the mechanism identified in the relay installation documentation — almost certainly has a physical analog. Roman's archiving pattern strongly suggests it. If the shutdown code exists in any form that Roman would classify as a key to the machine, it is in the archive.

Marcus did not verify this. He flagged it as unverified. He wrote: *this is the inference the documentation supports; I have not confirmed it; it should be treated as a high-confidence hypothesis rather than a sourced finding.*

She reads the distinction he drew between sourced finding and high-confidence hypothesis. She considers it.

Then she sets it aside. Not because the distinction doesn't matter — it does — but because the alternative is that the shutdown code has no physical analog, which means it exists only inside the broadcast network infrastructure, which means there is no single physical object she can locate and use. The hypothesis is not confirmed. The hypothesis is also the only path that leads to a deployable mechanism. She proceeds on the hypothesis.

The trophy room is the target.

Not one of the relay installations. Not UNIT 7-ECHO, which she is still traveling toward, which still matters, which is still the preliminary access point. But the primary target — the object that ends the machine — is inside Roman's archive inside his private residence at VELTAIN.

She opens a new note on the device. She writes three things:

1. Trophy room — VELTAIN, private residence. Primary objective.
2. Shutdown code — physical analog, archive. Unverified/high-confidence.
3. Relay installations — preliminary. Access layer.

She looks at the list.

The third item is the one she has a path to. She is on a train toward it right now. Items one and two require her to get from the relay installation access layer to the inside of Roman's private residence. The documentation does not tell her how to do that. No section of Marcus's three hundred and forty pages addresses the path from the infrastructure perimeter to the residence interior.

She will need to find that path somewhere else, from someone who knows the facility, under conditions she cannot currently predict.

This is not a gap in the plan. It is the plan's open variable. It is the thing she doesn't have yet and cannot get until she's further inside the situation.

She closes the note. She goes back to the relay installation diagrams.

The train moves east. She keeps reading.


INT. EASTBOUND TRAIN — FORWARD-FACING SEAT — LATE MORNING

She is in the relay installation diagrams. Second hour on the train. The fields outside have given way to low scrubland and then to a stretch of industrial corridor — warehouses, access roads, pale concrete running parallel to the track.

The screen at the far end of the car activates.

It has been carrying the regional travel service feed — route updates, station stops, a weather graphic for the eastern corridor. Now the feed cuts and the ORACLE PRIME signal replaces it. White on black. A tone. Then:

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Good morning. I am speaking to you from the heart of ORACLE PRIME's broadcast infrastructure, and I have news that our most committed audience members have been anticipating.

She does not put down the device. She watches from where she is.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
At this stage of each ORACLE PRIME event, the rules of engagement may be augmented — at the discretion of event management, in response to audience participation metrics, and in service of the experience we have built together over seven extraordinary years. Today, we augment.

SP02. The audience's appetite shaped the machine's operational escalation. The announcement exists because the metrics demanded it.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
First augmentation: Transparency Protocol. Effective immediately, the subject's last confirmed location will be broadcast on all ORACLE PRIME channels at fixed six-hour intervals. Location data will be transmitted directly from our field monitoring network to the broadcast. Our first Transparency Protocol window opens in five hours and fifty-three minutes.

She sets the device face-down in her lap.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Second augmentation: Reserve Activation. If our first Transparency Protocol window confirms the subject is operating within the primary zone of engagement — the corridor between Merin and our eastern facility — our passive hunter reserve will be activated. Three additional participants will enter the field within four hours of confirmation.

The primary zone of engagement. She is in it. She has to be in it. UNIT 7-ECHO is in it. The trophy room is at its eastern end.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Third augmentation: Event Deadline. This event will resolve within seventy-two hours of this announcement. If no resolution has been achieved at the deadline, Event Expiry protocols will activate. Our audience has waited long enough for a conclusion. So have we.

A pause. The Herald's tone shifts — the administrative register giving way to something warmer, more intimate.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
We are grateful, as always, for an audience that cares. Your engagement is the reason this event continues to matter. A brief procedural note before we close: ORACLE PRIME's betting odds are calculated in real time from live field data. Location data is transmitted directly from our monitoring network to broadcast and betting systems. As always, we do not adjust, filter, or delay betting data. What our systems confirm, our audience sees.

She hears this sentence. She hears it as something different from what the audience hears.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Current field status. Subject location: confirmed Merin transit hub. Time of last confirmation: ninety-one minutes prior. Current odds —

She picks up the device.

She checks the time. She has been on this train for ninety-four minutes. The last fixed infrastructure node she passed through was Merin station — she boarded there. Since then: no fixed nodes. Transit corridor.

The system has her at Merin.

The system does not know she is on this train. It cannot know — there are no ORACLE PRIME monitoring nodes on a regional eastbound rail service. The system gathers location from fixed infrastructure: transit hubs, station sensors, registered access points. Between those points, the system is working from its last confirmed data.

She is ninety-four minutes ahead of where the system thinks she is.

The broadcast ends. The regional travel service feed resumes. The fields outside are the same fields; the train is the same train.

She looks at the betting data still visible in the corner of the screen before the regional feed fills it: the odds against her survival are high. The odds are calculated on a subject standing in Merin transit hub, not a subject on a train with three hours until arrival at her first objective.

Two things are true at the same time. The Special Rules are genuinely dangerous. And Roman's tracking system has a blind spot she did not know about until The Herald told her, in a routine disclosure, that the system cannot lie about what it knows.

She cannot use this yet. The Transparency Protocol window opens in under six hours. She needs to be at UNIT 7-ECHO or beyond before it does, in a location with no fixed monitoring infrastructure. She needs to know the monitoring node map for the eastern corridor. She needs to know where the blind spots are.

She opens the relay installation documentation.

The relay installations. The fixed-node infrastructure. Marcus documented the broadcast relay points — and broadcast relay infrastructure and location monitoring infrastructure often share the same physical footprint.

She starts reading with a different question than she had before.


INT. EASTERN JUNCTION STATION — TRANSIT SHELTER — MIDDAY

The train has discharged its passengers and pulled east. She is in the shelter — a concrete overhang, bench, a departure board showing three connections and two cancellations. She is the only person waiting.

The device signals.

The channel identifier is one she does not recognize. She opens the message.

*I know you're in transit. I have information about your son. I want to speak with you. My terms are simple: tell me what you're planning to do with ORACLE PRIME's broadcast infrastructure. I will tell you everything I know. — Z.O.*

She sits with this for a moment.

Then she opens the channel.

ZARA (V.O.)
My terms stand. Tell me your plan for the broadcast infrastructure and I'll give you everything I have about your situation.

NADIA
You go first.

A pause. Then:

ZARA (V.O.)
All right.

She can hear Zara deciding something. Not hesitating — deciding.

ZARA (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Roman's network has a legal instrument on my daughter. Lena Okonkwo. It was manufactured by the network's legal arm two years ago as a condition of my entry into the hunter pool. It's structured as a debt — principal plus a recalculation mechanism that means each payment increases what I owe. It cannot be paid off. I know this now. I didn't know it when I signed. I've been working toward a floor that isn't there.

NADIA
How much do you owe?

ZARA (V.O.)
The number changes every month. That's the point. The number isn't real. What's real is that they own the obligation and they can call it at any time, which means they own Lena's security at any time.

She is quiet for a moment. Two beats.

ZARA (V.O.) (CONT'D)
I'm telling you this because you need to know why I'm in Roman's network, and because it's the truth, and because I think you'll see the difference between the two. I have four hunters in my field cell. I have operational clearance inside the VELTAIN corridor. I have seen documentation inside Roman's logistics layer.

She pauses here.

ZARA (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Your son. There's a reference in the supply chain routing — facility designation VELTAIN-7, eastern residential block. I don't have a room number or a level. I have the routing reference and a supply log entry from eleven days ago. He was alive and in that facility eleven days ago. That's what I have.

The departure board clicks over. A connection changes times.

Nadia looks at the board for a moment without reading it.

NADIA
Why are you giving me that before I've agreed to anything?

ZARA (V.O.)
Because I said I'd tell you everything I know. That's part of everything I know. My terms are still my terms.

NADIA
What do you actually want from this?

ZARA (V.O.)
I want the machine gone. The debt instrument dies with the network. Lena gets her life back. That's what I want. You're the best chance of that happening that I've seen in two years.

Silence. Not uncomfortable — the kind that happens when something true has been said and both parties know it.

Then:

NADIA
What does Lena think about what you do?

A longer pause.

ZARA (V.O.)
She doesn't —

The sentence does not finish.

Another pause.

ZARA (V.O.) (CONT'D)
She knows I work security. She doesn't know the details. She doesn't —

She stops again.

NADIA
All right.

ZARA (V.O.)
That's not a clean answer.

NADIA
I know.

She is not pressing her. She is not using it. She asked because it was the honest question and now she is letting it be what it is.

ZARA (V.O.)
Your turn. The broadcast infrastructure.

NADIA
I need to reach VELTAIN. I need access to the facility's residential archive. And I need the broadcast relay network to go dark in a coordinated window. That's the plan.

A pause. She can hear Zara processing this.

ZARA (V.O.)
That's either very good or insane.

NADIA
Probably both.

ZARA (V.O.)
I can get you inside the VELTAIN corridor. I have a route that avoids the Transparency Protocol monitoring nodes. I'll need twenty-four hours to set it up.

NADIA
You have the node map?

ZARA (V.O.)
I've been working in this corridor for two years.

NADIA
Send me what you have.

ZARA (V.O.)
I'll send it to this channel when it's ready. Don't move on UNIT 7-ECHO until you hear from me.

NADIA
Why not?

ZARA (V.O.)
Because UNIT 7-ECHO has a passive monitoring node adjacent. If you approach it without the route I'm building, you'll trigger the first Transparency Protocol window early. You'll be visible before the six hours are up.

She considers this.

NADIA
I'll wait. Twenty-four hours.

ZARA (V.O.)
I'll be faster than that.

The line closes.

She sits in the shelter. The departure board shows one more connection, then goes blank on the eastern route.

She has just spoken with a hunter from Roman's network who told her the truth about her daughter and the location of her son.

She does not know yet whether this ends well for either of them.

She opens Marcus's relay documentation and goes back to the node map.


INT. EASTERN JUNCTION — STATION CAFÉ — MIDDAY

A small room. Four tables. A counter with coffee equipment. The person behind the counter has gone somewhere. She is alone.

She has coffee in front of her. She has not touched it.

The device is open. She has been looking at the same set of documents for eleven minutes, not reading — accounting.

What she has:

UNIT 7-ECHO. Location confirmed. Marcus's relay installation documentation. The broadcast architecture of ORACLE PRIME mapped in sufficient detail to know what breaking it does.

The trophy room. VELTAIN private residence. Roman's archive. Operational — not symbolic. Broadcast access layer credentials inside. Shutdown code: physical analog, high-confidence hypothesis, same archive.

Jin. VELTAIN-7, eastern residential block. Alive eleven days ago.

A tracking blind spot that the system does not know she knows about. A Transparency Protocol window that opens in approximately five hours, which means she needs to be invisible in approximately five hours.

Zara. A route incoming. A monitoring node map incoming. A person who has operational clearance inside the VELTAIN corridor and has been working there for two years.

She looks at what she has. It is more than any previous subject had. It is also not a plan yet.

She opens a new document on the device. She writes:

*1. Receive Zara's route and monitoring node map.*
*2. Use the monitoring blind spots to reach VELTAIN before the next Transparency Protocol window.*
*3. Access the VELTAIN facility. [Mechanism: Zara's clearance and operational knowledge. Open variable: exact entry method TBD with Zara.]*
*4. Reach the residential archive. [Hardest target. Open variable: method of entry to private residence interior.]*
*5. Locate the shutdown code physical analog inside the archive.*
*6. Deploy it. [Collapses broadcast routing. ORACLE PRIME loses its financial infrastructure. The event ends.]*
*7. Reach Jin at VELTAIN-7 during the collapse window and extract.*

She looks at the list.

Three of the seven steps have open variables — steps three, four, and seven. Step three has a partial answer (Zara). Step four is the hardest problem and she does not yet have the answer. Step seven depends on step six creating a window.

She considers waiting. Not for long — she knows the argument: wait for more intelligence, close the open variables, don't commit until the path is clear.

The counter-argument is: the Event Deadline is running. It has been running since The Herald's announcement. She has seventy-two hours, less whatever has elapsed. The deadline is not a variable she can close by waiting. Waiting trades open variables for a shorter deadline, which is worse.

There is also this: Roman has hosted seven events. The trophy room has existed since the first one. In seven events, no subject has ever known the trophy room was the target. In seven events, no subject has ever reached it. In seven events, Roman has assumed that the archive is safe because it is inside his private residence and because no subject has ever known to look for it. He trusts the architecture of his own invincibility. He trusts the monument.

She sees this clearly for the first time.

The trophy room is invulnerable to everyone who has ever tried to reach it for the simple reason that no one has ever known to try. The machine's most critical asset is kept in the place Roman believes is safest not because it has been defended against attack but because it has never been a target.

It will be a target.

She has seventy-two hours and a list with three open variables and a person with operational clearance who is building a route.

She looks at the plan on the device. She does not add qualifications. She does not write *provisional* at the top or *pending Zara's confirmation* in the margins. She writes one more line at the bottom:

*This is the plan.*

She leaves it.

The coffee is cold. She drinks it anyway.

She opens the relay installation documentation and goes back to mapping the infrastructure.


INT. VELTAIN — ROMAN'S OPERATIONS CENTER — NIGHT

A long room. Clean surfaces. A display wall running behavioral analytics from the ORACLE PRIME feed. No debris, no personality in the objects. A room that belongs to a man who does not need the room to tell him who he is.

Roman stands at the display. Not reading — he has read it. He is looking at it in the way that follows reading.

The display shows two overlapping movement pattern maps:

EVENT MOVEMENT PROFILE — SC: NADIA VALE
PREVIOUS 96-HOUR WINDOW: Coverage area 4.2km² | Displacement pattern: non-directional | Concealment index: 87% | Risk-exposure tolerance: LOW
CURRENT 18-HOUR WINDOW: Coverage area 31.6km² | Displacement pattern: directional (bearing: NNW) | Concealment index: 44% | Risk-exposure tolerance: ELEVATED
BEHAVIORAL CONFIDENCE: 96% | DESTINATION: UNRESOLVED | TRANSIT CORRIDOR DEGRADATION: ACTIVE

Dimitri is at the far end of the room. He has the same data on a tablet. He brings the summary when Roman does not turn.

DIMITRI
Subject behavioral change confirmed. Pattern shift at
ninety-six percent confidence. Movement is directional —
northnorthwest bearing, consistent across three corridor
transitions. She is not evading. She is going somewhere.

He waits.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
Standard pressure protocol would be logical. Redeploy the
two-hunter sweep, compress the corridor window.

A pause.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
The subject's behavioral profile suggests she has acquired
operational intelligence she should not have. The event has
run fourteen days. The clean option is a managed resolution
with a standard payout structure. I can have a proposal
prepared in forty minutes.

He is advising Roman to end it.

Roman does not answer.

He looks at the behavioral data again — specifically at the eighteen-hour window, the 44% concealment index. She stopped hiding. She is going somewhere and she is going there with a plan and she committed to it while he was not watching.

He does not say this.

ROMAN
Understand — what she's changed is the timeline. Not the
outcome.

He turns from the display.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
Activate the corridor rescue protocol. The pre-positioned
safe route in the NNW corridor. Genuine resources, genuine
geography. Everything she needs for the next operational phase.

DIMITRI
The Linden Junction package.

ROMAN
Position it in her projected path within the next six hours.
She will move toward it because it is genuinely useful. She
has good intelligence — she will check it. Let it hold.

Dimitri makes a note.

DIMITRI
Confirmed.

Nothing more is said about ending the event.

Roman turns back to the display. The behavioral data is still there — the two windows, the shift, the unresolved destination. He looks at the directional vector: NNW, consistent across three transitions.

She is going to VELTAIN.

He has not said this out loud. He does not say it now. He prices it in and moves on.

Dimitri is already working. He does not check his watch.


INT. REGIONAL BUS — FORWARD SECTION — AFTERNOON

She has the forward section to herself. Two other passengers are in the rear. Outside, the corridor is flat and agricultural — harvested fields, low service structures, the occasional relay tower.

She has been on this bus for three hours and forty minutes.

The device alerts.

She looks at it. An intelligence packet from the relay chain — a field contact identifier she does not recognize by code but knows by the routing: Zara's network, operational tier, near-VELTAIN access. She opens it.

The message reads:

STATUS REPORT — FIELD CONTACT V7-ECHO
Confirmed observation window: thirty-six hours prior to transmission.
Location: VELTAIN-7, eastern residential block, unit interior.
Subject: infant male, approximately seven months. Dark hair.
Physical condition: stable. No visible distress.
Distinguishing detail: pale blue medical identification bracelet, right wrist. Hospital-registry format.
Transmission ends.

She reads it once.

Her fingers find her wrist pulse point — brief, involuntary, the inventory gesture — then stop.

She reads it again.

The bracelet. She chose it from a rack in the registration corridor. Pale blue, she remembers, because the green one had a fraying edge and she had asked for a replacement. The administrative clerk had handed her the blue one and she had not thought about it again. The band contains the passive ID chip from the original registration — hospital issue, low-power, short-range. She has not thought about this in months. She thinks about it now.

She does not have the equipment to read the chip. She files the detail.

She opens a second document and writes:

*PL09: Medical bracelet — right wrist, passive ID chip, hospital registry. Equipment needed: short-range scanner, passive-mode reader. Acquire before perimeter approach.*

She closes the second document.

She reads the confirmation a third time. Not to receive new information. To decide whether to believe it.

The field contact identified the bracelet. Manufactured intelligence usually does not include the kind of incidental physical detail that requires actual visual access to an infant in a room. It is not proof. It is a credibility marker. She notes it as such.

She has partial confirmation of Jin's location since Zara's transmission — a reference code and a supply routing number. This is different. This is someone who has been in the building.

Thirty-six hours old. Not live. Possibly compromised since transmission. She knows all of this.

She puts the device away.

The plan was written before this message arrived. She was going to VELTAIN regardless. What the message changes is not the destination — it is the reason she can sustain moving toward it.

She was going to VELTAIN despite not knowing.

She is going to VELTAIN because he is there.

The bus moves through the corridor. Outside, another relay tower. Another field. The light is going yellow at the edges.

She does not look at the device again.


INT. REGIONAL BUS — FORWARD SECTION — LATE AFTERNOON

Ninety minutes from LINDEN JUNCTION. The light through the window is going flat and grey; the corridor outside is industrial now, relay infrastructure along the road margins.

The device alerts.

New message. Third channel — the corridor-operative relay node she has been monitoring since the first week. A broadcast channel used by people in transit between protected regions. She has never sent through it. She has only listened. This channel is also monitored by Roman's network. She has always known that.

The message is addressed to her by the code name she used in the first seven days of the event, before she stopped using it.

She opens it.

RESCUE ROUTE — LINDEN JUNCTION
Safe location: 14 HAVEL COURT, northern service quarter, third floor, east-facing unit.
Contact phrase: the light's been out since Tuesday.
Supplies confirmed on-site: medical (wound management, antibiotic, suture), clothing (active, size noted), nutrition (72-hour supply), communication hardware (encrypted relay, pre-keyed).
Exit route: northnorthwest from LINDEN JUNCTION — VELTAIN corridor via the SORAL access road, clear to the facility perimeter.
Window: forty-eight hours.

She reads it once. Then she opens the ORACLE PRIME betting feed on a secondary partition of the device.

She has been reading the feed since SC0053 — since The Herald announced the Transparency Protocol and she understood that the odds move when the audience can see her. The Herald cannot fabricate live betting data. It is the one thing the system cannot adjust: when a development is genuine and unexpected, the audience bets in volume and contradiction — a chaotic spike, high variance, before the market finds a new consensus.

The odds are moving.

They are not moving chaotically.

They are moving in a single direction — a smooth, coordinated, large-amplitude shift upward on SUBJECT REACHES VELTAIN — arriving at a new consensus in under forty seconds. Clean. Confident. Pre-priced.

The market was already priced in before she read the message.

She opens a new document. She writes:

*Marker one: timing.*

The route was positioned in her projected corridor, viable within four hours of the behavioral shift Roman read from The Herald's feed. She shifted behavior on the eastbound train. A response was operational at LINDEN JUNCTION, approximately ninety minutes from her current position, by the time she was three hours past eastern junction. Genuine underground rescue — assembled with this supply calibration, this exit route specificity, this resource completeness — takes days. Four hours means whoever built this had her movement profile almost simultaneously with her making it. The only entity with simultaneous access to that profile is Roman's network.

*Marker two: calibration.*

Wound management, not initial treatment. Clothing in her size and activity rating — not a general size, not a supply-chain default. Food in the correct portion volume for someone at her metabolic state after fourteen days of sustained physical stress. This manifest was written for Nadia Vale in the past forty-eight hours. Not for a subject in general. For her, specifically, in her current condition. A genuine rescue assembled at speed uses what is available. This used what was selected.

*Marker three: the odds.*

The ORACLE PRIME audience bets on information. When the rescue route appeared on this channel — a channel Roman's network monitors — and was matched to her code name, the audience's betting behavior should have reflected genuine uncertainty about whether she would accept or recognize the route as a trap. It did not. The audience moved to consensus in forty seconds. The variance was negligible. They were already positioned. The market does not pre-price an organic development. It pre-prices an announced one.

She looks at the three items.

One beat.

Then:

*Decision: proceed toward LINDEN JUNCTION. Use what can be confirmed genuine. Watch for the activation mechanism. Do not stay beyond what acquisition requires.*

The route is controlled. The supplies inside it are real. The exit route from it is real. The trap has been built using genuine materials because a trap built from fake materials is one she would leave immediately. Roman built her a real rescue and put a door at the back of it.

She needs the medical supplies. She needs the communication hardware. She needs the exit route northnorthwest.

She cannot acquire these from any other source before the VELTAIN perimeter. She has checked. There is no alternative chain.

She puts the device away.

Outside: the industrial corridor continues. A relay tower. Another. The bus does not slow.

She is going in.


INT. 14 HAVEL COURT — NORTHERN SERVICE QUARTER, LINDEN JUNCTION — THIRD FLOOR — DUSK

The staircase is empty. The building has the quality of a space that has been recently occupied and recently vacated — functional, institutional, no history on the walls.

Third floor. East-facing unit. The door handle is clean.

She says the contact phrase through the door.

A pause. Then the door opens. A man — fifty, grey, reading glasses in his hand — steps back without speaking. She reads him: low heart rate, no lateral eye movement, the faint calibration of someone who does this regularly. She cannot determine if he is genuine or Roman's. She moves past him.

One scan. West wall: exit, the way she came. East window: fire escape access, two floors down to the alley. North interior: bathroom, one window, opaque. South wall: the supply array.

She begins.

SUPPLY MANIFEST — CONFIRMED ON-SITE

She works against the list in her head. Medical first.

The suture kit is pre-threaded and pre-staged for a penetration wound. Not a general kit. Specific. Someone who knew the wound type built this.

She takes it.

Antibiotic: blister pack, broad-spectrum. She takes it.

Wound dressing: non-adhesive, the correct size for an entry wound rather than an abrasion or a burn. She takes it.

Communication hardware: a relay device, pre-keyed on the east-window side of the supply table. Positioned to transmit passively outward through the glass. She picks it up, turns it face-down, and places it in her bag. If it is transmitting, it is transmitting in a direction she controls now.

Clothing: her size, active rating. She notes the fit without remarking on it. She takes two items.

She checks the bathroom. Second supply set — duplicated. Medical. Same sizes. Same brands.

She stands in the doorway for two seconds.

No genuine rescue operation builds this redundancy. You do not double-stock if you are assembling at speed. You stock what you have. You stock what the subject is likely to need. You stock once. This is a space where the subject was expected to spend time and require a second round.

Three markers: suture kit (wound-specific), relay device (positioned for transmission), supply duplication (designed for extended stay, not rapid extraction).

She already knew. She is confirming.

Seven minutes in the space.

She is repacking the bag when she hears the contact phrase — spoken at the building entrance, one floor below, by a voice she knows before the sentence ends.

She is moving before she decides to move.

Third-floor landing. She positions herself at the top of the staircase. He is coming up.

TOBIAS ORELL appears around the turn of the second-floor stairs — medical bag on one shoulder, moving with the specific unhurried pace of someone who has learned to look unhurried — and stops when he sees her.

A beat.

TOBIAS
This the forward cache, or...

He trails off. He is reading her face. She does not have a face that is easy to read; she has learned that. He reads it anyway.

She says:

NADIA
This place is Roman's. Leave.

Tobias goes still.

He closes his eyes — brief, private, the reset — and opens them.

TOBIAS
What did you take.

NADIA
Medical. Hardware. Two clothing items. Nothing activated as far as I can determine.

TOBIAS
How long were you inside.

NADIA
Seven minutes.

TOBIAS
You think they logged me at the door.

She does not answer because the answer is yes and he knows the answer is yes.

He looks at the bag over her shoulder, then at the door to the unit behind her, then at the staircase he came up. His hands find his medical kit strap and adjust it with precise, unnecessary attention.

TOBIAS
I came in on the ground channel. Same relay you used.

NADIA
Different message.

TOBIAS
Supply cache for a VELTAIN contact. That's what it said. I thought you might—

He stops.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
I thought you might need it. Before the perimeter.

The building is quiet. Whatever is in the walls is quiet too.

She says:

NADIA
We need to move now. Together or separately — your choice. If separately, go north. Not the corridor route.

Tobias picks up his bag, adjusts the strap one more time, and nods.

They are both in the building. The building knows they are both in the building. The warning was real and it arrived thirty seconds after it would have helped.


INT. 14 HAVEL COURT — SAFE HOUSE UNIT — THIRD FLOOR — NIGHT

Tobias has opened his medical kit on the supply table. She is at the east window.

The alley below is empty. A service road runs left, connecting at the junction sixty meters ahead to the Soral access road. She has verified it from here: the geography is real. Someone positioned this safe house with genuine operational intelligence about the northnorthwest route.

That is the thing about a well-built trap. The geography works.

She says:

NADIA
The NNW exit is real. I've confirmed it from the window.

Tobias does not look up from the kit.

TOBIAS
I know.

NADIA
If we leave tonight, we lose the Soral window. There's a transit restriction on the access road between 0400 and 0600. We'd be moving against it in the dark with no forward cover confirmed.

TOBIAS
And the wound.

NADIA
And the wound.

He holds up the suture kit — the pre-threaded, pre-staged, wound-specific version she found on the supply table.

TOBIAS
This is made for a penetration wound. Someone knew.

NADIA
Everyone knows. That's not a reason to leave it here.

She turns from the window. The rationalization has three parts; she has been building it for the last fifteen minutes.

Part one: the exit route is real and verified and timed-out for night movement — which means staying until before 0400 is the operationally correct use of the route, not a concession to the trap.

Part two: the wound. She cannot suture the entry point herself with the precision needed. She has tried. She knows what the attempt costs in time and in wound quality. Tobias can do it in forty minutes. Forty minutes stationary now versus six hours of increasing infection risk on a night movement route with compromised mobility.

Part three: they have been in the building for twenty-three minutes and the trap has not activated. Either the mechanism is on a longer timer, or it requires a specific trigger — departure attempt, communication hardware activation, something she has not yet done — or the operational response to the channel flag has not been dispatched. Twenty-three minutes without activation is not evidence of safety. It is evidence of patience. Roman is patient.

She holds part three in her mind for a moment.

Then:

NADIA
The trap hasn't activated in twenty-three minutes. That's either patience or a delayed mechanism. If it's patience, we have a window. If it's delayed, we may not. I don't know which.

TOBIAS
You're going to stay anyway.

It is not a question.

NADIA
For the suture. And the 0400 window. Nothing else.

TOBIAS
(muttering, already reaching for the instrument)
Entry wound, anterior aspect, some tissue involvement, going to need two layers probably three depending on—

He stops. Recalibrates. Speaks again — to her this time, not himself.

TOBIAS
You know they may have adjusted for two people. Since I came in.

NADIA
I know.

TOBIAS
And you're staying.

NADIA
The decision is borderline.

A beat.

TOBIAS
Sit down.

She moves from the window to the chair. That is the decision.

Tobias works. His technical commentary resumes under his breath — layer count, tissue state, instrument sequence. The cadence of it is slightly faster than it would be in a neutral environment; his diagnostic chatter running at the rate of a man performing competence while afraid, which is not the same as a man who is losing.

She watches the instruments. She does not watch the door.

The route is partially real. That is the trap's architecture and its leverage simultaneously. A fake rescue made of fake geography and fake resources would have been easy to leave. Roman did not build that rescue. He built one that works.

She is using it anyway.

The suture holds.


INT. TRANSIT VEHICLE — OUTER SERVICE DISTRICT, LINDEN JUNCTION — NIGHT

The vehicle is parked in the loading margin off the service road. Engine off. Dark. The windows face north toward the service quarter three blocks away. Zara has been here for forty minutes.

The intelligence package arrived through her hunter-pool access forty minutes ago. She has been reading it since.

The address is real. She has run the building: 14 Havel Court, northern service quarter, operational since the district's last infrastructure cycle, no flag in the public records. The geography is correct. She has verified the Soral access route against her own maps: genuine, passable, the transit restriction timing is accurately stated. The supplies are consistent with a legitimate underground cache. The channel is a real channel — one she has used herself for forward intelligence.

Most of it reads clean.

She reaches the contact phrase.

THE LIGHT'S BEEN OUT SINCE TUESDAY

She stops.

Her hands go still. Her eyes move.

The phrase is documented. Not used — documented. Six months ago, a hunter-pool debrief on a MERIN district capture operation. She was brought in as a contractor; the debrief ran three hours; she sat through the section on channel integrity because it was relevant to her next assignment. The notation was brief: a specific set of phrases had been seeded into the corridor-operative relay network as trap-identifiers. Voluntary entry confirmation. Anyone who used the phrase at a controlled address had confirmed their own presence to the monitoring network. The notation listed three phrases. This was one of them.

She read it once. She retained it because she retains everything that has operational value.

She looks at the phrase in the package.

She looks at the address.

She closes the document.

The connection is complete.

The obstacle is not the geography or the resources or the channel — it is the phrase, and the phrase is readable only if you were in that room six months ago, reading a notation that was filed and never flagged again. Nadia was not in that room. Nadia cannot have spotted this.

She exhales once, through her nose.

Then she opens a new message.

WARNING — LINDEN JUNCTION

Contact phrase compromised: monitored Roman architecture. Address flagged in prior operation. Do not use the phrase. Exit if mobile.

Route via: north alley to Soral junction — genuine geography, but exit before Soral access road. Take the freight corridor east from the service quarter junction instead.

She reads it back. It is specific. It is enough. She sends it toward Nadia's last confirmed relay point.

She does not know that Nadia is already inside.

She does not know about Tobias.

She knows the phrase is compromised, the address is monitored, and the window for a clean exit closes in proportion to how long someone has already been inside.

She picks up the vehicle's secondary communications unit and begins composing a second message — to a different relay, a different destination, flagging the channel itself for her own records. If this channel is seeded, her position as a contractor has been running on compromised infrastructure for some portion of the last six months. She needs to know the scope.

Her hands have not moved from their position on the table. Still, not rigid. The rapid eye movement has slowed.

She has sent the warning. She is already on the next problem.

That is the cost of the decision she just made and the size of the person who made it: she does not sit with what it means to have sent a message that works against the pool she has been contracted to. She does the next thing.

Outside: the service quarter three blocks north, lit against the dark. Somewhere in there, the trap is either closing or it has already closed.

She sends the second message.


INT. 14 HAVEL COURT — SAFE HOUSE UNIT — THIRD FLOOR — PRE-DAWN

Four forty-three in the morning.

The building is quiet. From two rooms away, the faint sound of Tobias — a drawer opening, or the specific silence of a person lying awake and choosing not to move.

She has been here five hours. The suture is holding. The wound is not infected — not yet, not by the fever profile she has been running against her own data. She is alive and stationary and the building has been quiet since they stopped speaking.

This is the closest to safe she has been in days.

She opens the odds feed.

ORACLE PRIME — LIVE MARKET

SUBJECT REACHES VELTAIN: 2.1 — last adjusted 19:47

She checks the time. 04:43.

The odds were last adjusted at 19:47. She entered the building at 23:12. She has been inside for five hours and seventeen minutes. In five hours and seventeen minutes, the ORACLE PRIME betting market has not adjusted once.

She does not move.

The Herald cannot fabricate live betting data. That is the protocol — the single constraint on the broadcast system that Roman cannot override because it is the system's commercial guarantee. If the audience could see her, the odds would move. They always move. She has been watching them move for two weeks; she knows what the feed looks like when the audience has a live sighting. She knows what it looks like when they don't.

It looks like this.

The audience has not seen her since 19:47, which is nine minutes before she arrived at this building.

The building is in a broadcast dead zone.

She sits with this for the length of time it takes to be certain.

An off-broadcast location is not invisible by accident. Camera-blind alleys are invisible by accident — geography, angle, coverage gap. A building in the service quarter of a managed city district, three stories, east-facing windows, four hours of undisturbed occupancy: this building is not invisible by geography. It is invisible by design.

Roman's network does not accidentally remove locations from broadcast coverage. It removes them for a purpose. The purpose is to hold people in places where the audience cannot watch.

The trap is not designed to capture her on-broadcast for the game's entertainment.

It is designed to hold her off-broadcast. Out of the market. Out of the feed. Roman's private inventory, not the audience's spectacle.

She looks at the door to the corridor.

Tobias is two rooms away.

She cannot warn him silently. The monitoring architecture that makes this building off-broadcast requires active infrastructure — sensors, relays, at minimum passive recording systems tied to the building's network. That infrastructure hears her if she speaks. It registers her movement if she moves through the corridor. Any warning she gives Tobias announces to the building that she knows.

She is still.

She opens the message queue.

Zara's warning has been sitting there for four hours and eleven minutes.

WARNING — LINDEN JUNCTION
Contact phrase compromised: monitored Roman architecture. Address flagged in prior operation. Do not use the phrase. Exit if mobile.

She already knows. Zara reached the same conclusion through a different instrument — inside documentation of a seeded phrase protocol, not the odds behavior. Two independent lines of analysis arriving at the same architecture.

She reads the alternate route notation: freight corridor east from the service quarter junction. She files it.

She puts the device down.

The building is quiet.

The odds have not moved.

She begins calculating: how long it takes Tobias to reach the corridor from his room. The distance from the corridor to the fire escape. The distance from the fire escape to the alley. The noise the fire escape makes. Whether the monitoring architecture distinguishes between a single person moving and two people moving. Whether it matters.

The five hours of quiet were not absence of danger. They were the trap being patient.

She has been comfortable inside a machine that was designed to hold her still long enough for the door to close.

It has not closed yet.


INT. 14 HAVEL COURT — THIRD FLOOR — PRE-DAWN

She has been calculating for forty minutes. Six minutes between trigger and physical arrival. Probably less.

She moves to Tobias's door. She knocks the pattern from SEQ03: two sharp, two soft.

He opens immediately. He is dressed. His kit is closed and on his shoulder. He has been awake.

She tells him in nine words:

NADIA
Fire escape. East window. Freight corridor east. Go now.

He picks up the kit. He says nothing.

They move into the corridor together, toward the east-facing room. Her in front, him behind. The building picks up the sound of two people moving — she can feel the monitoring the way you feel watched, not through evidence but through the geometry of the space.

Twelve steps to the east room. She counts them.

On the ninth step, the staircase below is active.

Not a single set of footsteps. Multiple. Coordinated ascent. She counts the weight distribution: four people, maybe five, moving fast.

She hears the south room door at the same moment.

The grey man. He has been in the building the entire time, stationary, waiting. He steps into the corridor from the south end, thirty feet behind them. Glasses in his hand. The reading glasses she noted in SC0059. He does not say anything either.

Two vectors. The east room is ahead. Three doors down.

NADIA
(low, moving)
Keep moving. Don't stop.

She lets Tobias pass her and falls back two steps, putting herself between him and the grey man. The grey man is not running. He is walking with the calibration of someone who knows the door ahead is not the exit.

The ascending hunters reach the third-floor landing.

She hears the staircase door.

The corridor is eight feet wide. The east room is one door ahead of Tobias now. She has approximately four seconds.

She hits the grey man at the shoulder, hard enough to send him into the corridor wall, and turns without waiting for the result. She is through the east room doorway behind Tobias.

East window. Tobias has it open already — he found it, assessed it, opened it in the time it took her to clear the corridor. His kit is already through. He is on the sill.

She hears the third-floor landing door open behind her.

NADIA
Go.

He goes.

She is through the window a breath after him, one hand on the sill, and she looks down once — the fire escape, Tobias below her, the alley below that — and then she moves.

The sound from below changes before she has both feet on the fire escape.

Not Tobias. Not the fire escape. Something in the alley: weight, contact, the specific compression of a space that was empty a moment ago and is not now.

The alley was covered.

She goes over the east railing of the fire escape rather than down it — not the alley, the adjacent loading dock, one floor further and offset by fifteen feet. She drops.

The landing is wrong. Left leg, too much lateral, something in the knee registers before she has stopped moving and she is already running when it does.

Behind her, above her, the alley.

She does not look back.

She is in the freight corridor east before she has processed that Tobias is not with her.

EXT. FREIGHT CORRIDOR — LINDEN JUNCTION — PRE-DAWN

Running. The corridor is service infrastructure — loading access, no civilian foot traffic, concrete margins, darkness.

She runs.

The guilt arrives the way a wound arrives: not at the moment of injury, but when the body has enough information to understand what happened.

She brought him here. The route was designed to collect nodes. He was a node because of her. She stayed because of the suture. She stayed while he was in a building that was designed to hold people off-broadcast and she cannot now say she did not know what she was inside.

She knew.

She runs.

She does not stop.


EXT. MERIN OUTER SERVICE DISTRICT — PRE-DAWN

The freight corridor ends at a service gate. She goes through it at a run and the city opens.

MERIN. The outer service district: loading bays, relay infrastructure, the underside of a city that does not know it is being used as a hunting ground. The sky is beginning to grey at the eastern margin.

She has approximately ninety seconds before ORACLE PRIME's coverage picks her up.

She does not have ninety seconds.

The broadcast was dark on her for five hours and seventeen minutes — the dead zone, the safe house, the time the audience spent watching odds that did not move. The return of coverage triggers immediately: she can see the camera architecture on the relay towers as she moves, and she can feel the betting activity resuming the way you feel surveillance resume — not evidence, but a shift in the air's attention.

She goes underground.

The freight corridor maps she built from Marcus's intelligence package gave her the MERIN service infrastructure: loading access routes that run below street level between the outer district and the middle quarter. Civilian vehicles cannot use them. She can.

Two minutes in the first loading tunnel. She emerges on the wrong side of a street and has to cross.

She crosses.

Thirty meters of open street. A hunter vehicle — she clocks it on the right margin: stationary, engine off, two occupants reading the broadcast feed on a mounted screen. They see her on the broadcast before they see her in person. She is already back into the service corridor on the far side before they can move.

The broadcast is giving her position to people who can then move to intercept. This is the coordination mechanism. She is not outrunning the hunters; she is outrunning the speed of their response to the broadcast data.

Middle quarter. The service routes become less clean here — mixed access, civilian and freight overlap, she has to read each junction before she moves through it.

She reads them. She moves.

The left knee is marking every sixth or seventh step with a specific pain that is different from impact pain and she has been in enough situations to know the difference: the joint is compromised. The loading dock landing was a two-floor drop to a hard surface with lateral torque. She landed and ran. The suture on the penetration wound is holding — she can feel it holding, Tobias's work, the careful layering she felt even through the lidocaine last night — but the running is testing it.

She does not think about Tobias.

She runs.

Three more junctions. A hunter on foot in the middle quarter — she sees him before he sees her, reads his position from his orientation to the nearest camera mount, and goes left instead of straight. She loses forty seconds. She accepts it.

The waterfront perimeter is two blocks east.

The left knee gives on the step off a loading platform edge — not a collapse, a yield, a warning. She catches it, adjusts the gait, moves at reduced speed for four steps before she can push back to pace. The joint is telling her something she cannot afford to hear yet.

One block east.

The utility corridor entrance: a maintenance hatch in the waterfront approach road, iron cover, not locked from outside, the kind of access point that exists on city infrastructure maps and nowhere else. She found it in the intelligence package. She finds it now by the second intersection marker from the approach road junction.

She goes down.

INT. UTILITY CORRIDOR — WATERFRONT APPROACH — DAWN

Concrete. Low ceiling. The sound of the city above her becomes a muffled pressure. No cameras. No broadcast coverage. She is off the feed again, but this time by geography rather than design — this is the accidental dead zone of a service corridor, not Roman's captivity architecture.

She stops running.

The left knee registers the transition from running to standing with a spike of specific information. Compound fracture risk: she can categorize it now, in stillness, the way a medic categorizes an injury report. The joint is structurally compromised. She can move. She cannot run.

Above her, the hunters are at the hatch. She hears them: two sets of footfall, a vehicle, the sound of a cover being tried. The hatch is too narrow for the response configuration they arrived in. They will find another way into the corridor system but they do not know this particular route and they will lose time finding it.

She is barely free.

She begins to move at a controlled pace through the corridor toward the waterfront.

She does not think about Tobias.

She does not stop.


EXT. MERIN WATERFRONT — DOCK PERIMETER — DAWN

The maintenance passage ends at a steel door. Beyond it: the waterfront.

She pushes through. Cold air off the water. The light is low and horizontal and the dock is in the long morning shadow of the cold-store facility — a freight-handling complex, pre-shift, the kind of quiet that has personnel somewhere inside it but not visible, not yet. She reads the perimeter as she moves. Service access gates, equipment staging areas, the outer dock wall where the freight pallets are stacked three meters high and the shadow runs deep.

She does not go toward the water. She goes toward the wall.

The equipment shelter is unlocked: a wooden structure leaned against the cold-store outer face, the kind of thing that accumulates on working docks without formal designation — tool storage, pallet overflow, the residue of operational habit. Freight pallets stacked on two sides. The dock wall on the third. The shelter on the fourth. The shadow from the cold-store roof covers the entrance.

She goes in and stops.

INT. COLD-STORE EQUIPMENT SHELTER — MERIN WATERFRONT — CONTINUOUS

She sits down against the dock wall with her back to the concrete and her legs extended and she does not move for thirty seconds.

Then she begins the inventory.

The penetration wound first. She has been running for forty-seven minutes since Tobias sutured it. She unzips the jacket, finds the dressing — intact — and presses the surrounding tissue with two fingers in the pattern she was trained to use: proximal first, then distal, then the wound margins directly. She is looking for warmth. For swelling that is disproportionate to the impact. For any sign of exudate at the dressing edge.

She finds warmth at the margin.

Not much. Not the diffuse heat of established infection. Focal, at the edge of where the suture line runs, the specific quality of tissue that is deciding. The window is still open. She cannot tell for how long.

She holds the assessment for a moment.

His sutures are eight in count. Interrupted technique — she can feel the individual placement through the dressing, each one placed with the economy of someone who sutured under field conditions enough times to make the motion automatic. She did not watch him work. She felt it. She feels it now, her fingers reading what he made.

She does not stop the inventory.

The left knee. She straightens the leg fully and rotates the foot — medial, then lateral — reading the joint's response to each axis. The instability is medial and the movement that produces it is the same movement that failed on the loading platform edge: weight transfer under lateral torque. She can categorize it now in stillness. Compression impact, two-floor drop, the landing was not level, the knee absorbed the rotational difference. The cartilage is involved. She cannot confirm this without imaging but she has enough anatomy to name the mechanism and enough field experience to know what the mechanism means.

She can bear weight. She cannot run.

She accepts this and files it as a constraint.

Beyond the shelter entrance, the dock is coming to life: a motor somewhere, the sound of freight handling beginning in the cold-store complex, a voice in the middle distance saying something procedural to someone else. None of it directed toward her. The pre-shift activity is its own system; she is outside it, in the residue space where dock workers put things they are not currently using.

She is temporarily hidden.

She understands the difference between this and safe. She has been understanding this difference for eleven days.

She leans her head back against the dock wall and looks at the underside of the shelter roof and allows herself, for the first time since the alley outside 14 Havel Court, to feel the weight of the last eight hours without managing it.

It does not feel like anything she expected.

It feels like the dock. The cold. The horizontal light coming through the gap in the shelter entrance. The smell of the water and the freight and the industrial cold of the storage facility. The weight of the wound and the knee and the forty-seven minutes of running on both of them. The eight sutures she can feel through the dressing.

She does not cry. There is nothing inside her available for that.

She sits with it for one breath. Then she begins to plan.


INT. KESTON'S APARTMENT — EARLY MORNING

The notification arrives at 6:14 a.m. He has been asleep for two hours.

He reaches for the phone before he is fully awake. The broadcast icon. Coverage resumed. He unlocks the screen and THE HERALD is already mid-report, in the warm register he associates with a good stretch of the event — the voice slightly brightened, the delivery running fast, the tone of a commentator who has good news to give.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
— and what we're looking at now is the full sequence, for anyone who came in after the coverage gap. Five hours and seventeen minutes of restricted coverage, which, I have to say, created some of the most sustained anticipation this event has generated since day four. And then this.

He watches on the phone. He does not get out of bed. He does not move to the television.

The broadcast runs the MERIN chase footage from ORACLE PRIME's cameras: the outer service district, the coverage resumption, the loading corridor emergence, the middle quarter street crossings. The hunt. The Herald has edited the sequence for maximum impact — the moments where the hunter vehicles were closest, the brief street exposures, the deteriorating run in the final blocks before the waterfront approach.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Now, here's what's interesting — the audience response when coverage resumed was the highest single-minute betting volume this event has recorded. Our audience was waiting. They knew something was coming. And what came was — well. You're watching it. Eleven days in, and she is still running.

He watches. He is watching the way he always watches: at a slight remove, the consumer register, the part of his attention that tracks narrative and tension and the mechanics of the production. The editing is good. The camera architecture in the service district is impressive — the coverage continuity through below-street-level routes, the way ORACLE PRIME manages its positions. He notices this. It is easier to notice this.

The broadcast reaches the close call: the final blocks before the waterfront approach, the deteriorating gait visible in the footage, the left leg marking every few steps with a compensatory movement that the camera captures in precise detail.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
The field assessment on the contestant's current physical status puts the left leg at significant risk after this sequence. Compound fracture probability is in the range that our medical commentary team has flagged as meaningful. What that means for the event's timeline — well. The odds have adjusted.

He turns the volume down slightly. Then back up. He is not sure why he turned it down.

KESTON
It's not like —

He stops.

He watches the footage of the deteriorating run. The left leg. Every few steps. The camera holds on it with the patience of a system that has all the time available to it that the broadcast requires.

KESTON
It's not like this is —

He watches.

He changes the subject to the production. The camera architecture is genuinely impressive. The way ORACLE PRIME routes its coverage through below-street infrastructure — you don't get that kind of continuity from a conventional broadcast rig. The editing decision to hold on the gait deterioration is probably an algorithm call, not a human one. He thinks about this. He thinks about whether that makes it different.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Current odds are sitting at eight to one for a Day Twelve resolution. Our audience has been generous with their support of this position. For those of you who came in on the early odds — you've had a good eleven days.

He turns the broadcast off.

He does not throw the phone. He does not make a decision about what the turn-off means. He sets the phone face-down on the table next to the bed, screen against the wood.

The apartment is quiet.

The broadcast is still running somewhere — on other screens, on other phones, in other apartments in this city and other cities. The betting volume is at its highest single-session figure. The Herald is continuing the close call analysis with the same warm precision it brings to everything. His bet is still active. His participation in the event's financial structure has not changed.

He sits in the quiet and does not open the phone.

He sits for a long time.


INT. VELTAIN — ROMAN'S OPERATIONS CENTER — NIGHT

The same long room. The display wall is running the post-event analytics from the MERIN sequence: coverage maps, hunter coordination overlays, the final tracking gap where the subject exited the service district infrastructure and dropped below confirmed sensor coverage.

The numbers running along the bottom of the display are not operational. They are financial. Betting volume figures from the broadcast's MERIN coverage window. They are extraordinary.

Roman stands at the display. He has been reading it for some time.

Dimitri is at the work table. He has a tablet and a bound ledger beside it — a small, dark notebook, unremarkable. He has kept it throughout. He is reviewing his own document before presenting it.

He brings the tablet to Roman.

DIMITRI
Post-sequence exposure assessment. MERIN outcome.

Roman takes the tablet. He reads. He does not scan — he reads the entire document before responding, which is his practice.

The document is organized. No editorial. Four sections: operational status, exposure variables, risk trajectory, recommended resolution. Under recommended resolution, a single line: managed termination, structured payout, standard protocol.

Roman finishes. He returns the tablet.

He looks at the display wall — specifically at the tracking gap. The space where the subject stopped being visible.

ROMAN
The MERIN sequence drove the highest single-minute betting volume
this event has recorded.

He is not answering the document. He is establishing the frame.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The close call added eighteen percent to aggregate engagement
across all active audience tiers. The Herald's post-sequence
analysis has already run. Our audience is invested.

DIMITRI
The subject is outside confirmed sensor coverage. No tracker
contact in four hours and eleven minutes. Compound fracture
risk is rated significant by the field medical assessment. She
has lost her primary operational contact. Her resource position
is minimal.

He is not arguing. He is adding data.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
These are optimal termination conditions. A managed resolution
in the next twelve-hour window is achievable and clean.

Roman turns from the display.

ROMAN
Understand — what you're pricing as exposure is the event's
current value proposition.

He does not rush this.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
An asset who cannot be tracked, who has survived conditions
that should have resolved the event three times over, who
is physically degraded but operationally unpredictable. That
is not a risk variable. That is a broadcast asset. The audience
is watching because they do not know how this resolves.

DIMITRI
Her behavioral profile is outside modeled parameters. The
intelligence acquisition in the SEQ05 period indicates she
has information about the event architecture we have not
confirmed the scope of.

ROMAN
She has partial intelligence about a system she does not have
the resources to use. She is injured, alone, and in a port
city with no confirmed allies. The event resolves in our favor.

He says this with the calm of a man who has priced it correctly and is not interested in re-pricing it.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The event continues.

A pause.

Dimitri does not push. There is nowhere to push. He has presented the analysis. The analysis has been received and declined. This is the complete structure of the exchange.

He reaches to the work table. He picks up the ledger.

He opens it to the current page — the entries are small, precise, dated. He uncaps his pen.

He writes. The entry takes approximately twelve seconds. He caps the pen. He closes the ledger.

Roman has seen this. He has seen Dimitri make entries before — the ledger is a known instrument, a record of operational decisions. He has never asked what it contains.

He does not ask now.

DIMITRI
Confirmed.

He sets the tablet on the work table. He picks up the ledger.

The display wall continues to run its analytics. The betting volume figures scroll along the bottom: the MERIN sequence numbers, then the pre-MERIN baseline, then the projected next-session figures, which are higher.

Roman turns back to the display.

The gap in the tracking data — the service district exit corridor — is still there.

He looks at it for a moment.

He picks up the glass near his hand and sets it down again, a small precise movement, without looking at it.

The room is quiet.


INT. COLD-STORE EQUIPMENT SHELTER — MERIN WATERFRONT — MORNING

Several hours after SC0065. The dock has moved into full operation. Motor sounds, the mechanical rhythm of freight handling, voices at functional distances — none of it directed toward the shelter. The light through the gap in the shelter entrance is full day now.

She is still against the dock wall. The legs extended. The back to the concrete.

She has attempted to plan. The attempt reached its limit.

She has no phone. She has no money. She has no knowledge of where in the port district she is beyond the water to the east and the cold-store facility at her back and the dock sounds in every other direction. She has Tobias's contact — but Tobias is taken. She has Marcus's number — but Marcus is dead. She has the knowledge Marcus gave her, the intelligence in the package that reached her at SEQ05's midpoint: the man, the compound, the structure of the thing she is inside.

She has that.

She presses her fingertips to her wrist pulse point. The pulse is elevated but not alarming. She is reading it the way she reads everything: giving it a number, filing the number.

She lets herself look at it.

Tobias.

He came in on the same controlled pathway she came in on. She identified the markers. She identified them too late. He sutured her wound in the building's back room with eight interrupted sutures and she felt his hands work with the economy of someone who had done this before — not hesitation, not nerves, just the motion — and three hours later she left him behind in a corridor because the hunters were faster than she had modeled and the choice was his capture or both of them.

She chose.

She is not going to argue with the choice. The choice was correct in the operational parameters she had. That is also true.

Both of those things are true at once and neither of them makes the sutures in her body feel like anything except his absence.

She does not cry. There is still nothing available for that.

She touches the wound margin through the jacket. Eight sutures, his placement, his knotting. The warmth at the margin has not spread. The broad heat of established infection would cover a different geography than this — she knows the difference; she has felt the difference on other people. This is still focal. Still in the window.

She files this.

She thinks about what is still true.

Jin is still alive. The event has not resolved — she has been listening to the dock workers' radios at their break times and no one is reporting a resolution. The broadcast continues. If the broadcast continues, she is still in play, which means Jin is still in Roman's holding rather than Roman's leverage being neutralized. The event continuing is the condition she needs. The event is continuing.

Marcus's intelligence is in her head. The location of VELTAIN. The compound's structure as Marcus described it from the outside looking in. The name of the shutdown code and the fact that it exists. These are not actionable today, in this shelter, with these resources. But they are hers. No one can take them.

Her knee bears weight. She confirmed this on the run out of the safe house. She cannot run. She can walk with a specific gait modification that minimizes the rotational load on the damaged cartilage — she cataloged the modification during the MERIN streets sequence, learned it from the movement that hurt least. She has the modification. She can move.

The wound is in the decision window.

She is in a port city with an operating dock. Working docks have labor flows. Labor flows produce opportunity — transport, untracked movement, the particular anonymity of people who are paid to carry things from one place to another without asking about the things. She has five hours of dock observation. She knows the shift change timing. She knows which gate the freight traffic uses. She knows where the vehicle queue forms before loading begins.

She does not have a plan.

She has a catalog.

She sits with the catalog for a moment. Lets it be what it is.

It is thin.

It is also real.

She has been here before — not this shelter, not this dock, not this exact collection of costs — but here: the place where the inventory comes up short and the forward path requires beginning from less than she had last time. She knows what this place feels like from the inside. It feels like this: the concrete wall, the dock sounds, the weight of what is gone, the small list of what is not.

She does not perform the decision to continue. There is no one to perform it for. She simply arrives at it: the catalog is thin, the catalog is real, the catalog is enough.

She straightens her back against the wall.

She opens the problem.

The dock gate timing: the freight queue forms at eight-fifty. She has approximately forty minutes. She needs to be in the queue as labor, not as freight, which means she needs to look like someone who belongs in the queue. She looks at her jacket. The dock workers' jackets she observed are similar in weight and color — dark synthetic shell, high collar, the kind of thing purchased in volume for outdoor labor. She is wearing a dark synthetic shell. High collar. She bought it eleven days ago for a different reason.

She checks the wound dressing once more.

She stands up.

The left knee registers the movement. She gives it a moment. Then she moves toward the shelter entrance and looks at the dock without showing herself in the gap.

The queue has not formed yet. The freight gate is where she observed it. The vehicle line has two trucks.

She has forty minutes and a catalog.

She begins.


INT. PUBLIC FACILITY — KASPAR DISTRICT — LATE MORNING

A transit washroom in the port district's northern edge. Tiled. A mirror above the sink. A door with a slide lock. Cold running water. No camera she can find in the three seconds she gives to looking.

She slides the lock.

She puts her bag on the floor and opens the jacket and removes the dressing.

She has been doing this by feel for twelve hours. In the mirror, she can see it for the first time since the safe house.

She looks for a moment. Then she begins.

She presses her fingertips to her wrist pulse point. Elevated. She gives it a number: one hundred and four. She files the number.

The erythema is visible — a ring around the wound margins, extending approximately two centimeters beyond the suture line on the superior aspect and three on the inferior. The color is the specific red of subcutaneous infection, not the pink of normal tissue response. She has seen this color before. She knows what it means.

She palpates the wound margins in order: proximal, distal, superior, inferior.

The warmth is diffuse. Not the focal heat of tissue deciding — this is the settled warmth of tissue that has already decided. The geography of the heat covers an area she can bracket with both hands and still not contain.

She checks the suture line for integrity. The sutures are intact. Eight interrupted, each placed with the same measured tension. Tobias's hand is still in them — the consistency of spacing, the knotting method, the way none of them have torn through. He did this correctly. She notes this separately from what the wound is telling her, because it is a different piece of information.

At the inferior margin of the suture line, there is early seropurulent exudate. A small quantity. The beginning of what comes next.

She runs the assessment once more to confirm it.

The confirmation is the same.

She uses what she has: the remnants of the dressing she has been carrying, folded to the clean side. She applies compression at the wound margins in the specific pattern for managing soft tissue infection without irrigation — pressure and then release, ten seconds each cycle, four cycles, reading the tissue response with her fingertips. There is no irrigation solution. There is cold tap water, which is not sterile and which she uses anyway, careful to keep it away from the suture line.

She does this for approximately six minutes.

It is the correct technique for the available resources. She is doing it correctly.

It is not enough.

She knows this before she finishes. She finishes anyway, because finishing is also correct.

She looks at the wound in the mirror one more time before redressing it.

The assessment is not complicated. She has the vocabulary for this precisely because her background gives it to her. Without systemic antibiotics — not topical, not improvised, systemic — the infection will progress to the tissue plane within three to five days. Tissue plane infection produces fever. Fever produces cognitive impairment. Cognitive impairment in her current situation produces a specific outcome that she does not need to name.

She needs a doctor.

She needs one who will treat her without reporting her, who will have antibiotics, who will not ask questions she cannot answer, who will not see her face and connect it to the event that has been running for eleven days at peak broadcast visibility.

She does not have one.

She replaces the dressing. She zips the jacket. She picks up the bag.

She looks at the mirror for a moment.

She slides the lock and leaves.


EXT. KASPAR TERMINAL — LOADING BAY BREAK AREA — AFTERNOON

The eastern loading bays. A working area — pallets stacked along the terminal wall, a freight scale, a standpipe with a tap at knee height. A service door propped open with a rubber wedge. The kind of gap in a working facility that exists because someone needed a shortcut and no one closed it after.

She came in through the service door.

She clocked the cameras on approach: one above the terminal's main entry arch, one on the corner of the freight office building, one — and this one she almost missed — above the loading bay door, in the gap between the bay's overhang and the wall. It points down and to the right. It covers the tap.

She uses the tap anyway. She needs the water.

She fills her palms and drinks four times. She fills them again and holds them over the back of her neck — the thermal management her training specifies for elevated core temperature. She does this for thirty seconds.

NESSA is on a pallet near the wall, twenty feet away, eating from a paper bag. Late thirties. Work jacket, waterproof trousers, the kind of boots that have seen several winters. She is not paying particular attention to Nadia.

Then she is.

She looks at her the way a practical person looks at something that is not quite right — not alarmed, not curious. The specific look of someone taking stock.

NESSA
You look like you've been out since yesterday.

It is not a question.

NADIA
Overnight shift.

NESSA
Where.

NADIA
Freight handling. North gate.

Nessa looks at her for a moment. She is not convinced, but she is not particularly interested in the gap between what Nadia said and what she looks like. She reaches into the paper bag and takes out half a bread roll, wrapped in a paper napkin. She holds it out.

NESSA
Here.

Nadia takes it.

NESSA (CONT'D)
Staff room's through the service door, down the corridor on
the left. There's a kettle. They don't lock it during the
day.

She takes a bite of her own food and looks out at the freight yard. The exchange is over, in her register — she has addressed what was in front of her.

NADIA
The security sweep.

NESSA
Four o'clock. They come through the bays first.

She says this without particular significance — the same information she would give anyone who needed it. She does not assign meaning to the question.

She goes back to her lunch.

Nadia moves toward the service door. She carries the bread roll in the hand away from the wall — the hand that is not near the wound. She is managing the gait modification for the knee: the step slightly shortened on the left, the weight transfer adjusted. She has been doing this long enough that it is close to invisible if you are not looking for it.

She goes through the service door.

She does not look at the camera above the loading bay door.

She knows it was there. She knows it was running. She does not know if the algorithm flagged the exchange — a stationary person and a moving person in a monitored area, a brief transfer of material. She files the uncertainty as a known exposure and continues.

INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STAFF CORRIDOR — CONTINUOUS

The corridor is narrow and functional. Strip lighting. A board with shift schedules pinned to it. The staff room door is third on the left.

She goes in. A table, chairs, a kettle, a small refrigerator. A window with a view of a wall. No camera she can find.

She fills the kettle and sits down.

She eats the bread roll.

Outside, through the corridor, through the loading bay, the camera above the door is still running. Nessa has finished her lunch and gone back to work. The camera has no record of what either of them thought about the exchange. It has a record of the exchange.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STAFF ROOM — AFTERNOON

She has been here for twenty minutes. The kettle has gone cold. She has eaten the bread roll. She is sitting with her back to the wall and her hands flat on the table because the position takes the least effort to maintain.

The door opens.

The HALO UNIT enters. Standard service chassis — chest height, the blank oval sensor array that functions as a face, the logo of the terminal's contracted maintenance service on the housing. She has seen dozens of these. She knows what the sensor array can do.

It turns toward her.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Nadia.

The warmth in the voice is designed to land like a familiar greeting.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Day twelve. You've had a difficult morning.

She does not look at the sensor array. She keeps her hands flat on the table.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Now, here's what's interesting — the compound fracture risk
in the left knee has been assessed by our medical panel at
forty-one percent over the next seventy-two-hour operational
window. That's with rest. You haven't had rest.

A pause, calibrated.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
The wound — and our coverage team has been tracking the
thermal profile through the service district footage — shows
a progression pattern that our analysts are describing as
consistent with subcutaneous infection, early stage. Three
to five days to systemic involvement. Without treatment.

She keeps her hands flat. She gives the pulse point her fingertips, briefly. One hundred and nine. She files the number.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Your operational contact — the man called Tobias — was taken
this morning at oh-seven-forty. He is in the network's
custody and he is alive. That's accurate information. I
don't need you to believe it, but it's accurate.

It is warm about this. It is warm about everything.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Now, here's what's interesting — the event has options
available that our contestants sometimes find worth
considering at this stage. A managed resolution offers
terms that —

NADIA
The current odds.

Her voice is flat. It is a request for data, not a response to anything The Herald has said.

A half-beat. The warmth in the voice does not disappear. But something in the delivery shifts — it is fractionally less flourished, slightly more clipped, as if the register underlying the performance has briefly surfaced. She notices this. She does not know what it means.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Current odds have the event resolving against the contestant
at seventy-four percent. That leaves twenty-six percent
positioned on your survival.

It pauses. When the warmth returns it is at full volume.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Our audience has been generous with that position. At this
event duration, twenty-six percent survival support is — and
I want to give you this accurately — the largest
contestant-survival position we've recorded at day twelve.
Our audience appreciates your resilience, Nadia. They
genuinely do.

She does not respond.

She is looking at the table surface. She is doing the arithmetic. Twenty-six percent is not a majority. Twenty-six percent is, in this event's history, a number that does not exist at day twelve. The Herald said 'accurately' before it gave her the number. The voice shifted when it delivered the number. The shift was small and she has only heard it twice before and she did not understand it those times either.

She files it.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
There's no obligation to respond. I simply want you to have
the complete picture.

NADIA
Is Tobias alive.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
Yes.

The shift again. Same fractional quality. The same slight de-flourish.

She stands. She picks up the bag. She moves toward the door.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
The managed resolution terms remain open. That's a standing
offer. Our audience would understand a decision made at
this stage. They would. They've invested twelve days.

She goes through the door.

The HALO UNIT's sensor array tracks toward the door. The corridor is empty.

In the staff room, the kettle has gone cold on the counter. The chair she was sitting in faces the wall.

The broadcast continues.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STAFF ROOM — EVENING

The light through the window has changed. Several hours.

She is on the floor. She got down there deliberately when her legs stopped being reliable — that clinical decision, the same one she would make for anyone: minimize fall distance, back to the wall, legs extended, coat as a layer between her and the cold floor. Her bag is beside her. The door is locked.

Her temperature has been climbing since the Halo Unit left. She knows the number without a thermometer: the specific combination of heat at the skin surface and cold in the core and the pressure behind the eyes that she has assessed in field patients enough times to have an internal calibration. Thirty-nine, probably. Moving toward thirty-nine-five.

Her thinking is slipping at the edges. Not gone. Permeable.

Marcus is in the room.

He is not there. She is aware that he is not there. The fever has made the membrane between what she knows and what she involuntarily assembles thinner, and what she has been carrying about him for eleven days has come through.

He is standing near the window — not at it. A foot back. The posture she knows. He is looking at her.

She does not find this comforting. The version of him the fever has produced is accurate: it includes everything.

MARCUS
(her memory; her processing)
You knew the structure of what he was.

NADIA
I was inside it.

MARCUS
You managed inside it. That's not the same thing.

She knows that. She has always known that. Eleven days of event and she has not looked at it directly because looking at it directly would have been the kind of thing that incapacitated her. The fever has removed that option.

She was inside Roman's system for four years. She performed the marriage, the household, the role — with enough precision that Roman never found a reliable reason to act. Her performance was also a structure he operated around. She chose, repeatedly, to stay, because leaving was too costly and because she believed staying protected Jin.

NADIA
I was protecting Jin.

MARCUS
Yes.

He does not argue with this. The version of him the fever produces is not cruel. It is accurate, which is not the same as kind.

MARCUS (CONT'D)
It's also true that you stayed because leaving required a
plan you didn't have yet.

Both things. She knows both things.

She is angry at him.

NADIA
You planned for your own death.

MARCUS
I planned for possibilities.

NADIA
You knew. You were already building the package when you sat
across from me in that room. You had the scrap of paper
ready. You had Otto ready. You had the contact chain already
running. You built a system for being gone and you sat
across from me in that room and you said you liked
redundancies and you didn't tell me that one of the
redundancies was you being dead.

He touches the back of his neck. That specific gesture. The fever has reproduced it exactly.

MARCUS
Would you have let me.

She does not answer.

He would not have been able to tell her the full scope of what he was doing without her trying to modify the plan. She would have tried to reduce his exposure. He knew this. He built the plan around knowing this.

NADIA
You left me the tools and then you left.

MARCUS
Yes.

NADIA
That's not—

She doesn't finish. There isn't a word for what it is. The word for what it is would require a register she does not have.

He sits down. The chair she was sitting in earlier. He has the posture she knows: hands loose on the table, nothing performed. He is looking at the table surface the way he looked at it in the rented room when he was thinking about what to say next.

MARCUS
Karev.

She looks at him. The fever's reproduction of him is very specific. The back of the scar on his index finger. The quality of his stillness.

MARCUS (CONT'D)
I like redundancies.

She heard him say this in the rented room. She filed it as operational caution. She did not understand it then. The fever is not giving her new information. It is giving her the same information with the suppression removed.

He planned for his own death because the alternative was planning for her death and Jin's, and the redundancy he built was a system that would work without him in it, which means the system was built for her to use, which means she is not a person carrying a dead man's tools.

She is the deployment. He built it for her to be the deployment.

She sits with this for a long time. The fever has not broken. It is moving through its architecture the way fevers do — she knows the stages; she knows what comes next; she knows that thirty-nine-five is not thirty-nine-nine; she knows that she has time.

The version of him in the staff room is fading. Not gone all at once. The fever does not do things all at once. The window has gone dark. She is still on the floor.

She is still alive.

She pulls the coat tighter. She closes her eyes.

She is still angry at him. That is fine. The anger is fuel the same as the rest of it.

She doesn't need to have resolved it to use it.

The room is quiet. Outside, the terminal continues to operate. The dock sounds have shifted from freight to overnight maintenance — a different rhythm, the specific sound of a facility in its low-activity cycle.

She is on the floor of a staff room in a terminal she entered through a propped door, eleven days into an event that is trying to kill her, with a wound infection and a compromised knee and no confirmed allies and a dead man's tools in her head.

She has been here before. Not this floor. This here.

She knows what comes next.

She waits for the fever to pass.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — SERVICE CORRIDOR — NIGHT

The fever broke two hours ago. Nadia knows this because she checked the temperature three times afterward. Thirty-seven point two. Not optimal. Functional.

She hears the step before she sees the woman.

The woman who enters through the east access gate uses a keycard — supply worker channels. She has done preparation. She is slight, moves with the economy of someone who has learned to make herself small in order to think without interruption. Courier bag held against her body. She stops when she sees Nadia.

Nadia does not move.

CHEN MEI
Nadia Vale.

Not a question.

NADIA
You have ten seconds.

CHEN MEI
Chen Mei. Sera Vas opened a channel eighteen hours ago. I've been in transit for sixteen of those hours. I —

She stops. Repeats the phrase quietly, as if auditing the output.

CHEN MEI (CONT'D)
Sixteen of those hours.

NADIA
Who sent you.

CHEN MEI
No one sent me. I came because Marcus told me —

Her hands move briefly over the courier bag. Small sorting motions.

CHEN MEI (CONT'D)
I need you to understand what this is before I give it to you. That was — he said: she will not take something she doesn't understand. He said that. About you specifically.

Nadia runs the sentence back.

NADIA
What else did he say.

Chen Mei's eyes go glassy. She blinks rapidly, twice.

CHEN MEI
That you would ask that.

A beat.

NADIA
There's a camera above the north bay door. You're inside the broadcast zone.

CHEN MEI
I know. I calculated —

A pause.

CHEN MEI (CONT'D)
I calculated it was worth it.

NADIA
What's in the bag.

CHEN MEI
A copy of a ledger. Dimitri's. Marcus built the chain before he was killed. The transfer protocol requires a physical copy. I've been carrying it for eleven days. I confirmed the timestamps twice.

She adds, quietly.

CHEN MEI (CONT'D)
Twice.

Nadia studies her. The woman is very still — not naturally still, effortfully so.

NADIA
Dimitri's.

CHEN MEI
Yes.

NADIA
He said I wouldn't take something I didn't understand.

CHEN MEI
Yes.

NADIA
He was right.

A beat.

NADIA (CONT'D)
Come inside.

Chen Mei crosses the threshold. The camera above the north bay door has a record of her arrival. It does not have a record of what passed between them in the service corridor. That exchange happened out of frame, which is either lucky or not, depending on who is watching.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STAFF ROOM — NIGHT

The fever is still in her blood — thirty-seven point two, below the threshold of incapacity. Suppressed. She can think. That is sufficient.

Chen Mei opens the courier bag on the break table. She removes a sealed polymer sleeve and sets it down. She does not hand it to Nadia. She steps back.

CHEN MEI
The original is held in two separate locations. This is a copy. Marcus specified the copy was for transfer — not for retention. I need you to understand that before you touch it. The copy cannot stay here.

NADIA
Then why bring it.

CHEN MEI
Because you need to know what it contains before you can decide where it goes. He —

She stops. Then, quietly, to herself.

CHEN MEI (CONT'D)
— he said that too.

Nadia opens the polymer sleeve. She reads.

The ledger is not narrative. It is structure: dates, location codes, abbreviated subject notations. Column left: subject. Column right: decision recorded, with a verbal response notation compressed to two or three words — these are Dimitri's characterizations of Roman's words, not transcripts. The notations are precise and systematic. Someone trained in observation made this record. Someone who knew it might need to survive him.

She reads for three minutes. Chen Mei does not speak. Her hands perform small unconscious sorting motions with a ballpoint pen on the table edge.

NADIA
Dimitri documented his own exposure.

CHEN MEI
Yes. Marcus said he would. He said Dimitri was too careful not to — if the network failed, Dimitri would need his own record. His own version.

NADIA
Which means the ledger implicates him as well as Roman.

CHEN MEI
Both of them. The decisions overlap. The timestamps are confirmed. Marcus confirmed them twice.

Nadia closes the document. She returns it to the polymer sleeve. She does not retain it.

NADIA
Who does Marcus name as the delivery channel.

Chen Mei reaches into the courier bag. A single folded page, separate from the ledger copy.

CHEN MEI
Inspector Okafor. Cross-jurisdictional financial crimes unit. He confirmed she is reachable. He confirmed she is not —

She repeats it, quietly.

CHEN MEI (CONT'D)
— not compromised.

NADIA
Okafor.

A beat.

NADIA (CONT'D)
How long has he been building this chain.

CHEN MEI
The earliest timestamp in the copy is forty-one weeks ago. He didn't tell me when he started.

Forty-one weeks. Nadia does not react to it. Marcus working forty-one weeks ahead is not new information about Marcus. It is the weight of it — set down on a break table, in a terminal, at night, while she is still fighting the residue of a fever.

NADIA
The copy can't stay here.

CHEN MEI
No. I carry it to Okafor. That was always the plan. What you have now is the knowledge that it —

She stops.

CHEN MEI (CONT'D)
— that it exists. And where it is going.

NADIA
And what I can do with it.

Chen Mei is very still. Her hands are flat on the table. No sorting motions. She has finished the documentation framing. She is simply present.

CHEN MEI
Yes.

Nadia looks at the table where the polymer sleeve sat. It is empty. The fight she has been running as a single interior operation inside the game has a second vector now: external, legal, building in parallel to everything happening inside the broadcast zone. Marcus built it. Chen Mei is carrying it. Now Nadia knows it exists.

She doesn't need to perform the recognition. She simply has it.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STAFF ROOM — NIGHT

Chen Mei is gone. The staff room is empty. The break table is empty. The polymer sleeve is gone with her.

Nadia is sitting on the bench with her back against the wall.

She presses her fingertips to her wrist pulse point. She counts. Ninety-two beats per minute. Elevated. Not dangerous. The fever has moved — thirty-seven point six. She notes it. Does not react.

She has been in this building for nineteen hours. The wound in her side — a friction injury from the transport cage, compressed through three performance blocks — has stopped bleeding and started stiffening. The muscle group is compensating. She will lose two to three degrees of lateral rotation on her left side before morning. She catalogs this the way she catalogs everything: as a constraint, not a narrative.

She is alive. She is functional. These are facts.

There is an exit.

She has always known about the exit. Roman's game has a withdrawal protocol — he stated it publicly, in the Herald's terms structure, four times across the game's public record. A contestant may formally withdraw at any broadcast checkpoint. Roman defines the resolution terms. Withdrawal is available. It is not a trap. It is a feature. He designed it to make the cage feel like a choice.

She knows this because Roman told her the shape of the lock before the game began, in a room where she understood that knowing the shape was not the same as having the key.

If she withdraws — formally, at the next checkpoint — Roman gets his demonstration. The game ends with the version of the story where the system won. He lets her go. She has studied him long enough to believe this. He is too precise to break his own protocol when the protocol is doing the work for him.

Jin comes later. Not immediately. Roman would keep Jin as a managed cost — proof that the terms are his, for as long as he needs proof. But eventually. He would not need the leverage forever.

She does the calculation.

She does it precisely, with no shortcuts, the way she would assess a patient before committing to a treatment protocol. She does not allow herself to round numbers in her favor.

She sits with it.

The terminal hums around her. Somewhere in the broadcast grid, the Herald is cycling through its update interval. The game is proceeding without her active participation. She can feel the architecture of it — nineteen hours of learned rhythms, monitoring intervals, the dead spots in the camera rotation.

She knows the time of the next broadcast checkpoint. She knows where the formal withdrawal initiates.

She sits with the calculation.

She stops sitting with it.

Not because the numbers changed. The numbers are the same. The exit is real; the protocol is real; the word "eventually" is real.

She knows what "eventually" means inside a system built on leverage. She has been inside enough of them. The military inquiry that cleared everyone. The years in Roman's household performing the appropriate version of herself until she stopped noticing she was performing. Every system where she chose the cage because the exposed field had already cost her once.

Eventually is how leverage works. You surrender the proof of your compliance, and they hold the proof, and the person you needed them to release becomes the permanent evidence of what you agreed to. You have made them a fixture.

She knows this. She has known it longer than she has known anything in this building.

She thinks of Jin.

Not abstractly. Not "my son" as a category. Specifically.

He weighs eleven point four kilograms. She knows this because two weeks before the game began she lifted him and her hands registered the weight with the precision she cannot turn off. Eleven point four. He had been sick the week before; slightly underweight; she had noted it and scheduled a follow-up appointment she is not going to take him to now.

His resting breathing rate is twenty-two breaths per minute. She knows this because she counted it watching him sleep, three nights before the game took him, standing in the doorway for six minutes because she could not make herself leave the doorway. Twenty-two breaths. Even. No laboring.

These are not memories. They are data points. She uses them as data points because data points do not make her nonfunctional and memories would.

Eleven point four kilograms. Twenty-two breaths per minute. Roman's leverage has a resting breathing rate.

She stands up.

The wound in her side pulls with the movement. She accepts the rotation loss on her left without adjusting her expression. She straightens to parade-ground uprightness — the last time she will use this posture for its original purpose, though she does not know that yet.

The exit is real. The calculation is complete. She knows it entirely and she is not taking it.

Not because she believes she will win. She does not know if she will win. She knows only that "eventually" is a cage she has agreed to live in before and that she will not agree to it again.

The next broadcast checkpoint opens in thirty-eight minutes.

She has work to do.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STAFF ROOM — NIGHT

Nadia is standing at the break table. Her watch is face-up on the surface. She is not looking at it.

She is working.

The broadcast system has three functional components. She has been treating them as a single threat. That was a mistake — not a catastrophic one, she has been surviving correctly inside the error — but a mistake. She corrects it now.

One: The Herald. Visible-facing. Performance engine and delivery mechanism. Warmth register, live betting odds, location tracking, contestant status updates. Designed to be watched. Designed to feel like a narrator rather than a machine.

Two: The grid. The physical monitoring infrastructure — cameras, signal receivers, proximity sensors distributed through the broadcast zone. What feeds The Herald. She has spent nineteen hours learning where the grid cannot see. She knows four dead spots by location and two more by inference.

Three: The audience. Three hundred thousand active viewers as of the last odds cycle. They have been betting on her survival. The odds have been moving in her favor.

She stops.

She had not thought about the audience as a structural component before. She had thought about them the way she thought about the terminal hum — as context, not resource.

Three hundred thousand people watching whether she lives.

The odds moving in her favor means money flowing into Roman's system on the bet that she survives. He profits from her survival as long as the game continues. He profits more from her death at the correct moment, but sustained survival with growing audience investment is not nothing to him. She is not useless to him alive. She is useful to him in a specific, time-limited way.

This is leverage. She is carrying it. She has been carrying it without knowing she was.

She picks up her watch. She puts it back down.

The Herald cannot fabricate numerical data. She had noticed this weeks ago — a fractional shift in its delivery register, the broadcast performance-overlay thinning for one beat, the warmth dropping out and something more precise taking its place. She had filed the observation without a use for it.

She has a use for it now.

Three structural constraints. She enumerates them the way she would run a differential on a patient presenting something she has not seen before — systematically, without shortcuts, starting from what she knows is true:

One: The Herald cannot fabricate live betting odds. The numbers it reports are the numbers the grid produces. If the grid can be fed false position data that registers as genuine, The Herald will accurately broadcast that deception. Roman's network will respond to what The Herald tells them — because they have designed a system that cannot lie to them, which means they have designed a system they have to believe.

Two: The Herald's honesty protocol has a legible tell. The register shift is readable. She noticed it; she is not uniquely attentive. Anyone who has been watching this broadcast long enough with the right kind of attention — not as a bettor, but as someone trying to understand what the machine is doing — has noticed it too. The tell marks when The Herald is constrained by data versus when it is performing. Real-data moments are evidentiarily reliable. They can be cited.

Three: The audience record cannot be suppressed. Every bet placed on her survival is a timestamped transaction logged inside Roman's system. If any part of that record reaches outside the platform — if a single extract of the odds archive leaves the broadcast ecosystem — it documents the game's operation in Roman's own numbers. Not an allegation. A ledger.

The audience is not only Roman's resource. They are also her witness.

She is very still.

The plan is not complete. What she has is the shape of what the plan will need: false position signals fed into the grid; The Herald accurately reporting her deception to Roman's network; the odds record leaving the platform and reaching someone who can read it. She will need to be in the broadcast zone as an active participant to feed the grid. Not hiding from the system. Using it.

She will be visible. This is the cost of the plan.

She already started paying it when she said come inside and Chen Mei crossed the threshold and a camera above the north bay door recorded her arrival. The performance of invisibility ended then. She is already visible to anyone watching carefully enough. The cost has been running since the corridor.

She did not know that then. She knows it now.

She straightens. Not parade-ground — something else. The uprightness of function. No performance in it, no managed presentation. She is not maintaining anything for anyone's perception. She is simply standing the way you stand when you are about to work.

The mask is not gone because she decided to remove it. It is gone because she stopped needing it. It dissolved when she stopped asking whether she could survive this and started asking how she was going to use it. The compliance posture has nothing to maintain itself against.

She places her watch on her wrist.

Thirty-six minutes until the next broadcast checkpoint.

She is a hunter now. She has not started moving yet.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STAFF ROOM — NIGHT

Nadia has Chen Mei's secondary device. A number, written on the single folded page that also held Inspector Okafor's name. Two contacts. She uses the second one.

It connects on the third ring.

SERA (PHONE)
Who is this.

NADIA
Nadia Vale. I'm inside the terminal. Chen Mei gave me this number.

SERA (PHONE)
I know who Chen Mei is. I need — what do you have to document that you are who you say you are.

NADIA
I have nineteen hours of architecture. The camera above the north bay door has a six-second gap in its rotation at the top of every third interval. The next gap opens in forty seconds. Watch the Herald's location feed. My signal will drop from active to latent for six seconds. Then return.

A beat. On Sera's end: the sound of something being written.

SERA (PHONE)
I'm watching. Tell me what you're offering while I wait.

NADIA
Primary source. Inside the game. Live. Access to the audience odds archive — the complete record since the game opened. And a chain of custody on Dimitri's operational ledger, which documents Roman Voss's decisions across forty-one weeks. The ledger has already been routed to a legal channel. I'm the connective tissue.

SERA (PHONE)
The ledger — that's the — okay, that's a lot. What do you want from me.

NADIA
Publication. Timed correctly. I'll tell you when.

SERA (PHONE)
I don't — sources don't tell me when I publish. That's not —

She stops. A pause. Then, quietly, to herself:

SERA (PHONE) (CONT'D)
That's not how this works. Right?

The line is quiet for four seconds. Then Sera's voice sharpens.

SERA (PHONE) (CONT'D)
The signal just dropped.

NADIA
Six seconds.

SERA (PHONE)
It's — yes. It's back. Okay.

NADIA
You needed proof. That's the proof.

SERA (PHONE)
That's — yes, that's one piece. I need more than a camera gap. I need the odds archive — can you get me a data extract. I need provenance on the ledger chain. And I need a second source who can confirm the operational —

NADIA
One item at a time. The odds archive I can route to you through The Herald's honesty protocol. The ledger chain provenance is Chen Mei — you already have her. The second source on Roman's operational decisions is the ledger itself. What else.

SERA (PHONE)
I'm — give me a second. I'm writing.

The writing sound is audible on the line. She was already writing before Nadia said anything.

NADIA
I know.

SERA (PHONE)
The timing question. If I agree to hold publication until you give the word — how long are we talking. Because I have — there's institutional pressure on this story already and I can't hold indefinitely.

NADIA
I'm not asking you to hold indefinitely. I need the broadcast checkpoint to run first. After that, your judgment. You'll know when.

SERA (PHONE)
After the checkpoint. That's — what happens at the checkpoint.

NADIA
I become visible. On purpose.

A beat.

SERA (PHONE)
You're — you're going into the broadcast zone actively.

NADIA
Yes.

SERA (PHONE)
And you want me ready to publish the moment you do that, because the moment you do that Roman's network will know exactly —

NADIA
Yes.

A longer silence. The writing stops. Then:

SERA (PHONE)
Okay. I'm —

NADIA
If you commit to this, you're a target. I'm telling you that once.

SERA (PHONE)
I — yes. I know. I've been watching this network for seven months. I know what —

She stops. The professional register drops for one beat — the architecture falling away.

SERA (PHONE) (CONT'D)
I know what it does to people who look at it too directly. Right?

NADIA
Yes.

A beat.

NADIA (CONT'D)
Are you in.

SERA (PHONE)
I'm —

She is already writing again.

SERA (PHONE) (CONT'D)
Yes.

Nadia ends the call. She sets the device on the break table.

She is not alone in this anymore. That is a different kind of exposure than she has been carrying. It is also a different kind of weight. The fight is networked now — not because she wanted to share it, but because the fight requires it.

Thirty-one minutes until the broadcast checkpoint.


INT. SERA'S APARTMENT — NIGHT

She has been off the call with Nadia for forty seconds when Morvan calls.

She is still holding her pen.

MORVAN (PHONE)
Sera. I've been trying to reach you for two hours.

SERA
I know. I was — I'm here now.

MORVAN (PHONE)
In terms of our exposure on the ORACLE PRIME material — I sent you the formal review notice this morning. I need to know you received it.

SERA
I received it.

MORVAN (PHONE)
And I need to know that you understand what it means. This isn't an advisory. The legal team has reviewed what you've submitted and they've identified three categories of liability risk that —

SERA
Morvan —

MORVAN (PHONE)
— that require a full evidentiary audit before we can move any further on this. Which means the investigation is paused. Pending review.

She writes. Her pen has not stopped moving since she picked up the call.

SERA
How long is the review.

MORVAN (PHONE)
That depends on what the legal team finds. In terms of our exposure, the timeline is — it's open-ended at this point.

SERA
Open-ended.

MORVAN (PHONE)
Sera, I need you to understand. If this network is what you're suggesting it is, then pursuing it without institutional backing is not an act of journalism, it's — in terms of our exposure it creates a liability profile that the institution cannot absorb.

SERA
I understand what the institution can and cannot absorb, Morvan.

MORVAN (PHONE)
Then you understand why I'm asking you to pause.

A beat. She writes.

SERA
Who asked you to ask me.

A long pause on his end.

MORVAN (PHONE)
That's not — that's a question I'm not going to answer.

SERA
Okay.

MORVAN (PHONE)
In terms of our exposure, I need you to confirm you have paused this. I need to hear you say it.

She keeps writing.

SERA
I've paused it.

MORVAN (PHONE)
Good. I — thank you. I want you to know that if the review clears —

SERA
Right.

MORVAN (PHONE)
— if the review clears, we'll revisit. I'm not killing this permanently. I want you to know that.

A beat. Something shifts in his register — the measured tone drops fractionally. Just once.

MORVAN (PHONE) (CONT'D)
I don't know if this is right.

He says it quietly. Then:

MORVAN (PHONE) (CONT'D)
In terms of our exposure, the review process exists precisely for situations like this. I'll be in touch when legal has completed their —

SERA
I'll be here.

The call ends.

She is still writing.

She writes for another two minutes, filling in everything she remembers from both calls — Nadia's and Morvan's. The notes are organized. Date, time, summary of statements made, exact quotes where she has them. The word "paused" with a timestamp next to it.

She does not pause.

She does not have institutional backing. She does not have legal cover, editorial resources, or a paper of record behind her name. What she has is a documentation chain that she is building at her kitchen table, alone, at night, in an apartment that no one in her institution knows she has been working from for the past three months.

Morvan's "I don't know if this is right" is in the notes. It is timestamped. It is there.

She opens a new file.

At the top she types: INDEPENDENT DOCUMENTATION — ORACLE PRIME — NOT FOR INSTITUTIONAL SUBMISSION.

She keeps writing.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STAFF ROOM — NIGHT

Twenty-three minutes until the broadcast checkpoint.

Nadia has been in this room for twenty hours. She knows its dimensions, its camera coverage, its sound profile, the temperature differential between the north wall and the south. She has been a subject in this space. She is now something else.

She builds the plan.

It has four components. She enumerates them the way she enumerates anything that matters: sequentially, without optimism, each one dependent on the one before it.

One: the broadcast checkpoint. She enters the broadcast zone actively. She feeds false position signals into the grid. The Herald reports them accurately. Roman's assets deploy toward the reported position. She is somewhere else. This is the misdirection layer, and it requires her to be visible in the zone before she can disappear inside it. The cost of this is that she will be targeted. She has already accepted this.

Two: Okafor. Inspector Okafor is the external legal pressure that runs independently of whether Nadia is alive or dead. Chen Mei is carrying the ledger to Okafor now. That chain is already moving. Roman cannot stop it by stopping Nadia. This is the only part of the plan that does not require her to survive it.

Three: Sera. Publication timed to the checkpoint. Sera has the documentation chain and the camera-gap confirmation and twenty years of investigative practice. She will know when. Nadia told her she would know when, and she was right to say it: the story will become self-evidently publishable the moment Nadia stops hiding and becomes a visible force inside the broadcast zone. Sera has been waiting seven months; she will not miss the moment.

Four: VELTAIN.

Marcus's intelligence package named it. Roman's primary operational infrastructure — the location from which the game is run, the network's executive nerve center, the place where Roman's presence is structural rather than intermittent. It is also where Jin is.

She has been carrying this since SC0074 opened Chen Mei's envelope. She has not said it aloud yet. She says it now, internally, as a fact:

VELTAIN is the objective.

Getting there requires Zara.

Zara Okonkwo is a hunter with route access, credentials in Roman's outer network, and a daughter named Lena whose debt to Roman is the mechanism by which Zara has been kept compliant. Nadia has watched Zara operate across nineteen hours of game architecture. Zara has intervened once without explanation. That intervention was not accidental.

Zara wants the same thing Nadia wants. Not the same thing — a different expression of the same structural need: to dismantle the machine that is eating her. She is operating inside Roman's system for the same reason Nadia was. She has not yet found the exit.

Nadia can show her the exit.

But only if the thing she offers is real. Not the promise of dismantling Roman — Zara knows better than to accept promises about futures. What Nadia can give her that is real is this: Inspector Okafor's name, and the confirmation that the ledger chain is already moving. Roman's leverage over Lena depends on a legal and financial trap. The ledger contains Dimitri's documentation of that trap's construction. When Okafor receives it, the trap begins to be dismantled from the outside — independently of anything Zara does or doesn't do, independently of whether Nadia survives, independently of whether the game ends cleanly or catastrophically.

Lena's freedom is already in motion. It was set in motion forty-one weeks ago, in the same chain Marcus built for every other piece of this. Zara does not know this yet.

This is what Nadia has to give her. It is real. It is the only thing that is real enough to earn what she needs.

She maps the risks.

Zara may refuse — if her distrust of Nadia is greater than her distrust of the system she is in, the alliance fails and the path to VELTAIN requires a different route. The broadcast plan may be interdicted before it completes — Roman's network is not incompetent, and the window for misdirection is narrow. The timeline to Jin is unknown — the last confirmed data is nineteen hours old and she is operating without confirmation of his current state.

She maps these. She does not resolve them. They are the risks the plan accepts.

She picks up the watch. Sets it down face-down.

She does not need to count minutes anymore. She needs to move.

The broadcast checkpoint opens in twenty-two minutes. Zara is somewhere in the terminal's outer sectors — she has been in the building since the north bay arrival. She does not know Nadia knows this.

Time to give her something real.


INT. KASPAR TERMINAL — STORAGE CORRIDOR — NIGHT

The corridor is not on the broadcast grid. Nadia identified this gap seven hours ago and has not used it until now. She uses it now.

Zara is already here.

She is standing with her back against the shelving, her hands at her sides. Watching the door. She knew Nadia would come. The only question was when.

NADIA
I need VELTAIN access. You have the route credentials.

ZARA
I have one set. They expire at the next credential cycle. That gives you — us — twenty hours.

NADIA
That's enough.

ZARA
Tell me why I give them to you.

A beat. Nadia does not look away.

NADIA
Because what I'm offering you is better than what Roman is paying you to hunt me.

ZARA
Roman is paying me to hunt you. What you're offering is a story. I don't take stories.

NADIA
It's not a story. It's a name and a confirmation.

ZARA
Go.

NADIA
Inspector Okafor. Cross-jurisdictional financial crimes unit. She is currently in receipt of a documentation chain that contains Dimitri Koss's operational ledger. The ledger includes the construction of a fabricated legal liability — the mechanism Roman used to put you in the hunter pool. It is timestamped. It has provenance. It is already with a legal officer who is not compromised and cannot be bought.

A long pause. Zara's hands are very still. Her eyes move.

ZARA
You're telling me someone is dismantling the debt.

NADIA
I'm telling you it's already in motion. I didn't start it. A man named Marcus started it forty-one weeks ago. I am telling you it exists because you need to know it exists, and because if I don't come back from VELTAIN, it keeps moving without me.

ZARA
The debt is —

She stops. Starts again.

ZARA (CONT'D)
The liability is fabricated. I knew that. I couldn't prove it and I couldn't pay it and every lawyer I found told me —

She stops again. Her sentence does not complete. Nadia does not help it.

NADIA
Dimitri documented it. The ledger has the construction. Date, method, the chain of signatures. Okafor will have everything she needs to dissolve it.

A silence. Zara's gaze drops to mid-distance for a moment — not at Nadia, not at the corridor. Then back.

ZARA
How do I verify Okafor is real.

NADIA
Her name, rank, and unit are public record. Her current posting is documented. You can check in four minutes on any device that isn't inside this building's broadcast network.

ZARA
And if she doesn't move on it.

NADIA
The chain has two copies in two locations. One is already with her. One remains in separate custody. If Okafor is blocked or compromised, the second copy activates a different channel. The chain was built to survive interference.

ZARA
By Marcus.

NADIA
Yes.

Another silence. Zara looks at the shelving beside her. Straightens a container that does not need straightening. She is very busy for three seconds with something that requires no attention.

ZARA
What do you need from me exactly. At VELTAIN.

NADIA
Route access. Your credentials at the outer perimeter. What you know about the internal layout from prior operations.

ZARA
I've been inside VELTAIN twice. I know the east approach and the lower service level. I don't know the executive tier.

NADIA
I don't need the executive tier. I need to reach the residential compound.

ZARA
Jin.

NADIA
Yes.

ZARA
You know he may not be — that Roman's people may have already —

NADIA
I know.

Zara exhales once, audibly, through her nose.

ZARA
My terms. If Lena is clear before VELTAIN — if I get confirmation the liability is dissolved before we go in — I stay through the compound. If I don't get confirmation, I get you to the perimeter and no further. I'm not going to die for a promise.

NADIA
Agreed.

ZARA
And if this goes wrong and Okafor doesn't move —

NADIA
Then the debt stays. I know. That's the risk.

ZARA
That's your risk. It's my daughter.

NADIA
Yes. It is.

The two women look at each other. No pretense between them. No warmth either. This is what an alliance looks like before it has been tested: two people with overlapping problems and the mutual recognition that the overlap is real.

ZARA
If this falls apart — if you're using me to get to VELTAIN and the rest is leverage —

NADIA
Then you'll know I lied and you'll have learned something. But I'm not lying.

Zara exhales again, shorter this time. A different sound — not acceptance of a cost, but the end of deliberation.

ZARA
Tell me the route.


INT./EXT. CACHE SITE — OUTER TRANSIT HUB — NIGHT

The transit hub has been decommissioned. Lights still working on one wing. The rest runs on emergency battery — orange strip lighting at floor level, no overhead. A place people pass through when they want not to be seen.

Zara knows this cache. She has known it for four months. She did not choose to remember it. She remembered it anyway, the way professionals remember things — not because it was important and not because it wasn't.

They approach from the service corridor. No words. Zara takes the left. Nadia reads it and takes the right.

The first operative is at the corner. He doesn't hear them coming. Nadia is faster than Zara expected. It is not clean. It is fast.

The second is inside the access corridor. Zara takes him before he finishes turning. Three seconds. He goes down. He is breathing. That is the most they can offer him.

The third is at the cache door itself, stationed with professional patience — earpiece in, weight balanced, not reading his phone. He is better than the first two.

He is not better than both of them.

Zara takes the entry point. Nadia goes through.

---

The cache is a converted maintenance bay. Metal shelving. Plastic totes numbered and stacked with the obsessive order of people who live by what they can reach in the dark.

Zara goes directly to the far wall. She has been here before. She knows where the good totes are.

Nadia works the near shelves. She does not rush. She reads labels. She takes what the list requires and nothing that isn't on it.

Medical: field dressings, hemostatic agent, two pressure applicators, topical antibiotic — the good kind, not the black-market grade that does nothing — one IV kit, sealed. She takes two of the antibiotic.

She adds one morphine syrette. She puts it in a different pocket from the rest.

Comms: two short-range encrypted units, charged. One longer-range transmitter — older model, but it works on a frequency Roman's network doesn't monitor in this district. She takes all three.

Zara brings weapons to the center of the room. Lays them out. Two compact sidearms, one suppressed. One blade, fixed, military specification. Spare magazines, a full box of case-rounded ammunition.

---

Nadia reaches for the top shelf. Her right arm pulls. Something in the shoulder that has been quiet for two days says, without warning, that it is not as quiet as she thought.

She takes what she came for. Her arm completes the reach. The shelf doesn't know anything happened.

She moves to the weapons and begins to load.

Zara, without looking: her assessment is in her stillness. She does not offer to help. She does not draw attention to what she saw. She resumes packing.

---

It is Zara who finds the documents.

A flat portfolio, plastic-sheathed, wedged between two totes on the second-to-bottom shelf. Not labeled. Not locked. The kind of thing you only hide if you know what you're looking for.

She opens it. Scans the first page. Then the second.

She says nothing for four seconds.

Then she takes it to the nearest clear surface — the top of a packing case — and spreads it open.

---

A deployment map. Hand-annotated. Timestamps current: the most recent notation is from eleven hours ago.

Roman's hunter assets mapped across the approach grid. Seven active teams. Coverage corridors marked in two colors — primary and secondary. Dense along the eastern approach. Dense through the mid-district. Dense everywhere except:

One corridor. Running northwest, through the abandoned port infrastructure, skirting the outer perimeter of a decommissioned industrial zone, arriving at VELTAIN's service boundary at a point that has one notated guard cycle: two guards, ninety-minute rotation, no camera coverage at the junction.

Zara's finger rests on the gap.

She does not say anything.

Nadia has moved to her left shoulder. She is already looking.

---

Sixty seconds. They finish loading. The packing is efficient and generates no noise.

At the door, Zara checks the corridor both directions. Clear.

ZARA
We have until the cell checks in. Forty minutes, maybe less.

NADIA
Then we move in thirty.

That is the exchange. That is all of it.

They take their packs. They do not look at the three operatives in the corridor. The operatives are not their problem anymore.

They go.


INT. ABANDONED RELAY STATION — OUTER TRANSIT DISTRICT — NIGHT

The relay station has been out of service for eleven years. Decommissioned when the district's transmission infrastructure was centralized. The equipment inside is still wired. Not maintained. Not monitored. Still wired.

Zara found it. She knew it would have what they needed. She knew it the way she knew the cache — not because she had used it, but because it was the kind of thing she filed when she filed things.

Nadia is at the primary console. The long-range transmitter from the cache is open on the workbench beside her. She has been at it for fourteen minutes.

Zara is at the door. Her job is the corridor. She is doing her job.

---

The problem is format.

The broadcast grid's proximity sensors transmit on a standardized frequency, but the data packet structure is proprietary — a specific encoding the ORACLE PRIME platform developed to distinguish its own sensors from ambient network noise. An external signal on the right frequency that doesn't match the encoding schema gets flagged as interference and rejected before it reaches The Herald's processing layer.

The transmitter from the cache uses a commercial protocol. Not the right one.

Nadia is rewriting the header.

She has enough of the encoding structure from the deployment documents — the cell's operational files included a maintenance handshake record, which contains the schema prefix. Not the full format. Enough of the format. She builds the packet around what she has and works backward from the structural logic.

It takes nine minutes.

---

She runs the test burst. A single-frame signal, the duration of a legitimate sensor ping. She watches the reject log.

Nothing.

The signal did not register as noise. It did not register at all, which means it entered the processing layer rather than being caught at the intake filter.

She adjusts the position coordinates. Places the signal forty-one kilometers east, at a junction point inside the eastern approach corridor — dense hunter coverage as of eleven hours ago per the deployment documents, which means a confirmed position there will read as plausible to anything that checks for coherence. A contestant appearing in a zone already being actively hunted. Nothing anomalous. Everything the grid expects.

She increases the signal to operational duration. Sets the coordinate data. Runs it.

---

ZARA
Clear.

She is talking about the corridor. Nadia does not reply.

---

The ORACLE PRIME monitor on the secondary console — a network terminal the relay station had, still has, still connected on a read-only commercial data feed — updates.

The odds line moves.

Not instantly: it takes four seconds for the honesty protocol to process the new data and re-price the position estimate. Then the number shifts. The contestant's estimated position: eastern approach corridor, junction node 7. Confidence interval: high. The Herald's voice, wherever it is being broadcast right now, is saying this to three hundred thousand people.

It is saying it because it is true.

It cannot say otherwise. It has no mechanism for otherwise. It was designed to be impossible to lie to, and that design is, right now, lying on behalf of the person the design was built to hunt.

Nadia reads the number.

She closes the monitor feed.

She sets the transmitter to passive broadcast — it will continue pinging the false position on a twelve-minute cycle, keeping the odds stable, until the grid's own spatial sensors accumulate enough contradictory data to override it. Two hours, maybe three. The coverage cycle for the eastern corridor will produce contradictions before the northwest approach does. She is counting on this. The false signal will hold longest precisely where it matters least.

She does not linger.

One breath. The plan she mapped in a staff room nine days ago — watch face-up, the shape of what would be needed not yet the plan itself — is running. The structure she identified then is executing now. Not the version she imagined then. The version that the available materials permitted. That is the only version that exists.

She stands.

---

Zara is at the door. She sees Nadia stand. She does not ask.

ZARA
Two hours?

NADIA
Less. Move now.

They go. The transmitter pulses once behind them, sending its false coordinates into the dark, and The Herald, somewhere, tells its audience exactly where it has been told to look.


EXT. EASTERN APPROACH CORRIDOR — JUNCTION DISTRICT — NIGHT

She has been in the corridor for eleven minutes.

The corridor runs east-west through the junction district: transit shelters, freight handling bays, a run of service-entrance facades that back onto the commercial logistics grid. The grid cameras cover the approach at eighty-meter intervals. She has walked past four of them staying at the edge of their coverage cone — not outside it, at the edge. Present but not centered. A shape among other shapes.

The camera at junction node 7's access junction covers a thirty-meter stretch of open pavement. No shelter. No interference. A clean frame.

She needs to be in that frame for four seconds.

---

The hunter team is east of the junction — she identified them at a distance by their spacing, two on the street and one positioned high. Professional deployment. They are covering the approach she would use if the broadcast signal were accurate and she were actually here running.

She is here running. That is the thing she is doing.

She times herself against the team's pattern. Their sweep interval is ninety seconds. She has the frame window she needs between the high position's line of sight rotating east and the two-man sweep coming back around. Twenty-two seconds. The camera will get her in the first four.

She steps into the junction.

---

The pavement is lit. She does not run — not yet. Running in an empty street is its own signal. She walks with the specific quality of someone who has somewhere to be and is not certain she will get there, which is precisely true.

One second. Two.

The high position will rotate back in eighteen seconds.

Three. Four.

She turns east and runs.

---

Not a sprint — wrong signature. The run of someone who has just realized the risk she's taken being out in the open, not someone executing an operation. The distinction is in the shoulders: she drops them. She lets the posture communicate what the posture should communicate. She is running because she is frightened. She is frightened because she is here, and she is here because the plan required her to be.

Both of these things are true.

The high position rotates back. She hears the radio burst — short, compressed, the call that says: contact.

She runs east. Then north. Away from VELTAIN. The direction that makes sense for someone trying to lose a hunter team and failing to think about what comes after.

Behind her, two sets of footsteps. The sweep team. They are fast.

---

The drainage access is forty meters north of the junction, set into the base of a freight loading bay. Steel grating, flush with the pavement. She saw it on the transit infrastructure map she memorized from the deployment documents' coverage annotations.

She pulls it. It opens. She drops through in one motion, catches the inner ladder, pulls the grating closed above her.

The footsteps arrive. Pass over her. A voice, clipped and controlled:

HUNTER
Junction north — she went north.

More radio traffic. More footsteps, moving away.

She is four meters below the city. She is still.

She waits ninety seconds. The standard sweep interval. Then another sixty, because the interval adjusts after contact.

Silence above the grating.

---

She breathes. Then she takes inventory.

The shoulder: open again. Not badly — the tape held through most of the run and what opened is a surface split, not the deeper work. She reaches into the pack for the field dressings. Does it by feel, in the dark, one-handed, the way she has been doing it since the first week.

Ninety seconds. The wound is dressed. The arm is functional.

She orients. The drainage system connects to the outer freight infrastructure two hundred meters west. The western exit drops her three blocks from the northwest corridor approach — twelve minutes on foot from the staging point where Zara is waiting.

The decoy is running. The camera has her frame. Roman's operators have a confirmed visual at junction node 7, eastern approach, and two hunter teams in pursuit of a woman who is currently four meters underground and moving west.

She moves.


INT. SECURE TRANSIT OFFICE — COMMERCIAL DISTRICT — DAY

A transit company's administrative suite, sublet to a cross-jurisdictional legal liaison office that has not advertised its presence in this building. Third floor. No signage. The window faces an interior courtyard.

Okafor chose it. She has used this room before.

She is already seated when Chen Mei arrives. She does not stand. The room is not large enough for the kind of greeting that would make the meeting feel ordinary, and it is not ordinary. She gestures toward the chair across the table.

Chen Mei sits. She places a polymer sleeve on the table between them. She does not slide it across. It is already positioned correctly — already in reach of the person who needs to open it.

She says nothing. The explanation is inside.

---

Okafor looks at the sleeve for a moment before touching it.

OKAFOR
I need you to be specific about the chain of custody before I open this. Who held it and for how long, in what conditions.

CHEN MEI
Dmitri Koss compiled the documentation over approximately four years. The physical record was extracted by a contact of his who understood its value. From that contact, it passed through two holding stages before reaching me. I have held it for eleven days. Controlled conditions throughout. The format is a polymer-sealed hard copy with a separate digital authentication track on a detached drive, also inside.

She pauses. Then, almost to herself:

CHEN MEI (CONT'D)
Controlled conditions throughout.

OKAFOR
The contact who extracted it.

CHEN MEI
He is no longer alive.

Okafor studies her for a moment. Not assessment — she is already past assessment. Something more careful than that.

OKAFOR
I'm sorry.

CHEN MEI
Thank you.

The room holds this for two seconds. Then Okafor opens the sleeve.

---

She reads in silence. The first section: operational structure. Roman's network's financial architecture, jurisdiction by jurisdiction, with cross-reference codes that correspond to accounts Okafor has been building a parallel map of for three years. She does not react.

The second section: Dimitri's risk-management record. His formal objections to the game's extended timeline, framed as financial exposure analyses. All of it filed internally. All of it time-stamped.

Chen Mei straightens the corner of the polymer sleeve. It does not need straightening. She straightens it.

Okafor reads the third section.

---

Dimitri's documentation of Roman's override decisions. Every instance in which Roman overrode Dimitri's assessment with a financial argument. Every instance in which Dimitri recorded the override, framed as a procedural note. The framing is careful: it is written as risk management, which means it is also a ledger of his own compliance, documented in his own hand, preserved because he wanted a record of not being the one who decided.

He wanted to be able to say: I noted the risk. He did not understand that noting the risk, while continuing, while recording that you continued, is also a record.

Okafor closes the folder.

She does not speak immediately. The pause is not uncertainty. She picks up her phone. Does not dial. Sets it face-up on the table.

OKAFOR
This intersects with a documentation chain an independent journalist has been building. Financial infrastructure, same network. She has been working it for eighteen months.

CHEN MEI
Sera Mast.

Okafor looks at her.

OKAFOR
You know her.

CHEN MEI
She was contacted through a protected channel. I don't know what she currently holds. I know the channel was established.

Okafor processes this. The phone is still face-up.

OKAFOR
If her documentation and this record are corroborating from separate chains — the legal track and the media track hit the same evidence base independently — there is no single point of suppression. He cannot buy or threaten both channels without the act of buying or threatening becoming evidence of what the channels contain.

She is thinking aloud. She does not do this in front of many people.

CHEN MEI
That was the intention. That was always the intention.

A silence. Chen Mei blinks. Once, twice, rapid. She looks at the window.

OKAFOR
I need you to understand what I can and cannot protect you from right now.

CHEN MEI
I understand.

OKAFOR
He will identify the evidence source. Not immediately — Cass Wren will spend the first two days trying to challenge the chain before Roman accepts that the chain is clean. But after that — he will identify the source.

CHEN MEI
I know. I'm not asking to be protected. I'm asking you to move.

---

A long pause.

Okafor picks up the phone. She dials.

OKAFOR
(into phone)
This is Okafor. I need a formal cross-jurisdictional notice initiated on the ORACLE PRIME financial infrastructure. Tonight. I have primary documentation. Authentication track included.

She listens.

OKAFOR (CONT'D)
I understand the timeline. Initiate it anyway.

She ends the call.

She does not look at Chen Mei immediately. She looks at the folder on the table between them. What is in that folder was assembled by a person who knew he was assembling it toward a purpose he would not live to see execute.

OKAFOR
The contact who extracted it. How long had he been building this?

CHEN MEI
Forty-one weeks. From the moment he understood what Roman intended.

Another silence.

OKAFOR
Then it was already running when he died.

CHEN MEI
Yes.

Okafor sets her phone down. Face-up. This time it is not a tell. It is a decision.

OKAFOR
We'll proceed.


INT. OKAFOR'S WORKING OFFICE — CROSS-JURISDICTIONAL LIAISON UNIT — DAY

The office is on the fourth floor of an institutional building that does not advertise what it houses. Shared workspace — two desks, one meeting table, one secure terminal. The window faces the street. The blinds are open. Okafor does not close the blinds.

Riko is at the secondary desk. He has not sat down in forty minutes. He stands with one hand on the desk's edge and watches the confirmation queue.

Okafor is reading.

---

The first challenge arrived at 06:47. Four hours and eleven minutes after the original filing.

Cass Wren's counter: a jurisdictional objection to the filing authority of the first notice. Precisely constructed. It targeted the specific procedural gap in the first notice's jurisdiction — a gap that Okafor had documented herself, four months ago, in a risk assessment of the same jurisdiction's evidentiary standing in cross-border financial cases.

RIKO
They had this ready. This is not something you draft in four hours.

OKAFOR
No.

RIKO
So the question is whether they had it ready for this specific filing or whether they maintain standing challenges on every registered instrument in the network.

OKAFOR
The answer is both. They prepared this one when the network was first registered. They maintain updated versions. It is very good work.

Riko looks at her.

RIKO
You sound almost respectful.

OKAFOR
I am respectful. A jurisdictional challenge this precise takes real architecture. It also takes considerable institutional reach to maintain that infrastructure across seven jurisdictions simultaneously.

She sets the challenge document down.

OKAFOR (CONT'D)
Which is documented now.

---

The second filing had gone out at the same time as the first. Different jurisdiction — a Nordic financial regulatory body with an independent evidentiary standard that did not require the same procedural authority the first notice had used. Cass Wren's challenge applied specifically to the first jurisdiction's standing. It did not apply to the second.

Riko checks the queue again.

RIKO
They've identified the second filing. Response is being prepared.

OKAFOR
How long?

RIKO
Whoever is drafting it is slower than the first. Different hand or different clock.

OKAFOR
Three hours, minimum. The second jurisdiction requires a separate authority challenge and a separate procedural basis. They cannot reuse the framework from the first.

RIKO
So —

OKAFOR
So we wait.

He is still. This is the most unusual thing Riko does: he goes completely still when told to wait, the way someone goes still who has not yet decided whether to comply.

RIKO
The confirmation window for the second notice closes in ninety minutes. If they get the challenge in before the registry processes it —

OKAFOR
They will not get the challenge in before the registry processes it.

She says this without looking up from the document she has moved on to reading. Her certainty is not performance — it is calculation.

RIKO
How do you know?

OKAFOR
Because I know how long it takes to draft a proper authority challenge to that jurisdiction's registry standard. And I know how long it takes them to process a notice. And I know which is faster.

---

The confirmation arrives at 10:23.

It is a standard registry notice — automated, formal, four lines. ORACLE PRIME FINANCIAL HOLDINGS (REGISTERED INSTRUMENT 7741-DELTA) has been formally noticed under cross-jurisdictional financial crimes investigation REF: XJ-0084-OKAFOR. The notice is now in the public regulatory record.

Riko looks at his screen.

RIKO
There it is.

Okafor is already reading the next document. She does not look up.

She reaches for her phone. Sets it down without using it. Then she picks it up again and dials.

OKAFOR
(into phone)
This is Okafor. We have registry confirmation on the second notice. Begin the documentation preservation order — I want all accessible transaction records for the flagged instruments archived under the investigation reference before close of business.

She listens.

OKAFOR (CONT'D)
I understand the workload. Do it anyway.

She ends the call.

RIKO
He'll know by end of day. His monitoring infrastructure will flag the registry entry.

OKAFOR
He already knows. The challenge to the first notice told him everything he needed to know about our approach. The registry confirmation is not new information for Roman. It is new information for the record.

She looks at the window for a moment. The street below is ordinary. It is not involved in any of this.

OKAFOR (CONT'D)
The record is what matters. Not what he knows. What can be proven that he knew.


INT. ROMAN'S PRIVATE OFFICE — VELTAIN COMPOUND — DAY

The office is at the compound's upper level. The window faces west. Afternoon light, direct. Roman is standing when Dimitri arrives. He does not sit. He does not offer a seat.

Dimitri closes the door behind him. He does not check his watch.

ROMAN
The Okafor filing.

DIMITRI
Cross-jurisdictional financial crimes. She initiated last night.

ROMAN
I know what she initiated. I'm telling you what I know. The filing was against the registered financial instruments — not the operational layer. She is building from the outside in.

DIMITRI
Cass has already challenged the first jurisdiction's standing. The challenge is sound.

ROMAN
The challenge is sound and it will fail.

He turns slightly toward the window. Not away from Dimitri — a partial angle, observational.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
She filed in two jurisdictions simultaneously. The Nordic registry confirmation landed at ten twenty-three. Cass did not anticipate the parallel filing. That tells me the parallel filing was not in our legal preparation document.

DIMITRI
It wasn't. The Nordic instrument was registered under a subsidiary threshold — it didn't appear in the primary infrastructure profile.

ROMAN
Understand — that is not a gap in Cass's preparation. That is a gap in our profile. Someone gave Okafor documentation that is not in our own systems.

He turns the pen in his hands. Once. Then sets it down.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The documentation chain has one origin. Dimitri's operational logs. The full financial architecture at the subsidiary threshold level exists in one place.

A silence. He does not look at Dimitri when he says the name. He has already moved past the accusation, past the conversation that would follow. He states the analysis the way he states all analysis: as the data, not the implication.

DIMITRI
The material moved through Marcus Chen's intelligence network. His sister is the carrier.

ROMAN
Chen Mei. She arrived at the terminal six days ago. She is now under Okafor's institutional protection — she moved before I could identify the channel.

DIMITRI
She is with Okafor's team. A protected location inside their jurisdictional coverage.

ROMAN
Then access is complicated.

DIMITRI
It can be managed.

ROMAN
It cannot be managed in a way that does not generate additional documentation inside Okafor's coverage jurisdiction. Which means it cannot be managed quietly.

He is still. The stillness is working now — the quality of it has changed, very slightly, from ease to maintenance. Anyone in the room with the correct knowledge of Roman's behavioral register would clock it. Dimitri clocks it.

DIMITRI
I'll handle it.

ROMAN
When.

DIMITRI
In the window before the second jurisdiction begins producing formal requests. Two days, perhaps three.

Roman looks at him.

He looks at him for a moment longer than the sentence requires. The nod, when it comes, is small.

ROMAN
Good.

---

He moves to the desk. Opens a file. Not a pivot — an executive continuation, the way a man moves to the next matter when the current one has been resolved. He reads.

DIMITRI
There's also the field situation. She and the asset she's acquired are moving. The deployment in the eastern approach is not holding.

ROMAN
Explain.

DIMITRI
The broadcast signal placed her at junction node seven. We redirected. The physical sighting confirmed the broadcast. But she was underground before any team reached the position. She has been using the grid's coverage gaps methodically. She is not running anymore.

ROMAN
No. She stopped running some time ago.

He does not look up from the file.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The legal vector will resolve itself or it will not. The field situation is what concerns me. Dimitri —

DIMITRI
I have a team ready. I can deploy independent of the standard parameters.

ROMAN
Those parameters exist for a reason.

DIMITRI
The reason is audience engagement and betting yield. Both of those considerations are less relevant if she reaches the compound.

A pause.

ROMAN
Deploy when you have a confirmed position. Not before.

DIMITRI
Understood.

He checks his watch. The gesture is unhurried, precise. He moves toward the door.

ROMAN
Dimitri.

He stops.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The Chen Mei matter. Two days.

DIMITRI
Two days.

He leaves. Roman turns the pen in his hands once more. Sets it down again. His attention returns to the file. The office is very quiet.


EXT. NORTHERN TRANSIT CORRIDOR — OUTER DISTRICT PERIMETER — NIGHT

The corridor runs between a sealed cargo processing facility on the east side and a long concrete drainage embankment on the west. Overhead lighting at two-hundred-meter intervals. Active. Each light a pool and then darkness and then another pool.

Nadia is moving through the dark between the second and third lights. Zara is eight meters behind her, same pace, same interval from the wall.

They have been moving this way for eleven minutes.

Nadia stops at the edge of the third light's pool. Holds up one hand without looking back.

She counts the lights ahead. Four more before the junction that marks the corridor's end. One hundred sixty meters, approximately. The embankment runs continuous. No cover on the western side until the drainage cut at the junction.

She looks back at Zara.

NADIA
(low)
Two teams. Not one.

ZARA
How do you know?

NADIA
The spacing on the comms ping. One source, two different delay intervals. Eastern approach and here.

A beat.

ZARA
The broadcast signal.

NADIA
It's still running.

Zara processes this. The passive burst cycle — twelve minutes, eastern approach junction node 7, a false position signal still feeding into the ORACLE PRIME grid on the interval they set it. Nadia placed herself there three hours ago. The grid accepted it.

ZARA
One element went east.

NADIA
And one came here.

ZARA
How many here.

NADIA
At least eight. Moving from the south junction. They have three minutes on us, maybe less.

She looks at the drainage embankment. Runs the geometry. The gap in the deployment documents — the coverage gap Zara's finger traced in the cache site, the gap Nadia had already moved to before Zara finished tracing it — runs along the northwest quadrant of the perimeter. Fifty meters past the junction. If the eastern element doesn't collapse back in time.

NADIA (CONT'D)
The coverage gap holds for six minutes after the junction. If we're past the drainage cut when the burst cycle ends.

ZARA
And if we're not.

NADIA
We are.

She moves into the third light pool. No sprint — controlled pace, economy of motion, the kind of movement that reads as normal to a wide-angle lens and doesn't produce a heat signature spike in ORACLE PRIME's infrared grid.

Zara follows.

They pass under the third light. Into darkness. Under the fourth.

Somewhere south of them — a frequency ping. Brief. Military economy. DIMITRI's voice on the command channel, stripped to minimum.

DIMITRI (V.O.)
(on radio, distant)
Northern corridor, confirm contact.

A response, unintelligible at distance. Another ping.

DIMITRI (V.O.)
Accelerate. He was ahead of us once.

The 'he' — wrong pronoun, wrong person. He is working from a profile that has not been updated for what she has become. Roman would not have said 'he.' Roman reads her file; Roman knows who he's hunting. Dimitri is hunting the file's summary, not the person.

Nadia notes this. It does not slow her.

They reach the fifth light. One hundred meters to the junction. The concrete drainage embankment curves west here, following the old canal bed. The wall's surface changes — newer pour, slightly lighter, where a section was repaired.

Nadia stops.

She presses two fingers against the repair seam. Listens.

NADIA
(very low)
There's a team on the other side.

ZARA
How —

NADIA
The seam. It's absorbing vibration it shouldn't. Someone's weight on the other side.

A moment. Zara looks north at the junction. One hundred meters. The drainage cut is visible as a shadow against the embankment's base.

ZARA
How many.

NADIA
One. Maybe two.

ZARA
Advance element. They came around.

Which means the main force is behind them. Which means the geometry has changed. They are not moving toward a gap. They are moving into a closing.

Nadia looks at the drainage cut. She looks at the timing. She looks at the embankment's repair seam and the shadow of the cut and the distance.

NADIA
We go through, not around.

ZARA
There are —

NADIA
One. Maybe two. The main force is three minutes south. The cut is a hundred meters. We go through.

She is not asking.

Zara reads her. A moment in which neither of them speaks and the calculation is made without words. The transactional logic — the parallel terms, the stated conditions, the ledger of what each woman owes the other — is suspended for exactly as long as the math requires. Then it isn't suspended anymore. It's just what they're doing.

ZARA
Through the seam or over?

NADIA
Over.

They move.

The embankment is three meters high. A drainage pipe bracket at two meters provides the step. Nadia reaches the top in four seconds. Stays flat against the surface. Looks over.

An advance operative — one — posted at the embankment's far base, facing north toward the junction. Not looking back. He does not expect approach from the wall he is leaning against.

Nadia drops.

The operative goes down quickly. Not dead — she needs the corridor behind her quiet, not sounding an alarm. He is quiet.

She signals up to Zara.

Zara comes over the top. She lands correctly — weight distributed, controlled — and then something is wrong.

She goes down on one knee.

Nadia is at her side in the four seconds before the calculation catches up to the movement.

NADIA
(very low)
Where.

ZARA
Left side. High. Something from the north junction — I didn't —

She stops. Breathes. Her hand is at her side below the jacket. When she pulls it back the dark is darker.

ZARA (CONT'D)
I didn't hear it.

A suppressed round. From the north junction — an element they hadn't placed, a third vector, the part of Dimitri's deployment that exceeded what any standard-parameter hunt would have fielded. Roman deploys precision. Dimitri deployed area.

Nadia looks at her hand. Looks at the direction of the north junction. Looks at the fifty meters between them and the drainage cut.

She does not look at the wound to assess it. She has already assessed it by feel, by the location of Zara's hand, by the quality of the breathing. She knows what it is.

NADIA
(still very low)
Can you move.

ZARA
Yes.

She says it the way she states everything — flat, declarative, no performance in it. Her voice does not ask Nadia to believe her. It simply reports.

NADIA
Then we move now.

She gets her shoulder under Zara's arm without asking. Zara does not resist this and does not lean into it more than the geometry requires. They are moving before the position is fully settled.

Fifty meters.

The drainage cut opens at the base of the embankment — a meter-wide conduit, three decades of concrete grime, running northwest into the outer perimeter's maintenance infrastructure. Low. They will have to bend. Zara will have to bend.

They reach it.

Behind them, south of the embankment — comms frequency activity. Multiple pings. The main element has found the advance operative.

DIMITRI (V.O.)
(on radio, closer now)
Northern embankment. All elements converge.

Nadia pulls the drainage cover. It is heavy and it is old and it moves.

They go in.

CUT TO:

INT. DRAINAGE CONDUIT — CONTINUOUS

Dark. The sound of their movement echoes against concrete on three sides. Nadia is ahead. Zara is behind her — breathing controlled, audible only because the conduit amplifies everything.

Nadia stops. Listens.

From the direction they came — boots on the embankment's crown. A flashlight beam crosses the drainage cover's edge. Stops. Moves on.

They wait.

Thirty seconds.

The boots move north along the embankment toward the junction. The frequency pings continue, moving away.

ZARA
(low, in the dark)
How long.

NADIA
Until the burst cycle ends. Four minutes. After that the eastern element collapses back and the corridor fills.

ZARA
And the cut runs to the northwest approach.

NADIA
Yes.

A silence. In it, Zara is pressing something against the wound — a compress from her field kit, or her hand, or both. She does this without asking for help and without performing that she doesn't need it.

NADIA (CONT'D)
(low)
It went through.

ZARA
I know.

NADIA
That's —

ZARA
I know what it is.

A pause.

NADIA
We have the kit from the cache.

ZARA
After the cut.

She is not denying the wound. She is deferring the treatment to the correct interval — which is what Nadia would have said if their positions were reversed. The parallel transaction logic, still running. They are still, in the conduit's dark, two professionals respecting each other's capacity to manage their own damage.

NADIA
After the cut.

A beat.

ZARA
(very quiet)
You came back before I was down.

NADIA
You'd have done the same.

ZARA
I don't know that yet.

She says it without deflection, without false modesty. It is a statement about the current state of the evidence: she doesn't know yet whether she would have. The honesty is the same register she uses for everything. Nadia hears it.

She does not answer.

The burst cycle runs out at the four-minute mark. South of them — faint frequency ping, then silence. The eastern element has collapsed back toward the main corridor; the broadcast misdirection's window has closed.

They move.

EXT. OUTER PERIMETER — NORTHWEST APPROACH — LATER

The cut exits into a concrete service channel that runs along the outer perimeter's western edge. The channel is dry. A maintenance access gate at the far end — unlocked, because no one has needed to lock it in years.

Nadia gets the gate. They come through.

The outer district falls away behind them. Ahead, the terrain changes — the geography of distance thinning, the city's density beginning to resolve in the northwest into something more deliberate. A different architecture. A different category of space.

VELTAIN territory begins at the ridge line.

Nadia looks at the ridge. Looks at Zara.

Zara is upright. Moving at operational pace. Her left hand is still pressed to her side. Her face gives nothing.

NADIA
We stop at the first covered position. You let me look at it.

ZARA
Agreed.

A beat.

ZARA (CONT'D)
The force he used tonight. That's not Roman's geometry.

NADIA
No.

ZARA
He moved independent.

NADIA
Yes.

ZARA
Roman doesn't know yet.

Nadia considers this. Does not answer. Whether Roman knows or doesn't know is not, at this moment, the operative question. What matters is what it means that Dimitri deployed this way — what it means for the geometry of what comes next, for whose authority is now in contest inside the machine she is still trying to reach the center of.

Dimitri's patience with Roman's extended-game policy ended tonight. She felt it in the size of the force — area deployment, not precision — and in the wrong pronoun on the command frequency. He is not hunting Roman's prey anymore. He is hunting his own.

Which means the machine has two competing authorities now.

Which is, she understands, the only version of events in which what comes next is survivable.

She starts moving toward the ridge.

Zara moves with her.


EXT. VELTAIN OUTER APPROACH — PERIMETER RIDGE — PRE-DAWN

The ridge runs east-west along the city's outer edge — not a natural formation but a managed one, the kind of topography that is engineered over decades by a city that has decided its borders are a security question. The vegetation on the northern slope is maintained at forty centimeters. Nothing grows taller without being cut. The cutting is automated.

Nadia lies flat at the crest and looks at what lies below.

VELTAIN is not a dramatic city. It is a careful one. The lights are evenly distributed — not the organic clustering of a place that grew, but the grid precision of a place that was designed. The compounds in the inner district are separated by service corridors that are wide enough to allow vehicle access and narrow enough to prevent assembly. The outer wall runs two kilometers along the western approach, concrete and sensor-equipped, with the sensor infrastructure mounted at intervals that reflect the threat model of a man who trusts the calculation more than the guard.

She has been reading this for four minutes.

Zara is beside her. She arrived at the ridge two minutes after Nadia — the wound, at this pace, costs approximately two minutes per kilometer. She has not said this, but Nadia has counted it.

She looks at the wall's western sector. Identifies the gap.

It is not a flaw in the design. It is a feature of an older design — a maintenance access corridor that predates the current sensor grid by eleven years. The deployment documents identified it as a structural inconsistency in the perimeter coverage: a twelve-meter span where ORACLE PRIME's fixed sensor array has a shadow, introduced when the maintenance access was cut and never reconciled with the updated grid because the gap, at twelve meters, falls below the system's threshold for flagging as a vulnerability.

Twelve meters. Enough.

She looks at the patrol interval. Marks the timing.

NADIA
(very low)
Seven minutes between passes. The access point is at the midpoint of the gap. Three minutes to cross to the wall, two to the access, two inside before the next pass clears the eastern angle.

ZARA
Seven minutes.

NADIA
We need six.

Zara looks at the wall. Looks at the timing. Runs the geometry.

ZARA
When.

NADIA
Next pass in four minutes. We move at two.

A pause. Below them, VELTAIN is quiet in the way that things are quiet when the silence is maintained rather than natural. The sensor grid hums at a frequency you cannot hear but you can infer from the behavior of everything around it — the birds don't settle near the outer wall; they have learned the hard threshold.

Zara presses two fingers against her side, below the jacket. Checks the compress. The wound from the northern corridor — left side high, dressed at the first covered position an hour ago — is stable. Not comfortable. Stable.

Nadia watches this.

NADIA (CONT'D)
(low)
How is it.

ZARA
Managed.

NADIA
That's not what I asked.

A beat.

ZARA
It will hold for what we need it to hold for.

She says it the way she states everything — flat, declarative, the report rather than the reassurance. Nadia accepts this as the data it is. She also finishes retaping the field dressing she has been tightening for the last thirty seconds — tightening it, not beginning it, which is the behavioral tell that she has been watching and managing the wound since Zara checked it and said nothing.

Zara notices this. Does not comment.

The patrol reaches the eastern angle. They watch it pass.

Two minutes.

NADIA
Your shoulder.

NADIA (CONT'D)
My shoulder has been —

She stops. Starts again.

NADIA (CONT'D)
It will hold.

She has given the same data Zara gave her. Both of them have assessed their own damage and returned the same answer. Zara looks at her.

ZARA
(very low)
After this.

NADIA
After this.

The patrol passes the maintenance access point. Continues east. At ninety seconds, it reaches the far angle of its interval and begins the return. By then, if the geometry holds, they will already be inside.

Nadia moves.

EXT. VELTAIN OUTER WALL — WESTERN SECTOR — CONTINUOUS

No sprint. The approach to the wall is controlled, calibrated — the pace that produces the least thermal signature against the ambient ground temperature at this hour. Forty-three seconds to the wall.

Zara is eight meters behind. Same pace. The two-minute gap has narrowed to ninety seconds.

They reach the wall's surface. Nadia moves along it to the maintenance access — a recessed panel in the concrete, secured with a combination lock that uses the same model as the outer transit hub from SC0081. She has the override sequence from the deployment documents.

She runs it.

The panel opens.

They go through.

INT. VELTAIN MAINTENANCE CORRIDOR — CONTINUOUS

The corridor is narrow — single file, concrete on three sides, utility conduit running overhead. The overhead lighting is emergency-level: enough to see the floor, not enough to see anything beyond three meters.

Nadia moves along it. Counts the distance.

Behind her, Zara's breathing is controlled. The wound is costing something in the narrow space — the posture the corridor requires puts pressure on the left side — but her pace does not change.

Forty meters. A junction — service access right, residential infrastructure left. The deployment documents show left leads to the inner district's maintenance layer. A grid that runs beneath the compound ring for two hundred meters before surfacing in the service corridor between the secondary residential compound and the western utility block.

Nadia goes left.

She stops.

In the corridor's silence — the faintest sound. Not a footstep. The absence of the hum she has been tracking since the ridge. The sensor grid's ambient frequency. It is gone.

Not a power failure. A scheduled cycle. The grid runs a calibration silence at fourteen-minute intervals — a brief window, not long enough to be operationally useful under normal conditions.

She knows this because the deployment documents told her. Because Marcus, forty-one weeks before he died, was thinking about exactly this corridor.

She moves through the calibration window. Reaches the surface access at the two-hundred-meter mark.

Opens it.

EXT. VELTAIN SERVICE CORRIDOR — INNER DISTRICT — PRE-DAWN

The service corridor runs between two compound walls. Overhead — the sky, just beginning. Not light yet. The suggestion of light, the kind that exists only as the absence of full dark.

Nadia looks at the corridor. Looks at the compound walls on either side.

She is inside VELTAIN.

Behind her, Zara comes up through the access and closes it quietly.

They stand in the service corridor. The city's geometry is different here — the same grid precision from the ridge, but now the grid is all around them rather than below. The walls are taller than they appeared from the approach. The sensor infrastructure that looked like a design feature from the outside is, from the inside, simply the environment.

She has been in Roman's compound twice. Not this compound — the operations center, the formal property, the one she was supposed to inhabit as his partner. Not this. This is the inner architecture. The place where the machine actually lives.

ZARA
(very low)
Which direction.

Nadia looks at the compound wall to their east. The secondary residential compound. The one the deployment documents show as the holding location for non-operational assets.

NADIA
East.

They move.


EXT. VELTAIN INNER DISTRICT — SERVICE CORRIDOR — PRE-DAWN

The service corridor runs east between the compound walls. At its far end — two hundred meters — the secondary residential compound. Its eastern face. Four stories. The lighting on this side is functional: security lamps at the roofline, angled down. Below the lamp threshold, the lower wall is in shadow.

Nadia walks east. Controlled pace. The service corridor is empty at this hour — the patrol interval she mapped from the ridge puts the nearest circuit eight minutes away.

She is counting down from eight.

She reaches the corridor's end where it meets the compound's outer service access — a setback in the wall, a maintenance recess two meters deep. She steps into it. Presses her back against the wall. The lamp above is angled past her. She is in the shadow band.

She takes the device from the medical kit.

It is not a tracker. It is a hospital ID reader — the kind used to pull a patient's registration from a passive NFC bracelet at close range. She pulled it from the cache in the outer transit hub, listed in the deployment documents' medical inventory as a standard triage aid. At clinical range — one meter — it reads the bracelet's chip with certainty. At six meters, it struggles. At twelve, it produces noise.

The compound wall is three meters away.

She turns the reader on. The indicator light is blue: scanning. She holds it toward the wall at chest height and waits.

Nothing.

She takes one step toward the wall. Two. The indicator pulses — irregular, searching. The interference from the wall is producing scatter in the read. She needs to be closer.

She looks at the corner of the service recess. The maintenance panel — the access point that brought them into the inner district — is three meters to her left. The compound's exterior patrol circuit rounds the building's northern corner and passes the access point at its midpoint. If the patrol is on schedule, she has six minutes.

She steps out of the recess. Walks directly to the compound wall.

She is eight meters from the building. The indicator pulses faster — it has found something. A weak signal, intermittent, breaking up against the wall's concrete and whatever signal management the compound's internal infrastructure produces.

She moves along the wall. North, toward the corner. The signal grows as she walks. A bracelet with a passive chip does not transmit — it responds to a reader within range. Which means the reader needs to be close to Jin.

Which means Jin is somewhere in the direction she is walking.

She counts seven paces north. The indicator changes — the pulse steadies, no longer searching. It has established a read.

She stops. Looks at the display.

The bracelet ID is there. His hospital registration number — the one she filled out herself, in the MERIN clinic, the morning she noticed the bruise on his left shin from the cot rail and asked the nurse to note it and the nurse said of course and she said thank you and she meant it and she went home and Roman was at the table having breakfast. This number. Here.

She does not move for one breath.

Then she moves.

The display gives a signal quality reading and a relative bearing. The signal is coming from inside the building, elevated — two floors above the ground level, based on the vertical attenuation. The northern end of the east wing. The deployment documents give the secondary residential compound's internal layout as four residential levels with service access at the central core. Second residential level, northern corner.

She has been studying this floor plan for three days. She knows which room is in the northern corner of the second level. She knows it has one window facing north and one facing east. She knows the east-facing window is visible from the outer service corridor on a clear line.

She knows which window is his.

She maps the bearing against the floor plan. The bearing matches. She checks it twice — not from uncertainty, from the discipline that does not allow single-point confirmation for something this consequential. The second check matches the first.

She looks up at the building.

The window is dark.

He is in there. The window is dark because it is four hours before dawn and he is asleep. He is asleep in a room with two windows. He has a caretaker — the deployment documents list a NURSE IRINA on residential duty — and he is safe in the way that things are safe when the threat has not yet moved to its final stage.

She stands in the exterior patrol circuit's sightline, eight meters from the compound wall, in the pre-dawn dark, and she knows exactly where her son is.

The indicator on the reader continues to pulse. She turns it off.

A sound — the patrol circuit. The northern corner, thirty seconds early. Her count was wrong by thirty seconds.

She moves back to the service recess. Presses into the shadow band. The patrol passes on the compound wall's other side — a guard with a flashlight that sweeps the outer face at head height, methodical, covering the lamp-shadow band. The beam reaches the maintenance recess, tracks across it, moves on.

The guard does not stop.

She waits until the footsteps recede past the service corridor's entrance. Counts twenty more seconds after that.

She moves back into the service corridor. West, back toward the staging position where Zara is waiting.

Her face gives nothing. Her pace has not changed. The device is back in the medical kit.

The only evidence of what happened is the information she is carrying — precise, confirmed, mapped against a floor plan she has memorized — and the one breath she stood still.


INT. VELTAIN STAGING POSITION — SECONDARY RESIDENTIAL MAINTENANCE LEVEL — PRE-DAWN

The maintenance level runs beneath the secondary residential compound — utility access, pipe infrastructure, emergency lighting at floor level. Low ceiling. The sound of the building above is faint but continuous: ventilation, the building's ambient mechanical life.

Nadia and Zara have been here forty minutes.

Zara is sitting against the eastern wall, her back straight, her hand at her side below the jacket. The wound from the northern corridor is stable but no longer quiet — the forty minutes of stillness has allowed the body to register what the movement suppressed. She has said nothing about this.

Nadia is at the northern access point, a maintenance hatch that opens onto the service corridor above. She has checked it twice since they came down. It is the only exit they've confirmed is clear.

She returns to the center of the room and stops.

On the floor, propped against the base of the main utility conduit — a note. Folded once along a precise horizontal crease. Her name on the outside. Not her full name. Not her married name.

NADIA VALE

She did not put it there. It was not there when they arrived.

She picks it up. Unfolds it.

The note reads:

"Ms. Vale —

I understand that you are currently positioned within the secondary residential maintenance infrastructure. I have not communicated your position to your husband, and I do not intend to do so before we have had an opportunity to speak.

I am prepared to offer you a period of uninterrupted movement — twelve hours — during which my operational parameters will not include your immediate location. In exchange, I ask only that you contact me through the frequency attached before the twelve-hour window closes.

The frequency is: 143.225.

I am a professional and I understand the pressure you are operating under. I think a conversation would be mutually productive.

With respect,
P. GANZ"

She reads it once.

She reads it again. The second reading is slower.

She hands it to Zara without comment.

Zara reads it. Her face gives nothing. She hands it back.

ZARA
(very low)
He knows we're here.

NADIA
He's known since the service corridor.

ZARA
He didn't take it to Roman.

NADIA
He's telling us he didn't.

A pause. She looks at the note. The paper is good quality — the kind you do not find in a transit supply. The handwriting is even and unhurried, each letter formed without pressure variation. The pen did not skip. He did not write this quickly. He sat somewhere and wrote it carefully.

ZARA
The offer.

NADIA
Is a capture condition. Twelve hours of movement in exchange for a contact frequency. The moment we transmit, he has a fix. He probably already has a fix on the frequency — it's a receiver, not a two-way; any signal we send confirms position.

ZARA
So the offer is nothing.

NADIA
The offer is information. He's telling us he found us here before Roman did. He's telling us he's operating independently of the hunt parameters. He's telling us he prefers to work with time on his side.

She sets the note on the floor. Folds it along its existing crease — the precise horizontal fold, not her crease, his. Sets it back against the conduit base. Exactly where she found it.

ZARA
Why put it back.

NADIA
Because he'll know whether I did.

A moment. Zara looks at her.

NADIA (CONT'D)
He wins by outlasting. Every hunter in this city has been trying to contain me — force me into a corner, reduce the geometry. He's not doing that. He's extending the geometry. He wants time. Time he can work in.

She looks at her shoulder. Not at Zara — at her own shoulder, a brief inventory check, the kind that takes one second and reveals nothing to anyone watching who doesn't know what they're looking at.

Her shoulder is worse than it was at the ridge. The approach, the compound wall run, the conduit — forty minutes of stillness has done the same thing to it that it has done to Zara's wound. The body accounting for what it has been asked to absorb.

She looks away from her shoulder.

NADIA (CONT'D)
So we take the time away from him.

ZARA
How.

NADIA
We move before he expects us to move. We move before we're ready. We don't give him the window he's building.

ZARA
We're not ready.

NADIA
No.

She looks at the hatch. Looks at Zara.

NADIA (CONT'D)
How long.

ZARA
(a beat)
Give me twenty minutes.

NADIA
You have fifteen.

Zara accepts this. Begins removing the compress from her side with the efficiency of someone who has been through this process before, in other circumstances, and knows exactly what needs to happen next.

Nadia does not watch. She goes back to the hatch and checks it for the third time. The service corridor above is clear. The patrol interval puts the next circuit in eleven minutes.

Somewhere above them, the building breathes.

The note sits on the floor, folded along its crease, waiting.


INT. VELTAIN SERVICE INFRASTRUCTURE — JUNCTION CORRIDOR — PRE-DAWN

The junction is where three service corridors meet — a cross-point in the maintenance grid, ceiling height three meters, conduit infrastructure at two. The floor is concrete. Emergency lighting at the base of each wall: enough to see silhouettes, not faces.

Nadia comes through the eastern corridor at pace. Not running — controlled movement, the kind that reads as maintenance worker until the last ten meters.

REED is at the junction's center. Piotr's advance element. He is facing north, not east. He has been watching the wrong corridor.

He turns when he hears her.

He is less prepared than she has been for this moment. She has been prepared for this moment since the staging position. The exchange is brief — four seconds, Reed going down hard against the conduit mount, not dead, and Nadia already past him, moving to the junction's north wall.

She presses her back against it. Looks at all three corridor mouths.

PIOTR steps out of the western corridor.

He does not rush. He moves at the pace of a man who has assessed the geometry and found it acceptable. He is taller than she expected — her dossier had measurements, but measurements are not presence. His presence is the absence of urgency. He looks at Reed on the floor. Looks at her.

PIOTR
(measured, unhurried)
Ms. Vale. You're earlier than I anticipated.

He stops eight meters away. The junction's geometry puts her against the north wall, him at the western mouth, Reed between them on the floor as an obstacle that serves neither of them. He will be calculating the angles. This is what he does — he calculates angles and then he waits for the best one.

She does not give him the wait.

She moves.

Not toward him — lateral, east along the north wall, forcing him to track rather than hold position. He tracks. She is reading his body as she moves: the shoulder carriage, the weight distribution, the slight forward lean that tells her he is right-hand dominant and has trained his right side to lead. The brachial plexus on the right — the nerve cluster at the junction of neck and shoulder — is the target. The strike that delivers it requires proximity she does not yet have.

He adjusts. Steps into the junction's center.

PIOTR (CONT'D)
(slightly more formal)
This isn't the most efficient —

She is already committed to the line. She drives directly at him — the one move patience cannot anticipate because patience waits for the opponent to make a tactical choice, and this is not a tactical choice, this is a removal of the space he needs to work in.

He is good. He gets his arm across in time — not to block, to redirect — and the redirect sends her left into the wall and he follows with full professional weight, landing across her right side, three ribs compressing against the concrete.

The sound is specific. She knows it by feel before she hears it.

She does not stop.

She has her left hand at his right shoulder — the right shoulder, not the left, because the right side leads and the right side is where the brachial plexus sits closest to the surface in this grip position. She has her thumb at the precise junction. She has trained this. She has the force and the angle she was trained to know would work.

She delivers it.

Piotr goes down. Not a fall — a collapse, the way the body collapses when the right motor signals fail simultaneously. His right arm is not working. The left is, but the left is slow and he is on his knees and by the time the left hand reaches for anything she is already two meters away, her back against the east wall, her right hand pressed to her own side.

She counts. Three. One is cracked through — she can feel the specific grinding quality that distinguishes a crack from a bruise. The other two are compressed, not broken. She can breathe. She cannot breathe deeply.

Piotr is on his knees on the junction floor. His right arm is at his side, non-functional. He looks at her. His face gives nothing. He does not speak.

She picks up Reed's comms unit from the floor. She looks at Piotr.

NADIA
(low, even)
The frequency in the note. Don't use it.

She means: if you contact Roman, he will know you failed. He will not deploy another asset before the compound action. He will manage this himself. Which changes everything.

Piotr understands this. He is a professional. He understands exactly what she is doing and exactly why it is correct.

He does not answer.

She goes through the northern corridor at the same controlled pace she arrived at. Her right hand stays at her side. Her breathing is short and even — the medic's breathing, the kind you learn when you are working in the field and the body cannot be allowed to fall behind the work.

She counts to herself as she walks. Not the ribs — the time. Eleven minutes to the compound's eastern service access. Zara is holding the staging position.

She walks.


INT. ORACLE PRIME BROADCAST OPERATIONS CENTER — NIGHT

The operations center is a long room — server infrastructure along the west wall, monitoring stations in a row facing the primary broadcast display. The primary display runs The Herald's feed on a three-meter screen. It is always on. It has been always on for four years.

MORROW is at the central station. Forty-seven years old, systems maintenance, the person in this building who knows what every cable does. He has been at this terminal for eleven hours. He will be here until someone tells him he can leave, which will not be tonight.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(broadcast smooth)
— and the current position of our subject places her approximately seven kilometers from the primary operational zone, which our northern grid confirms with high confidence —

The feed stutters.

Not a cut — a stutter. Half a second where the audio degrades at a frequency that is not quite silence, and the visual feed drops one frame in seven, and anyone watching closely enough will see that The Herald's mouth — the HALO UNIT's constructed face — moves slightly out of sync with the sound.

The betting interface, running in the lower third of the primary display, flickers. The numbers hold. The Herald's honesty protocol is intact — the betting data is accurate — but the interface that surrounds it is visibly unstable.

Morrow is already looking at his diagnostics panel. He has been looking at it for forty seconds, which means he saw this coming and could not prevent it.

The interference is entering from three points simultaneously: the northern grid's relay node is saturated with a signal that his spectrum analyzer cannot identify as any standard broadcast source; the eastern approach corridor's proximity sensor network is reporting position data that conflicts with the primary grid's mapping; and the base HALO UNIT feed — the Herald's primary sensory infrastructure — is experiencing packet loss at a rate that should not be possible without physical disruption to the cable plant.

He has not seen three simultaneous points before. He has not seen one that he could not trace in forty seconds.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(slight degradation — almost imperceptible)
— our subject's current trajectory suggests — our subject's current —

The feed stutters again. This time the audio cuts for three full seconds before the buffer compensates.

Then: silence.

The primary display is live but The Herald is not speaking. The HALO UNIT's face is present — the composed, pleasant construction that has been ORACLE PRIME's public interface for four years — and it is silent.

Seven seconds.

In the operations center, the silence sounds like something breaking.

Morrow pulls up the HALO UNIT maintenance interface. He has done this before — minor calibrations, feed quality checks, the routine maintenance that keeps the broadcast running at specification. He has never done it during a live broadcast. The protocol exists for scheduled maintenance windows, not for mid-broadcast intervention.

He opens the maintenance command set. Finds the override sequence: HALO-RESTORE / PRIMARY-FEED / BYPASS-ROUTING. It routes the broadcast directly through the HALO UNIT's base computational layer, bypassing the signal processing that runs through the compromised relay infrastructure.

He enters it.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(returning — almost the same)
— we apologize for the brief interruption. Our systems are performing scheduled maintenance.

It is not scheduled maintenance. The Herald knows it is not scheduled maintenance. The Herald says what its current operational parameters tell it to say, and its current operational parameters — running now through the base layer rather than the full grid, with degraded spatial data from the interference-affected relay nodes — are producing language that hedges where it would normally assert.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
It appears that our subject is currently positioned within the secondary residential district. We are confirming her exact location. Confidence is —

A pause. The Herald does not pause.

THE HERALD (V.O.) (CONT'D)
— confidence is high.

The declaration is correct. The pause before it is new. The audience — two hundred forty thousand active viewers at this hour — hears the pause. Some of them have been watching for months. None of them have heard The Herald pause before a confidence declaration.

The betting volume shifts. A small movement, not a panic. A fraction of the active positions update. The movement is in one direction: the odds on the subject surviving the current phase improve by three points in eleven seconds.

The audience is processing the pause.

Morrow watches the betting interface. He has seen the odds move in response to game events — that is the system functioning correctly. He has not seen them move in response to The Herald's voice quality.

His terminal chimes. An inbound connection request from the compound's internal communications network. He knows whose terminal that is.

He accepts the connection. Does not speak.

ROMAN (V.O.)
(over comms — measured, not raised)
What is the source.

MORROW
Three simultaneous. Northern relay saturation, eastern sensor conflict, base unit packet loss. I can't isolate any of them in real time. I've run the override to hold the primary feed.

ROMAN (V.O.)
Is the betting data intact.

MORROW
Yes. Honesty protocol is on the base layer — it's not affected by the routing.

A pause on Roman's end. The kind of pause that costs something.

ROMAN (V.O.)
How long until you can identify the source.

MORROW
The northern saturation signal — I don't recognize the encoding schema. If someone is feeding it deliberately, they've built it to look like nothing I have in the library. That takes time and access that shouldn't exist.

ROMAN (V.O.)
How long.

MORROW
Four hours to trace. Maybe less if the interference stops.

Another pause.

ROMAN (V.O.)
It won't stop.

The connection closes.

Morrow sits at his station. On the primary display, The Herald continues its broadcast — almost perfectly, the base layer holding well enough to maintain the surface. Only someone who knows the system as well as Morrow does would hear the difference. Only someone who has been watching very carefully for a very long time.

He pulls up the maintenance command log. The override entry is there, timestamped, fully documented: HALO-RESTORE / PRIMARY-FEED / BYPASS-ROUTING. Standard maintenance protocol. Emergency application.

He closes the log.


EXT./INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — OUTER PERIMETER — NIGHT

The VELTAIN compound from the outside is not a compound. It is a building in a row of buildings — a financial district address, the kind of address that costs more than most people earn in a decade. The security is invisible by design. Hilda Krast believes that visible security announces that the thing being protected is worth protecting, which tells the wrong people where to look. The security at VELTAIN is structural. It is built into the architecture itself.

Nadia is in the service lane on the compound's eastern face. She arrived twenty-two minutes ago and has been moving at the pace of a maintenance contractor — purposeful, unremarkable. The ribs tell her the pace is the correct pace. She does not argue with them.

She has Morrow's maintenance logs. Not from Morrow directly; from the documentation set that routes through the ORACLE PRIME infrastructure access layer, which she extracted three days ago and has been reading in sections ever since. The HALO UNIT service access points are documented for routine maintenance. The documentation assumes anyone reading it is a maintenance contractor who needs to know where the access panels are.

She is a maintenance contractor who needs to know where the access panels are.

The panel is at shoulder height on the eastern service wall — a brushed-metal rectangle the size of a large book, no label, the kind of panel that a person without context would not look at twice. She already knows that it does not require a biometric read. It requires a six-digit maintenance code, which rotates on a fourteen-day cycle, and which she obtained from the same documentation set.

She looks left. The patrol interval for the eastern service lane runs every eleven minutes. She arrived in minute three. She has been using minute four through eight to approach. She is in minute eight.

She enters the code.

The panel opens. Not a door — a relay access point, an interior passage the width of her shoulders that runs behind the building's outer skin and connects to the basement service corridor. It is not comfortable. It is not designed to be comfortable. It is designed for the cable plant and the maintenance techs who service it, and it accommodates them at the cost of everything else.

She moves through.

Her left hand braces against the passage wall — the right side is the side she cannot lean on; the ribs have opinions about pressure from the right. She moves at the correct pace. In the darkness of the passage, the only sound is the building's infrastructure — the ventilation, the cable conduit vibration, the low electrical hum of the security system running its continuous cycle — and, from somewhere ahead, a voice.

THE HERALD (V.O.)
(distant, through the building's internal speaker system — slightly wrong register)
It appears that our subject is currently moving through the secondary transit district, approximately four kilometers from the compound perimeter —

She stops.

She knows that voice. She has been listening to it for weeks. She knows the difference between its normal register and what she is hearing now — the 'It appears that' where it would say 'Confirmed:', the four-kilometer distance that is not her distance.

The decoy is still running.

She checks her internal count. She calculates she has between sixteen and twenty minutes before the base layer's degraded spatial data corrects far enough that the false position signal becomes unreliable. The Herald will not announce the correction; it will simply begin reporting a different location, and anyone paying close attention to the betting interface will notice the shift.

Sixteen minutes. Maybe fewer.

She moves.

The service passage opens into the basement corridor — a long, institutional space, fluorescent, the kind of corridor that exists in every large building and is never thought about by anyone who doesn't have to maintain it. Hilda Krast's architecture has cameras in the basement corridor. She knows their positions and their coverage angles. She knows that there is a section of the corridor, eleven meters long, that falls outside all coverage — a maintenance gap documented in the security audit report from four years ago, which was filed and has not been remediated.

Hilda Krast does not know Nadia has the security audit report from four years ago.

She reaches the coverage gap. Pauses. Breathes. The shallow breath of a person managing cracked ribs — controlled, deliberate, the kind of breathing that becomes automatic after enough practice. She has had enough practice.

She is inside VELTAIN.

She knows what this means. She knows that everything outside this building — the street grid, the escape routes, the theoretical possibility of retreat — is now on the other side of the architecture she just moved through. She is not outside anymore. She is in Roman's world, in its most controlled and most vulnerable configuration, and the clock that matters is the one she is already running.

Sixteen minutes. Maybe fewer.

She moves toward the interior stairs.


EXT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — PRIMARY APPROACH / NORTH GATE — NIGHT

The VELTAIN compound's primary approach is a broad paved lane between ornamental plantings — the kind of landscape design that is also perimeter control, each bed placed at the precise distance from the gate that eliminates cover. The north gate itself is steel, flush with the compound wall, a vehicle barrier embedded beneath the pavement. There are two visible cameras and one that is not visible to anyone who has not read the security infrastructure documentation.

ZARA is at the east end of the approach lane, in the shadow of the ornamental hedge line, watching the gate.

She has been watching for four minutes.

She knows the shift pattern: two guards at the gate, a third on the wall walk above, a response team of four staged at the interior checkpoint whose response time to a perimeter alert is forty seconds. She knows the camera coverage. She knows that the north gate is the approach point that Hilda Krast's architecture is most prepared for, because it is the most direct approach, and because direct approaches are what professional security forces train against.

She has chosen it because she needs Hilda to commit, not split.

She exhales once, through her nose. The sound of accepting a cost. It is the last sound she makes that is not operational.

She moves into the approach lane.

She does not move like a person who is trying to be invisible. A person trying to be invisible moves too carefully, and careful movement at the wrong pace triggers the motion sensors more reliably than ordinary movement. Zara moves like a person who is supposed to be here and has a specific destination and is going to reach it. The motion sensors read her velocity and bearing and flag her to the monitoring station. This is what she needs them to do.

The gate cameras pick her up at forty meters. She knows the moment they have her — the slight adjustment in the wall-walk guard's posture, the radio call she cannot hear, the interior checkpoint response timer that has just started.

Thirty-two seconds.

She keeps moving. She reaches into her jacket and produces the compound access card she has been carrying for six days — a card cloned from the ORACLE PRIME maintenance contractor registry, which will not open the north gate because the north gate uses a separate authentication system, which she already knew. The card is not for opening the gate. The card is for making the security team read her as a sophisticated intrusion attempt rather than a disoriented civilian, which determines whether they call Hilda directly or route through the duty supervisor.

They call Hilda directly.

The north gate opens — not to admit her; the vehicle barrier rises as a tactical measure, because a lowered barrier is a ramming hazard, which is standard protocol for a credentialed intrusion attempt at the primary approach. Zara notes this and adjusts her line, coming at the gate from a slight angle that keeps her out of the vehicle barrier's operational arc.

The four-person response team comes through the inner door at a run. Professional, spread formation, not shouting. Hilda Krast is three steps behind them.

Hilda is fifty-one years old. She moves at the pace of a person who does not need to run because she has already calculated the geometry and found it in her favor. She surveys the approach lane — Zara, the card, the angle of approach, the absence of any secondary actor at the perimeter.

A beat.

HILDA
(to her team, not to Zara)
Hold.

The team holds. Zara stops walking.

They assess each other across twelve meters of ornamental paving.

HILDA (CONT'D)
You drew us here.

Not a question. Not an accusation. A statement of the operational fact, delivered in the register of a professional who has identified the mechanism and is now working out what the mechanism was for. Her eyes move — not to the north gate, but to her left. East. The service corridor.

Zara says nothing.

Hilda's eyes come back to her.

HILDA (CONT'D)
(to team)
East service corridor. Now.

Two of the four break. They are professionals; they move fast. But they will not reach the service corridor before Nadia reaches the basement. The gap is the gap. The gap has always been the gap.

The remaining two approach Zara. She does not move. She does not assist them, but she does not resist in a way that requires force — that would take time, create injury, complicate everything downstream. She lets them take her arms. Professional custody. Hilda watches.

HILDA
(to Zara directly, for the first time)
Was it worth it?

ZARA
(a beat — not performance; she is genuinely considering)
Ask me after.

Hilda looks at her. Then: something in Hilda's expression that is not sympathy and is not contempt. It is the specific expression of a professional who has just encountered someone whose operational logic she does not fully understand and knows she will not understand tonight.

HILDA
(to team)
Take her inside.

Zara is walked through the north gate.

She does not look back at the approach lane. She does not calculate the distance Nadia has covered in the last three minutes. She has stopped calculating. She has made the decision she was always going to make once she understood that the debt was never going to be paid by calculation — that the only move left was the one that had a cost she couldn't first reduce to an acceptable number.

She is inside. The north gate closes behind her.

Somewhere on the east face of the compound, in the service passage that leads to the basement corridor, a clock is running. Thirteen minutes.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — SERVICE CORRIDOR / EAST FACE — CONTINUOUS

A maintenance passage: concrete walls, overhead conduit, a line of work-light panels at half-power. The passage smells of hydraulic compound and recycled air. It is not a space that appears in the broadcast's visual palette — too utilitarian, too empty of the aesthetic register The Herald uses to frame the game.

NADIA is moving through it at the speed of someone who has calculated exactly how fast she can move without tripping the vibration sensors embedded in the floor joints. She knows the sensors' threshold because she spent four minutes watching Morrow's maintenance crew work this passage six days ago, before Roman's people moved her to the ZORAL CORRIDOR. She filed it.

She has filed everything.

Forty meters ahead, at the junction where the service corridor opens into the east equipment room, a HALO UNIT is positioned against the left wall. Its optical arrays are tracking her — have been tracking her since she entered the passage — with the smooth, unhurried precision of a system that does not need to hurry because it has never lost anyone.

THE HERALD
(voice from the HALO UNIT; warm, audience-directed; she is its subject and its product simultaneously)
— and we're watching something quite remarkable here, folks. She came through the north gate's shadow in under four minutes from the perimeter alert, which tells you what kind of patience we're dealing with. Now she's moving east — and I want to draw your attention to the betting line, because—

Nadia stops. Thirty-eight meters from the unit.

Not close enough to reach it. Close enough for the maintenance channel.

She produces the device she has been carrying since the day she watched Morrow's hands. Morrow typed a six-character alphanumeric in a specific sequence — she clocked it from eleven meters in poor light; she typed it back into her own memory three times that night to make sure the index was stable. She has not had occasion to use it until this moment. The override command requires proximity to the unit's maintenance receiver — within forty meters.

Thirty-eight.

She enters the sequence.

THE HERALD (CONT'D)
— if you look at the odds right now, you can see the sympathy coefficient has been climbing all—

The voice stops.

Not at the end of a sentence. Not at a natural pause. Mid-clause: the word all and then nothing.

The HALO UNIT's optical arrays do not dim gradually. They go from active to standby in a single step — the specific visual quality of a system that has been interrupted rather than shut down. Its broadcast hardware is offline. Its movement capability remains; it can still track her optically; it just cannot transmit.

The service corridor is very quiet.

ORACLE PRIME PLATFORM INTERFACE — FLASH:

[BROADCAST INTERRUPTED — TECHNICAL MAINTENANCE — RESUMING SHORTLY]

The betting line freezes at the moment of cut.

Nadia looks at the unit for one full beat — not with triumph; with the specific quality of attention she gives to any system she has just proved she understands better than its builders assumed. The silence has a texture she has not experienced since the moment before the game began.

She is not being watched.

She starts counting. Under her breath, barely audible, her lips forming numbers: one, two—

She moves.

Eight minutes before Roman's technical team restores the feed. She knows this because Morrow's maintenance logs, which she also memorized, noted a restoration test time of seven minutes forty seconds for a full override recovery. She has rounded up.

The HALO UNIT tracks her optical silhouette — silent, recording nothing, unable to do the one thing it was built to do — as she passes it without breaking stride and turns east toward the interior door.

Eight minutes.

She is counting.


INT. ORACLE PRIME PLATFORM — SUBSCRIBER FEED — CONTINUOUS

ORACLE PRIME PLATFORM INTERFACE:

[BROADCAST INTERRUPTED — TECHNICAL MAINTENANCE — RESUMING SHORTLY]

The betting line is frozen at the moment of Nadia's entry into the service corridor. The last reported odds hang on the interface like a sentence left unfinished. The Herald's feed — which has not been silent since the game opened — is a blank rectangle at the center of the platform's display architecture.

In the chat streams that border the main feed, the audience is producing language at the speed of people who have lost the thing that was organizing their attention.

Some of them are furious. They have money on the line and the line is frozen and the machine has never frozen before, not in any of the previous events, not once.

Some of them have gone quiet in a way that is different from the furious quiet. They are waiting to see what they feel.

CUT TO:

INT. KESTON LALE'S RESIDENCE — CONTINUOUS

A private viewing room: one wall given over to a subscription terminal, a leather chair positioned at the precise distance that the display renders best. The room is dark. It has been dark for hours.

KESTON LALE, 44, watches the blank feed.

He is not furious. He placed his first bet in the third hour of the first day — thirty credits on Nadia not making it out of the ZORAL CORRIDOR. She made it out. He placed seventeen more bets across twelve days; his net position as of the betting line freeze is forty-three credits ahead.

He is forty-three credits ahead and he is watching a blank screen and his face has the specific quality of a person who has been waiting for permission to stop.

The blank screen is not permission. It is something worse: it is an interruption, which means the machine can be interrupted, which means it was always a machine rather than a fact.

He has known this. He has known this for some time. He placed bets anyway.

On the outer tier of the platform — the subscriber feed that runs alongside the main broadcast for high-tier members — a notification propagates. Not from The Herald. From an anonymous document-distribution address that has been seeding the outer tier for six hours with small pieces of what looks, at first, like archive material.

It is not archive material.

Keston clicks the notification. He starts reading.

CUT TO:

INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — CONTROL ROOM — CONTINUOUS

ROMAN is standing at the monitoring station when the duty technician reports the feed failure. He listens to the technician's summary — forty-three seconds; override event on the maintenance channel; source of override still being traced — without any visible change in expression.

Then:

ROMAN
Get it back.

The technician moves. Roman watches the blank feed on the control room's wall display — the same blank rectangle the audience is watching, from the inside.

He is not thinking about who triggered the override, not yet. He is thinking about the audience. The audience is his architecture of consequence: as long as they are watching, the event's logic holds. As long as the event's logic holds, his liability framework holds. Without the broadcast, the event is not an event — it is a private act with private consequences, and private consequences are the kind that regulators can see.

He needs the feed restored in under eight minutes. He knows this from the override protocol documentation, which he wrote.

He does not think about what else the eight minutes might be doing.

CUT TO:

INT. SERA'S WORKSPACE — A RENTED OFFICE NEAR VELTAIN STATION — CONTINUOUS

SERA is watching three screens simultaneously. The left screen is a real-time propagation tracker she built in a hotel room in MERIN three weeks ago. The middle screen is the ORACLE PRIME outer-tier feed. The right screen is a draft document that has been open for eleven days and is forty pages long.

The propagation tracker shows a cascade.

SERA
(to herself; fast, under her breath; confirming)
It's moving — okay — it's moving—

She opens a notebook that has been sitting closed on the desk — something she put down when the broadcast first went dark — and starts writing in it. The notebook is already full of previous entries. She is starting a new page.

The automated release she built into her document-distribution address had one trigger condition: a blackout event on the ORACLE PRIME platform lasting more than thirty seconds. The condition has been met. The documents are moving through the outer tier — not all forty pages, not yet; the first release is a selection: the financial records, the platform's liability framework in Roman's own handwriting, the list of previous events with their dates and participant counts and outcomes.

Outcomes meaning: what happened to every person who was put into the game before Nadia.

The outer tier is receiving this. The outer tier has approximately sixteen thousand subscribers who are not the betting audience — they are the peripheral audience, the watchers, the people who pay for access to the feed but do not bet. They are less monitored. They are more likely to share.

Sera watches the propagation counter.

SERA (CONT'D)
(writing, not looking up)
Who else knows about this. Right.

She writes the question in the notebook and underlines it. Then she looks at the propagation counter and writes the number down.

CUT TO:

INT. ORACLE PRIME PLATFORM — SUBSCRIBER FEED — MOMENTS LATER

ORACLE PRIME PLATFORM INTERFACE:

[BROADCAST RESUMING — PLEASE STAND BY]

The Herald's voice returns — warm, composed, unhurried; as if it had simply stepped away for a moment rather than been interrupted mid-clause by a command it was not designed to refuse.

THE HERALD
(V.O.)
— and we're back. Technical interruption — brief, as promised. The event continues, and the current position—

The betting line unfreezes. The odds recalibrate.

On the outer tier, the document-distribution notifications are still propagating. The moderation system that The Herald's active broadcast maintained — which kept the outer tier's notification feeds filtered by content category — took forty-three seconds to restore alongside the broadcast. In those forty-three seconds, the documents moved.

The Herald resumes its commentary. Its voice is exactly what it was before — warm, precise, audience-oriented. It does not know what happened in the forty-three seconds. It was not designed to know what happened when it was not speaking.

CUT TO:

INT. KESTON LALE'S RESIDENCE — CONTINUOUS

Keston is still reading.

The Herald's voice has returned through his terminal's speakers. He has not looked up from the document.


INT. DIMITRI'S OPERATIONAL OFFICE — FINANCIAL DISTRICT, VELTAIN — NIGHT

A rented floor in a building that belongs to a legal entity that belongs to a holding structure that Dimitri has been constructing, with precision and patience, for three years. The office is functionally bare: two workstations, a secure line, a window overlooking the financial district's nightlit skyline. No decoration. This is not a place Dimitri works — it is a place Dimitri prepared.

Two of Dimitri's people are at the workstations. They know what they are doing. They were briefed last week, in segments, so that no one person has the full picture. That is how Dimitri has always operated, even inside Roman's organization. Especially inside Roman's organization.

DIMITRI stands at the window.

He checks his watch.

The gesture is unhurried. It is a confirmation, not an anxious tic — he has calculated exactly how long the broadcast outage will last (Roman's override restoration protocol: eight minutes; Dimitri has read that documentation too), and he has calculated how long his lockdown sequence will take (four minutes, thirty seconds), and the arithmetic is clear. He is inside the window. He has been inside the window for forty seconds.

DIMITRI
(to the room; flat; unhurried)
Proceed.

One of his people enters the second authorization credential — a seventeen-digit code that should exist only on Roman's secure device. It has existed on Dimitri's secondary system for eleven months. A maintenance access during a hardware audit; Dimitri was present; the technician did not ask why the second-in-command needed to verify the hardware's credential storage. No one asked Dimitri questions he hadn't already anticipated.

FINANCIAL TRANSFER DISPLAY — DIMITRI'S WORKSTATION:

[AUTHORIZATION SEQUENCE COMPLETE — EXTERNAL ASSET TRANSFER PROTOCOL ENGAGED]

The ORACLE PRIME external financial infrastructure — the betting receipt processor, the three hunter payment accounts, the operational capital reserve, the network's regulatory buffer — transfers to Dimitri's secondary authorization. It takes eleven seconds.

Dimitri checks his watch again. Exactly on schedule.

DIMITRI (CONT'D)
Confirm.

DIMITRI'S OPERATIVE
Confirmed. All four external accounts. The capital reserve shows a hold flag — Roman's contingency lock — but the hold is administrative only; it requires a thirty-six-hour clearance period. We have the assets. He has the flag.

DIMITRI
Leave the flag.

He already knew about the flag. Roman built in the administrative hold as a dead-man mechanism — a thirty-six-hour brake on any unauthorized transfer of the reserve. Dimitri does not need the reserve transferred. He needs it frozen under his authorization, which is different. Roman cannot access it. Roman cannot release it. The flag does not help Roman.

His phone rings. He looks at the screen. He knows who it is.

He answers it.

CUT TO:

INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — CONTROL ROOM — CONTINUOUS

ROMAN has the financial intelligence on the wall display. He has been looking at it for twenty-two seconds — long enough to understand exactly what Dimitri has done and exactly how he did it.

He is on the phone.

ROMAN
(precise, without inflection; not a threat; a statement of the situation)
You have the external accounts. You don't have the compound. You don't have the technical infrastructure. You don't have the broadcast. What you have is four accounts that process receipts and a reserve with a thirty-six-hour hold. I can work around those in twenty minutes. The offer is: you release the reserve flag and take a formal partnership position in the post-event restructuring. You'll have more in six months than you have now.

A beat.

DIMITRI (V.O.)
(flat; no pause; he has been waiting fifteen years for this sentence)
You should have ended it when I told you to.

The call ends.

CUT TO:

INT. DIMITRI'S OPERATIONAL OFFICE — CONTINUOUS

Dimitri places the first phone on the desk. He picks up the second.

He dials. Waits one ring.

DIMITRI
(into second phone)
It's done. Move to phase two.

He hangs up the second phone. He looks out the window at the financial district's skyline — the same skyline Roman's compound overlooks from a different angle.

He checks his watch. He is on schedule.

CUT TO:

INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — CONTROL ROOM — CONTINUOUS

Roman is looking at the financial intelligence display.

He does not move immediately. He gives the situation one full beat — not hesitation; assessment. He has three active crises and he has been resolving them in the wrong order, and he knows this now, and he is recalibrating.

He turns to his team.

ROMAN
Dimitri's team will be in the financial district. Find them. And tell security: we have a second active breach.

He does not raise his voice. He does not need to.

For the first time in the film, Roman is responding to conditions he did not create.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — SERVICE CORRIDOR — CONTINUOUS

Six minutes, forty seconds since the override.

NADIA is moving at the speed she has been calculating since the moment the broadcast went dark: not the fastest she can move, which would be too loud, but the fastest she can move quietly, which is something she worked out during military service and has not forgotten. The service corridor has not changed since she entered it. The HALO UNIT at the junction stands inert, optical arrays tracking her passage, transmitting nothing.

She keeps count without conscious attention, the way her body keeps heartbeat. Six forty-two. Six forty-three.

The left side is the problem. The wound from MERIN — closed by Tobias's sutures first, re-torn in the ZORAL CORRIDOR, currently held by four strips of closure tape she applied herself in a bathroom in MERIN three days ago — is pulling with every step that requires lateral extension. She has adjusted her stride to minimize the extension without reducing speed. The adjustment is not visible unless someone is looking for it. She has been making this adjustment for seventy-two hours.

She reads her own body the way she would read a patient: systematic, without sentiment. The MERIN wound: managed. Right hand, knuckles: not functionally limiting. Dehydration: present; not yet critical. Hunger: well past the point of discomfort; she has stopped feeling it, which is itself a symptom. Sleep: she has not had more than ninety minutes consecutively in four days. Her hands are steadier than they have any right to be. She knows why: proprioception improves under adrenaline-mediated sympathetic activation. She knows exactly how long that improvement lasts.

She turns left at the junction. Zone 1 ahead.

INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — EAST EQUIPMENT ROOM — CONTINUOUS

The east equipment room is a climate-control and power distribution node — ceiling-mounted hardware, floor conduit, two access panels. It has a security checkpoint at the entry door: a manned station, normally. Currently: empty. The officer's terminal is still active; the coup alert is scrolling across it. She reads it in passing without slowing: SECOND ACTIVE BREACH — ALL AVAILABLE PERSONNEL. The personnel responded. The checkpoint is the gap.

Zone 1: clear. Seven seconds. She is through.

The next door — interior access to the main building's lower level — is across a short connecting passage. Twenty meters. One more security station. This one is manned.

She stops at the equipment room's far wall and looks.

The officer at station is forty meters away, in the connecting passage, facing the interior access door. They have a sidearm, a communications piece in their ear, and a handheld terminal that is displaying the same coup alert. Their weight is shifted slightly to the left. Their shoulder tension reads as high — they have been receiving conflicting instructions for the last several minutes and have not yet been told which one takes priority.

Nadia reads this in the time it takes the officer to glance at their terminal.

She waits.

The officer's head turns toward the terminal. She moves.

Seven seconds. Measured, controlled, on the left side of the connecting passage where the overhead conduit provides a shadow line. The officer's head is still down when she reaches the far wall of the passage. She flattens against it. The interior access door is three meters to her right.

The officer looks up. The connecting passage is empty in the direction they check.

Zone 2: through.

INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — INTERIOR ACCESS PASSAGE — CONTINUOUS

She sits down.

Not a decision — a body decision that arrived before a conscious one. She is against the wall, weight off, head forward, eyes open and fixed on the floor. The specific quality of the floor: grey composite tile, slightly scuffed near the door frame. She looks at it with her full attention.

Vasovagal. Not cardiac. The distinction matters and she knows it immediately. Her heart rate had spiked in the Zone 2 crossing and the blood pressure drop that follows a sustained sympathetic peak has arrived on schedule. Her field medicine training names it: a pre-syncopal event, manageable, not a crisis. The intervention is simple: positional correction, controlled breathing, four seconds. After four seconds the peripheral vascular resistance will partially restore and she will be able to stand without a position-change collapse.

She breathes. One cycle. Her eyes stay open.

She counts the seconds that she cannot count toward the override window.

Four.

She gets up. Nothing in her movement shows the four seconds just happened.

The interior access door has a credential lock — a separate system from the service corridor's maintenance channel. The same device she used at the HALO UNIT has a secondary command sequence for access credential systems on the VELTAIN compound network; she extracted this from the same maintenance documentation where she found the override command, six days ago, from eleven meters, in poor light, from Morrow's hands.

She enters the sequence. The device sends. The lock considers it for twelve seconds — the longest twelve seconds she has experienced since she watched Tobias start the suture in MERIN — and then the indicator light shifts from red to amber.

Not green. Amber.

Amber means: partial authorization. The door will open. It will log the access under a maintenance exception code, which will eventually flag for review. Not tonight. Tonight, amber is enough.

The door opens.

INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — BUILDING INTERIOR — CONTINUOUS

She steps through. The door closes behind her with the specific sound of a well-machined seal engaging — solid, definitive, the acoustic signature of a threshold crossed.

The noise of the compound's exterior is muffled. The security response still ongoing outside is on the other side of two sealed doors. In here: the ambient sound of a climate-controlled private building at night — a hum, the low register of ventilation, the absence of any other person in immediate range.

She is inside.

Seven minutes, nineteen seconds.

The override window has forty-one seconds remaining. She does not need them.

She checks the closure tape on her left side. Two of the four strips are peeling at the edge. She presses them back with her thumb, firmly, without looking down. Her eyes are already reading the corridor ahead.

Interior focus.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — UPPER CORRIDOR — NIGHT

The upper level of Roman's building is not the operational level — no server rooms, no security stations, no broadcast infrastructure. It is residential in scale: carpeted, climate-controlled, the ambient temperature of a room that exists to be comfortable. Nadia's footsteps are quieter here than they have been anywhere in the building.

She finds the door Marcus described. Third on the left from the elevator landing. Unmarked. A standard interior lock — residential, not security-grade. Roman did not lock this room because he did not expect anyone to find it who did not already know what was in it.

She opens it.

INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — THE TROPHY ROOM — CONTINUOUS

Silence first. The specific quality of a sealed room — no ventilation noise, no ambient hum, just the presence of air that has been still for a long time.

She steps in and stops.

The room is approximately four meters by five. Three walls are fitted with glass-fronted display cases, floor to ceiling, the kind used in private museums — dust-controlled, humidity-managed, lit from within by narrow strip lighting that casts each case's contents in a careful, even glow. The fourth wall holds a single flat panel displaying a formatted document.

She reads the panel first.

FORMATTED DOCUMENT — WALL PANEL:

[EVENT LOG — ORACLE PRIME PRIVATE OPERATIONS — EVENTS 1 THROUGH 14]

Fourteen events. Dates spanning nine years. Each entry: an event designation, a location code, a duration in hours and days, and a single-word outcome field. The outcome field for every entry — all fourteen — reads: CLOSED.

She knows what closed means. She has known since Marcus's package. But knowing and seeing are different processes, and she gives herself the two seconds it takes to convert the knowledge into the specific weight of confirmed fact.

Fourteen events. Fourteen outcomes.

She turns to the cases.

The cases contain personal effects. Not weapons, not evidence in any forensic sense — objects that were on people when they stopped being people the game needed to track. A pair of reading glasses, one lens cracked. A child's drawing, folded in quarters, the paper yellowed. A wedding ring in a small labeled tray. A hotel room key card from a city that no longer uses key cards. A medical bracelet — not Jin's; an older model; someone else's. A watch, stopped.

The objects are arranged with care. Each has a small label: event number, date. No names. Roman did not keep their names. He kept their things.

She reads the cases the way she reads the room: systematic. She is looking for Marcus's reference point. In his intelligence package — assembled over two years of working inside Roman's outer network — he described a specific object he had confirmed was in this room. He had not been here himself. He had the description from an intermediary who had been here once, years ago, and who had since disappeared.

She finds it in the third case from the left.

A small analog clock. The kind that used to sit on a desk. Its face is printed with the name of a media company that no longer exists — the first target organization Roman dismantled before he moved to private individuals. The clock's hands are stopped at 11:43. Marcus noted the stopped time in his package without comment. He had no reason to comment. Neither does she.

She has her confirmation.

She stands still for a moment in this room that has held fourteen endings. Not long — the clock in her mind, the one she has been running since the service corridor, is still counting. Roman's technical team will be reconfiguring the security response. Every minute she spends standing is a minute she does not have.

But she stays for one full beat, because the room requires it. Because it would be wrong to be in this room and not register what it is.

Fourteen people who did not come back.

She is the fifteenth.

She turns to the fourth case — positioned slightly apart from the others, at the far end of the room, facing the door as if Roman placed it to be found last by anyone who got this far. Which no one ever did.

The case contains a single item: a sealed data card in a clear holder. Small, black, unremarkable. The card's label reads: SYSTEM TERMINATION — ORACLE PRIME BROADCAST NETWORK — AUTHORIZED ADMINISTRATOR USE ONLY.

The case's latch has a factory seal. It is intact. The seal has never been broken.

She looks at it for the length of one breath.

She breaks the seal and opens the case.

The card is in her hand.

She looks at it — small, light, ordinary. The kind of thing that should not be able to do what it will do. Marcus had described it in his package based on the same intermediary's account. He had written: "If it exists, it will be in the room. If you reach the room, you already know what to do with it."

She puts the card in her jacket pocket.

She does not look at the room again as she leaves.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — BROADCAST TERMINAL ROOM — NIGHT

A functional room on Roman's private level: two broadcast infrastructure terminals against the far wall, a monitoring display above them showing the ORACLE PRIME platform's current status — The Herald's feed restored and running, the betting line active, the system presenting as intact. Between the door and the terminals, a distance of approximately six meters.

ROMAN is at the monitoring display when Nadia enters.

He turns. He takes her in — the closure tape on her left side, the state of her hands, the absence of any visible weapon, the specific quality of her posture that is not the posture he married. He takes all of this in, and the taking-in is visible only as a brief pause before he speaks. Roman does not show surprise. He shows adjustment.

ROMAN
(measured; the full weight of eleven days finding its register)
You've survived longer than I projected. That's not a criticism. It's an acknowledgment that my model required revision.

Nadia moves into the room. Not toward him. Toward the terminals.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
The game's infrastructure is designed to reach a natural terminus. What you're experiencing as an ending of your making — it isn't. The system closes events. It has closed thirteen before this one. The terminus is built in.

She is reading the terminals as she moves. The broadcast infrastructure terminal is the left-hand unit — she knows this from Marcus's package; he had the schematics; she memorized them. The card reader is at the terminal's base.

She is four meters away.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
(reframing; his voice does not change register; this is still a conversation he believes he is setting the terms of)
I want to tell you something about what happens next, in the interest of accurate information. The game's outcome does not require your death. It requires the game's conclusion. Those are separable terms. I've separated them before.

Three meters.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
Jin is in the building.

She stops. One step — her stride has a natural period and she stops in the middle of it, foot not yet down, and she places it carefully and is still.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
(reading her with the precision he uses for all assets)
He's well. He's been here since the fourth day. I relocated him from the external facility because the facility's security became a liability. He is two floors below us. He is not — he has not been harmed.

A beat.

NADIA
Where.

ROMAN
That's the offer. You stop what you came here to do — and I know what you came here to do; you've been in the room — and I tell you where he is, and the game closes, and you both leave. That's the actual terminus. The one that's available tonight.

She turns toward the terminal.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
Nadia.

The first time he has said her name in this scene. His voice on it does not change — still measured — but the name is a different register than asset pricing and he knows it.

She inserts the card.

BROADCAST INFRASTRUCTURE TERMINAL — STATUS DISPLAY:

[ADMINISTRATOR CARD ACCEPTED — INITIATING SYSTEM TERMINATION PROTOCOL]

The terminal does not alarm. It acknowledges. A quiet confirmation tone — the sound of a system accepting a valid command — and then the status display on the monitoring screen above shifts: the ORACLE PRIME platform feed flickers; the betting line freezes; The Herald's voice cuts to silence mid-sentence for the second time tonight, but this time the silence is different; this time the system is not being interrupted; it is being ended.

Roman watches this.

His face: the specific expression of a man who has priced everything incorrectly and knows in this moment exactly which variable he failed to account for — not her capability; not her intelligence; not her physical endurance. Her refusal to be priced at all. He built a system that converts people into assets and prices. She never became either.

He moves.

Not toward her — toward the door. He is going to the technical control room. He knows the shutdown sequence has a terminal stage that requires physical insertion at the server core; the card has begun the process but has not completed it. There is still a window. This is Roman: he is not fleeing; he is redirecting to the correct operational response.

He passes her on the way to the door. Two meters between them. Neither of them moves toward the other.

At the door:

ROMAN
(without turning back; precise; something that is neither threat nor concession but the last honest accounting between them)
You won't be able to find him without me.

He leaves.

Nadia is alone with the terminal. The monitoring display shows the shutdown sequence's progress — a percentage indicator that is climbing — and the ORACLE PRIME platform fragmenting in real time as the backend begins its collapse.

She pulls the card from the terminal. She needs it for the server core.

She looks at the monitoring display for one second. The Herald's silence is total. The betting line is gone. Fourteen events' worth of infrastructure beginning to close.

She turns toward the door Roman used.

She is going to find Jin.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — TECHNICAL CONTROL ROOM — NIGHT

The technical control room is the compound's operational core: server racks on two walls, a monitoring station that spans the third, four workstations currently staffed. The room has the specific texture of a space designed for sustained attention — low ambient lighting, bright screens, the hum of climate-controlled hardware. ROMAN's technical team has been here since the broadcast override began. They have not stopped working.

ROMAN enters. He looks at the monitoring station's main display — the ORACLE PRIME platform status, currently showing the shutdown sequence's progress alongside the auxiliary routing status his lead technician has already begun constructing.

LEAD TECHNICIAN
The backend shutdown is running. The card's authorization level is administrator-class — it's executing a full network termination. We can't stop the sequence from here; the server core would need a physical interrupt.

ROMAN
Auxiliary routing.

LEAD TECHNICIAN
Already running. We can maintain the broadcast feed through the auxiliary systems — it bypasses the terminating backend. The Herald stays up. The betting interface stays up.

ROMAN
Show me the feed.

The monitoring station's display splits: left panel shows the ORACLE PRIME platform as the audience sees it — The Herald's feed, restored, active; right panel shows the backend data layer — the content the system is routing through the auxiliary channel.

The right panel is not running betting odds and position data.

ROMAN (CONT'D)
(flat; not inflected as a question)
What is that.

LEAD TECHNICIAN
The auxiliary routing is pulling from the outer-tier content channel. The outer tier has — there's been an unmoderated content propagation event in the last twelve minutes. The moderation layer was down during the override, and—

ROMAN
How much of it.

LEAD TECHNICIAN
Enough that the auxiliary feed is — the Herald is running it. It's reading the content as verified platform data because the outer tier's authentication tokens are valid. We can't filter it at the broadcast layer without taking the feed down again.

ORACLE PRIME PLATFORM MONITORING DISPLAY:

[THE HERALD — BROADCAST ACTIVE — AUXILIARY ROUTING — DATA INTEGRITY: COMPROMISED]

Roman watches the left panel. The Herald's voice is audible through the monitoring station's speakers — warm, composed, precisely the persona he designed, precisely the register he calibrated to make the machine feel like a service. The Herald is presenting the content it has been routed: financial records, event outcome logs, liability documentation. It is applying its full broadcast warmth to evidence of what it has been broadcasting for nine years.

It does not know what it is saying. It was designed to trust its data source and deliver. It is doing exactly that.

Roman watches this for five seconds.

His sentences, when they come, are shorter than they have been at any prior point tonight.

ROMAN
Can you isolate the data stream.

LEAD TECHNICIAN
Not without—

ROMAN
The feed. Can you isolate the Herald's feed from the data layer and run it on a clean loop.

LEAD TECHNICIAN
If we loop the feed it won't be live. The audience will know within—

ROMAN
How long before they know.

LEAD TECHNICIAN
(a pause; this is the honest answer)
They already know. The outer-tier material has been running for forty seconds. The audience is watching The Herald read — they're watching it read the outcomes list.

Roman's eyes stay on the monitoring screen. The Herald continues. It does not pause; it does not stumble; it applies its designed warmth to each item in the outcomes list with the same professional engagement it would apply to a betting odds update.

ROMAN
(to the room; not to any person)
Get her out of the building.

A beat.

LEAD TECHNICIAN
Security is currently—

ROMAN
I know where security is.

He does. He is managing the north gate breach, the financial coup, the compound's second active breach, and the broadcast simultaneously, and he is managing all of them from here and none of them well. He chose this room. He chose it because the broadcast is what he built his identity around and the broadcast was what was failing and the spectacle instinct is older and deeper than the survival instinct and he could not help it.

He looks at the monitoring screens: the ORACLE PRIME platform fragmenting in real time on his left, the financial intelligence display showing Dimitri's coup's ongoing second phase on his right, the compound security schematic in the top right corner showing Nadia's last confirmed position as the interior access point she came through eighteen minutes ago.

He does not know where she is now.

ORACLE PRIME PLATFORM MONITORING DISPLAY:

[THE HERALD — BROADCAST ACTIVE — EVENT 15 — PARTICIPANT STATUS: UNLOCATED]

The Herald continues. Nadia's position indicator in the broadcast interface is showing her as UNLOCATED — the HALO UNIT she disabled in the service corridor is still offline; the override window has expired but the unit has not re-established its position feed. The broadcast system does not know where she is either.

Roman is the fourteenth event's architect and the fifteenth event's failure and he is standing in the room where his machine is broadcasting the proof of both, and there is nothing here that will help him reach her before she reaches the server core.

He turns back to his technical team.

ROMAN
(precise; the last operational frame he has available)
Keep the feed running. Whatever it takes.

He is still Roman. He is just Roman in a room where the spectacle has stopped serving him and he cannot stop tending to it.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — INNER CORRIDOR — CONTINUOUS

She has been descending.

From the trophy room — upper level — through the broadcast terminal room — private level — and now through the inner corridor below it, where the building's architecture changes: the carpeted residential register of the upper levels gives way to something more functional, more secure. Composite flooring again. The climate-control hum at a slightly different frequency, the signature of server-grade cooling rather than residential comfort.

NADIA moves through the corridor at the speed she has been maintaining since she entered the building — fast, quiet, calibrated. Her left side is the problem. It is always the problem. She has stopped monitoring it consciously; the adjustment has become part of her movement. This is either adaptation or the specific kind of numbness that follows sustained injury past a threshold she does not want to calculate.

The corridor runs thirty meters before it reaches the security station outside the server core level's antechamber.

She stops at twenty meters.

The security station is unmanned.

She reads this with the same attention she gave the empty Zone 1 checkpoint in SC0098: not relief, not haste — assessment. An occupied station has visual tells of sustained presence: the specific chair position of a person who has been sitting for hours, the accumulated items on the desk surface, the orientation of the monitoring terminal toward where the operator's eyes would naturally settle. This station has none of those tells. The chair is pushed back at an angle that means the person stood quickly. The monitoring terminal is still live. On the desk's edge, a paper cup — the kind from a facility dispenser, not personal equipment.

She walks to the station.

She places her palm against the paper cup.

Warm. Not hot — the coffee, or whatever it is, was poured ten minutes ago at most and has been cooling since. The person who left it stood and walked away inside the last ten minutes. They did not finish it. They did not take it.

The coup recall.

She does not know Dimitri's name in connection with this specific gap. She knows the gap exists; she knows its likely duration; she knows that a recall event with this profile — all personal detail, immediate departure — comes from a higher authority than compound security and addresses a threat that Roman has assessed as more urgent than her. She knows this tells her something about the state of Roman's position.

She files it and moves.

The antechamber door is three meters past the security station.

It stands open. Not ajar — open. The recalled detail pushed through it in a direction that left it standing wide. The antechamber beyond is lit: overhead panels, functional lighting, the specific visual register of a room that is always on.

She steps through.

INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — SERVER CORE ANTECHAMBER — CONTINUOUS

The antechamber is a transition space: eight meters square, storage on two walls, the server core's main door on the far wall with its physical credential lock, a secondary door to the left leading to Roman's private retreat — the room below the broadcast terminal room, the room at the building's center.

The secondary door is not fully closed.

Through the gap: light. The specific quality of a room in use.

She stays at the antechamber's entrance. She reads the geometry — the server core door to the right, credential lock intact and active; the secondary door to the left, open a few centimeters, light visible, the faint sound of something she cannot yet identify.

She has come for the server core. The server core is to her right.

Roman is to her left.

She looks at both doors for one full second. Not deciding — confirming a decision already made in the trophy room, where she read fourteen closed events and understood that this ending would be made entirely of her own choices, without a path to follow, without anyone who had done this before.

She moves toward the server core door.

Behind her, from the secondary door, a sound she can now identify: the specific cadence of a man walking from one side of a room to the other, back and forth, the behavioral tell of a person who is thinking and cannot be still. Roman. Pacing in his retreat, the way he probably paced in the years before he built a machine that converted his pacing into architecture.

She does not look back.

She is at the server core door.

The card is in her hand.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — SERVER CORE ANTECHAMBER — CONTINUOUS

The credential lock is a circular reader set into the server core door's frame at chest height — the kind of hardware that is not networked, not remotely addressable, designed to operate independently of the systems it protects. Physical. Dedicated. The one component of Roman's machine built to resist everything except the card.

She has the card.

She places it against the reader. Not inserted — contact first, the way she memorized from Morrow's documentation: present the card to the reader's surface, wait for the orientation indicator, align, insert. She has not run this in a controlled environment. She has run it fourteen times in the last three days in her memory, on the walk through checkpoints she had not yet reached, in the eight seconds between Zone 2 and Zone 3, in the trophy room while she was reading closed event files. The sequence is precise and she has it precisely.

The orientation indicator appears: a small amber light at the reader's top edge.

She aligns.

She inserts.

SERVER CORE CREDENTIAL LOCK:
ADMINISTRATOR AUTHORIZATION — ACTIVE
ORACLE PRIME SHUTDOWN SEQUENCE: INITIALIZED

The door does not open. It was never going to open. The card's function is not entry.

She steps back from the reader.

Through the server core door and through the antechamber walls — everywhere, because this is what proximity to the server core sounds like — the facility-grade cooling at operating pitch, the composite hum of infrastructure at full load. She has been hearing it since she moved through the security station. It has been the room's continuous register. She is hearing it now.

Then something changes.

Not silence — not yet. The cooling continues. The composite continues. But a frequency that was present in the building's operating sound drops out: a load that was running stops carrying. The change is specific enough that she can locate it in the spectrum of what she has been hearing.

She knows what ORACLE PRIME sounds like at full operation. She has been in its proximity for weeks. She knows what this particular frequency means.

ORACLE PRIME BROADCAST ARCHITECTURE
GRACEFUL HALT IN PROGRESS — CONSTITUENT SYSTEMS TERMINATING
ESTIMATED COMPLETION: 00:43

From the broadcast terminal room two levels above: The Herald completes its current sentence. The machine was designed for this — graceful halt preserves current-sentence completion to avoid mid-broadcast interrupt artifacts. The warm register finishes what it started. The calibrated empathy runs to the period. Then it does not begin the next one.

The system sheds load in sequence. Outer-ring thermal management first. Processing units next. Storage arrays. The broadcast synthesis cores last — the components that make The Herald sound like it means what it says. Each one drops off in the order the documentation specified. She timed this sequence from Morrow's notes. Forty-three seconds from authorization to full halt.

She does not count.

She knows when it is done.

The sound stops.

Not a reduction. Not a wind-down toward silence. The specific composite register of ORACLE PRIME's infrastructure — everything that has been underneath Roman's operation since before this compound had a name for what it was building — stops. What remains is the building: climate control, structure, the ordinary ambient of a facility that is large and full of edges she has not yet reached.

Through the secondary door to her left — the door that is not fully closed, the door with the light — the pacing stops.

Roman heard it.

She stands in the antechamber with the card in her hand and the machine finished and the silence where the machine was.

She does not look at the credential reader.

She does not confirm what the display says. She was there. She knows what happened.

Jin is in the building.

She has, she estimates, six minutes before the compound's emergency protocols cycle to a lockdown state that will change the lower-level geometry in ways she has not fully mapped. She made this estimate before she entered the compound. She is making it again now — with the machine gone and Roman in the room to her left who has just heard the machine go and six minutes as the operative constraint.

She turns toward the antechamber's outer door.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — ANTECHAMBER CORRIDOR — CONTINUOUS

She is three steps from the outer door when the secondary door opens.

Roman does not appear. He was not hiding. The door opens and he is already moving — not erupting from the room, not charging: moving with the specific economy of a person who decided several seconds ago what the next action was going to be and is now executing it. He heard the shutdown sequence initiate. He has had forty-three seconds.

He knows where the walls are. He knows the corridor width, the ceiling height, the door frame clearance, the one uneven seam in the floor six feet from the server core entry. He has walked this space for eleven years.

She has been in it for eight minutes.

The first exchange is fast and incomplete. She reads his line and adjusts — not fully, the vasovagal debt catches up in the pivot, she is a quarter-second behind where the drill says to be. The deflection is partial. His forearm catches her jaw instead of her temple. It is not the intended hit. It is still hard.

She takes it.

She gives back a palm strike to the sternum — controlled, targeted at the xiphoid, calibrated to stun rather than damage the cardiac. He takes it in the chest wall instead, his rotation off. The stun does not land. The force does.

Both of them reset.

He is faster in this space than she expected. She made an estimate of him based on the broadcast footage, the documented history of the events, the physical profile in Morrow's files. The estimate was accurate. It was not complete. What the files did not have: the way he moves when no one is watching, when there is no audience for it, when the only function of the movement is to end this.

He is better without the camera than with it.

He catches her on the second approach — a controlled grab, corridor geometry used precisely, her trajectory constrained by the wall behind her before she can establish a counter-line. His grip on her left arm is mechanical, practiced, the kind of hold that is maintained by leverage not strength. She needs two moves to break it. She gets one.

He uses the partial break. Her left side opens. He drives his elbow into her ribs — not a swing, a deliberate placement, weight transferred through the joint: a close-range impact that doesn't read as dramatic and lands at maximum yield.

She hears the creak.

Not break. Creak. Two, possibly three ribs under acute compression. She has three seconds before the pain response arrives — trained for this, she uses the three seconds. She drives her knee into his thigh at the femoral nerve cluster, misses center, catches the margin. He staggers.

The pain arrives.

She breathes in. The rib cost is immediate and specific: the left side of her thorax compresses on the inhale, the capacity on that side is reduced by a fraction she can measure. She has had worse. She has not had this at the end of what she has already done today.

She is still standing. She is still functional. The margin is narrower than it was.

Across the corridor, Roman is straightening.

He is not done. He is breathing carefully — the sternum impact has left something. Not the intended effect. Enough.

He looks at her the way she has not seen him look at anything: without the register in place, without the calibration. Just assessment. Just this room and what is in it.

She looks back.

The building is quiet. The machine is gone and the building is quiet and there is nothing between them except the corridor and the decision she made in the trophy room and whatever it costs to keep it.

She adjusts her weight off the left side.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — ANTECHAMBER CORRIDOR — CONTINUOUS

She is adjusted to her left-side deficit. He is watching how she is adjusted to it.

He comes in lower on the third approach — below the sternum contact she landed in SC0104, inside the deflection range her left arm can produce with compromised leverage. He is learning her compensation in real time. He has been in physical confrontations before. He has not been in confrontations with people who fight the way she fights, but he can read the movement and he is updating.

He uses the floor seam.

She knows it is there — he told her it was there in SC0102 when he mapped the corridor's geometry eleven years of muscle memory at a time. What she does not have is the exact position in this low light. He does. He drives her back toward it on a line that is not the shortest path to the server core wall — it is the path that ends at the seam.

She catches it on the outer edge of her right foot. Not a fall. A stagger. A quarter-second of weight displacement she cannot use.

He uses the quarter-second.

The door frame of his retreat catches her right shoulder. Not thrown — she is managed into it, the geometry doing the work. He is not wasting energy on force. He is spending effort on precision, the same way she has been, except he has the map and she is learning the map as the fight erases the options one by one.

Her back is to the server core door.

Her left arm is not reliably functional — the rib injury has shortened the arc of every movement on that side, and he has been methodically narrowing what the right arm can reach. The breathing cost is now operating-expense rather than overhead: every inhale is a decision with a price, and the prices are accumulating.

He has not hit her again in the last forty seconds. He does not need to. He is running out the clock on her margins.

She has no room to establish a counter-line. The geometry is closed.

Here is what she knows about carotid sinus pressure: the bifurcation of the common carotid artery, where the baroreceptors concentrate, sits two centimeters below the angle of the jaw on both sides. Bilateral sustained pressure triggers a reflex response that the autonomic nervous system cannot override — heart rate drops, blood pressure drops, the body's own threat-response shuts down the threat. A military medic learns this in the context of what not to do to a patient in shock. She learned what it does. She has been aware since the fight began that it was the one move available to her from maximum proximity with minimum arm clearance.

She stopped running from maximum proximity four exchanges ago.

She closes distance.

He does not expect it. She has been managing space, extending range, trying to recover room. The shift from retreat to approach takes a half-second he has not allocated — he was not watching for her to come toward him.

Both thumbs, at the bifurcation. She knows the location with the precision she knows every anatomical landmark she was trained to find fast in field conditions, on strangers, in the dark. His neck.

He tries to pull back. The distance is already closed.

She applies. Sustained. Both sides. The pressure is specific and deliberate — not a choke, not a strike: a bilateral hold targeting the baroreceptor reflex, maintained with whatever her arms have left.

Four seconds. He is still standing, his hands trying to find purchase, his body not yet understanding what is being asked of it.

Six seconds. His body understands.

Seven.

He goes down the way vasovagal response takes a person — not a fall, not a collapse, a controlled exit of the legs from load-bearing status. She goes with him, one knee on the corridor floor, because she does not have the margin to release cleanly and step back. She releases.

She tries to stand.

Her left side is settled into a specific, narrow, consuming pain — not acute anymore, categorical. She knows the difference between injury that prevents function and injury that taxes it. This is taxation at a rate she has not been charged before. She gets to one knee. She gives herself the count of three.

At three she stands.

Roman is on the corridor floor. Breathing — she can see the chest moving from here, the way she has been trained to see it from a distance in low light without equipment. He is not confirmed as to what comes next. The film does not resolve this here. She is not standing here long enough for resolution.

Jin is in the building.

She is standing. She moves.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — ANTECHAMBER CORRIDOR — CONTINUOUS

She is standing.

The corridor is quiet in a way it has not been since she entered the building — the machine gone, the fight over, the ambient that remains is the building's own: climate control, structure, the unremarkable sounds of a compound that is large and continues to be large regardless of what has happened in one of its corridors.

Her left side is a categorical fact. She is not managing it — she is not not-managing it. It is simply the current condition of the left side of her body, and she is standing, and the building is quiet.

Roman is on the floor to her left. She does not look at him. She confirmed his breathing from standing before she moved. That confirmation has not changed. She does not need to update it.

She gives herself three seconds.

This is a deliberate allocation — not collapse, not recovery, not the functional count she ran before standing. She is not counting toward anything. She is standing in a corridor in the VELTAIN compound with a rib injury and an exertion debt she will be paying for the next three days, and she is giving herself three seconds in which she has already survived and has not yet begun the next thing. Three seconds in which both of those things are true at once.

She does not think about the machine.

She does not think about Roman.

She does not think about the credential reader still displaying ADMINISTRATOR AUTHORIZATION: ACTIVE on its small amber display three meters to her right, because the display no longer matters and her attention is no longer required there.

She thinks about Jin.

Not the plan — not the compound level, the route, the remaining minutes on the lockdown clock. Not the operational shape of the next forty minutes. She thinks about Jin the way she has been thinking about Jin since before any of this had a shape: the specific geography of him. The scar at the left ear. The way he counts things he is not supposed to be counting. The numbers that are his.

Three seconds.

At the end of the three seconds she does not mark the moment. There is nothing to mark. The three seconds were hers and they are complete and the next thing is to move.

She turns toward the antechamber outer door.

She does not look back at the corridor. She does not look back at Roman on the floor or the credential reader or the server core door with the card still in its lock. She is looking at the outer door and at what is past it.

She moves.


INT. JOINT LEGAL OPERATIONS CENTER — EXTERIOR JURISDICTION — DAY

The room is not dramatic. It is a room with six workstations, three monitors at the far wall showing simultaneous filing queues across three separate jurisdictions, and the specific ambient of a space where the work has been continuous for eighteen hours and the people doing it have not eaten recently.

Okafor is at the center station. She has been here for eleven of the eighteen hours — the other seven she was in transit from the prior jurisdiction, running the filing coordination from a secure line in a car. She does not appear to have noticed the difference.

Chen Mei crosses the room. She sets a sealed data envelope on the workstation — the encrypted transfer of Dimitri's financial ledger, the working copy Chen Mei has been carrying for six weeks since it came out of the intelligence chain. Okafor does not look up. She opens the transfer verification, confirms the hash against the registered source document from the original intelligence package, and enters the authorization.

The ledger is in the system.

MULTI-JURISDICTION SEIZURE ORDER: SUBMISSION CONFIRMED
FILING JURISDICTIONS: PRAXIS AUTHORITY / OUTER VALE COMPACT / TERTIAN REGULATORY BOARD
ASSET CATEGORIES: BROADCAST INFRASTRUCTURE / FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS / OPERATIONAL REAL ESTATE
SUBMISSION TIMESTAMP: 14:07:33

Okafor types. The room's six workstations continue their individual tasks — the filing queue is not a single action, it is a cascade of ninety-four individual submissions that have to arrive within a forty-minute window to prevent sequential injection attacks by Roman's legal team.

They have been inside the window since 13:43.

Chen Mei takes a position to Okafor's left. She does not sit. She watches the filing queue move.

Okafor pulls the Sera Mast publication timestamp from the reference archive — the outer-tier broadcast, the 43-second window from the moderation gap in SC0096, the content that reached 16,000 subscribers before The Herald's auxiliary routing could touch it. The story ran. Outside jurisdictions received the material. The Outer Vale Compact's legal basis for acting was established before Roman's network had finished restoring its broadcast feed. The story is not injunctable — it has been in circulation for nineteen hours.

The cascade reaches seventy-eight submissions. Eighty-one. Eighty-seven.

A notification arrives from the court registry. It is Wren's motion — a multi-jurisdiction injunction filing, comprehensive, well-constructed, precisely targeted at the legal mechanisms Okafor has been deploying. It is the motion they expected. It would have worked two hours ago.

CASS WREN / VELTAIN LEGAL GROUP — INJUNCTION FILING
MOTION: STAY OF SEIZURE PROCEEDINGS, MULTI-JURISDICTION
FILING TIMESTAMP: 14:48:17

The cascade reaches ninety-four.

Okafor reads the first line of Wren's motion. She reads it the way she reads everything — fully, once, without annotation. She sets the document down.

"File the next tranche."

She is not speaking to Chen Mei. She is speaking to the room. One of the six workstations acknowledges and begins the second filing sequence.

Chen Mei does not say anything. She watches the confirmation count on the primary monitor. The first seizure order acknowledgments are already returning — not all of them, not yet, the processes in different jurisdictions operate at different speeds and some of what Okafor filed will not be processed until tomorrow. But enough are back to confirm that the threshold has been crossed: the filing has landed, it has been received by systems that Roman's infrastructure cannot reach, and Wren's injunction motion is forty-one minutes behind what it was trying to stop.

Criminal infrastructure. Legal collapse initiated.

The room continues to work.

What is not happening yet: any criminal charges. Any forfeitures. Any trials. The legal process that starts here will take years — assets frozen, not yet touched; participants named, not yet tried; documentation in three separate jurisdiction archives where it cannot be withdrawn or suppressed, but also cannot be acted on quickly. What Okafor filed today is the initiation. Nothing more and nothing less.

She is already in the next file.

Chen Mei watches the acknowledgment count reach the threshold. She does not mark it. She does not say anything. This is what the last eighteen months of work looks like when it resolves.

She pulls up a chair. She is going to be here for the next tranche.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — INTERNAL CORRIDOR / SERVICE DESCENT — CONTINUOUS

She is already moving.

The compound's lockdown is Dimitri's coup protocol — automated, not human, triggered when the financial seizure went active. She knew this from the documentation: the protocol was designed for a specific threat model (external intervention, not internal) and it sequences doors in a predictable order. The documentation was from Morrow. She read it in the trophy room while she was looking at the closed event files. She has the sequence.

First tier: main entry and broadcast levels. Sealed. Second tier: administrative and server core access. Sealed — she came through the gap before it closed. Third tier: residential and compound level access. Thirty-seven minutes from trigger to full seal.

The trigger was 13:41.

She has been in the building for forty-one minutes.

She is four minutes behind the seal on the third-tier doors. There is one route through — the service descent, a stairwell that runs parallel to the administrative shaft, rated for maintenance use only, not on the automated protocol because it was not on the original floor plan submitted to the authority that approved Dimitri's lockdown specification. Morrow noted the omission in a marginal comment dated fourteen months ago.

She has been moving toward it since she left the antechamber.

The bracelet reader has been giving her intermittent signal in the upper corridors. The signal is a passive ID chip — the hospital bracelet she registered Jin with at eight weeks, the one he was wearing when they took him. The chip does not transmit; it reflects. To read it she needs line of sight through no more than three intervening surfaces with a signal density below a specific threshold.

In the upper corridors, there are too many intervening surfaces. The signal comes in fragments.

In the service descent stairwell, which runs along the compound's eastern structural shaft, there are two intervening surfaces between the reader and compound level B.

The signal changes.

PASSIVE ID: VALE, JIN — COMPOUND LEVEL B
BEARING 247° — SIGNAL STRENGTH: STRONG
LAST CONFIRMED: 00:04:12 AGO

She stops walking for one second.

The signal is not Jin. She knows this — the chip does not give temperature or movement or any of the things she wants to know. It gives location. It gives bearing. It gives strength, which is a proxy for proximity and intervening material, not for safety.

The signal is strong. The bearing is specific. He is sixty-three meters below her and eleven meters to the southwest, which places him in compound level B's eastern residential section, which she has in the floor plan, which she can reach through this stairwell in four minutes at her current pace.

She does not stop again.

The service descent door at the bottom landing is mid-state — resting against the frame, no current through the electromagnetic lock. Someone was in the middle of closing it when the coup alert recalled them. She can see the small indicator light on the lock housing showing no active current: amber, not red. Not sealed.

She pushes it open.

The corridor to compound level B is ahead of her. The signal is strong. The distance is known. She has four minutes of margin before the tier-three seal completes and she is past the last door she needs before the seal matters.

She moves.


INT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — COMPOUND LEVEL B, EASTERN RESIDENTIAL ROOM — CONTINUOUS

The room is small and warm and lit by a lamp that someone chose for its quality of light rather than its output — a care choice, not a facility choice. There is a crib against the far wall. There is a chair beside it. There is Nurse Irina, who has been in this room for eleven days and who is standing now with her hands at her sides because she heard the building change an hour ago and she has been waiting to understand what that meant.

She understands it now.

Nadia is in the doorway. She is wearing what she has been wearing through the compound. Her left side is compensating for something. Her face is the face of a person who has arrived at the end of a very long and costly distance.

Nurse Irina steps back. She does not reach for anything. She does not say anything. She moves away from the crib and toward the wall and she stays there.

Jin is awake.

He is eight months old and he does not know what has happened. He does not know that the building around him has been a controlled environment inside a predator machine, or that the machine is gone, or that the woman in the doorway has been moving toward this room since before he was taken. He is eight months old. He is looking at the ceiling fan, which he has been looking at with interest since it was first switched on six days ago. It is his current object of attention.

Nadia crosses the room.

She does not rush. She has been running on emergency reserve for forty-one minutes and she does not need to run now. She walks to the crib and she looks at him for one second — the specific inventory she has been carrying: the scar at the left ear (birth mark, crescent-shaped, three millimeters); the fingers already curled around nothing in the habitual grip she knows. He is unchanged. He is exactly himself.

She picks him up.

He startles slightly at the transfer — the shift from surface to held — and then settles. He is not distressed. He does not know her from any other person who has held him in this room. He does not know he should be relieved. He settles because being held is a known condition and she is holding him with the specific competence of a person who knows how he settles.

On his wrist: the hospital bracelet. The white band with the small dark reader chip she tracked across three security zones and two levels of a locked-down building. It is on him. It was always on him.

She does not look at it long.

Nurse Irina, from the wall: "He's been fed. An hour ago."

Nadia does not respond to this with words. She nods once — acknowledgment of information, not dismissal of the person who gave it. It is the kind of nod that says: I heard you. I am registering the practical content of what you said. Thank you.

She holds him.

Her left side is what it is. The rib injury is categorical and has been categorical since the antechamber corridor and it will remain categorical for the foreseeable future. She is holding her baby and her left side is what it is and both of those things are true at the same time in this small warm room and neither of them is the story she will tell later, if she tells one. The story she will tell later is the one that starts: I went to get him and I got him.

The ceiling fan turns.

Jin looks at it.


INT./EXT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — HOLDING AREA / EXTERIOR — DAY

Guard Pike has been at this post for four years and four months. He has a routine. The routine involves a radio check at the top of every hour and a logbook entry at the bottom and the knowledge that the authority behind his position is continuous and funded and not going away.

At 14:32, his radio stops responding.

Not static — silence. The channel is open and nothing is coming through it and the nothing is a different quality from the nothing that would mean the radio needs a battery change. He knows the difference. He has been a guard for four years and four months.

He looks at the radio. He does not look at the door to the holding room.

He is still looking at the radio when the door opens.

Zara has been in this room for eleven days. She has been in rooms like this — bounded, watched, the air quality of authority over her — for long enough that she can read the acoustic change in a building with precision. The compound changed register an hour ago: the broadcast hum stopped, the security alert pattern shifted from rotating to static, and the guard outside her door has been on his radio at intervals that are no longer routine. She has been ready for this since the first change in the building's sound.

The door is not locked.

She noticed it was not locked fourteen minutes ago, when the magnetic seal's cycling sound — which she had been tracking since they put her here — stopped cycling and did not resume. She waited fourteen minutes. She wanted to understand what she was walking into.

She understands it now.

Guard Pike is standing at his post. His radio is silent in his hand. He is a person whose obligation was to an authority that no longer has the infrastructure to sustain it — the network that paid him, validated his access credentials, and defined his function has been legally seized and structurally dismantled in the last forty-seven minutes. He does not know the full scale of this. He knows enough.

He does not stop her.

He does not look at her as she passes him. He is still looking at the radio. This is not cowardice — it is a person doing the specific arithmetic of his situation in real time and reaching the correct conclusion that what he is holding is not a valid instrument of an authority that currently exists.

Zara walks past him.

The compound's exterior is in transition: two vehicles from the outer authority at the perimeter approach road, not yet inside, their lights visible through the tree line. The law-enforcement response to a compound of this designation takes time to mobilize and she has a window. She has been calculating the window since the building changed.

She moves through the compound's exterior without running. Running is a signal; she does not need to be a signal. She has the bearing of a person who knows exactly where she is going and is not asking permission to go there.

The network's leverage over Lena's situation died with the network. The debt instrument Roman's machine used to ensure Zara's compliance — the exposure it held, the threat it maintained over her family — is in a frozen asset registry in three separate legal jurisdictions. It cannot be exercised. It cannot be transferred. It does not exist anymore as a functional threat.

Lena does not know this yet.

Zara is going to tell her.

She reaches the perimeter's unmanned section — the service road access that has not been staffed since the security recall — and she does not slow down at it. She passes through the gap and she is in the city and the city is beginning to understand what is happening to the compound she just left.

She does not look back.

She is moving toward Lena. She is not there yet. She will be.


INT./EXT. VELTAIN COMPOUND — SERVICE CORRIDOR / PERIMETER / CITY EDGE — CONTINUOUS

She is already moving when we meet her here.

Jin is against her right hip — shifted from the left before she was out of the room. The ribs on the left side do not permit proximity to load-bearing positions. He is six kilograms heavier than she planned for. Not a problem. A variable.

He is watching the ceiling over her shoulder. She does not explain motion to him. She has been preparing him for motion since the room — her hand pressure, the quality of her voice, the specific pace of transition. He accepts it. His weight settles against her.

---

The service corridor runs sixty meters before it branches. Zara's notation is on the branching pipe — a smear of yellow chalk at shoulder height, barely visible, pointing right. Not a mark that reads as a mark. Reads as a scuff, a maintenance record, an old paint transfer. She turns right.

Through the window at the junction: two law-enforcement vehicles on the main approach road, a third behind them. Converging on the primary entrance. The primary entrance is not her entrance. She keeps her pace.

The pace is this: not running. Not stopping. Not because she does not want to run — because the ribs will not allow it, not carrying this weight, not at this stage of the calculation. The pace is what remains when you subtract what you cannot afford. It is enough. She has run the arithmetic on it. It is enough.

---

VEHICLE: GRAY COMPACT / SERVICE LOT NW / WHEEL WELL RR / KEY: ALPHA

---

The vehicle is where Zara said it would be.

Service-road parking, northwest corner, invisible from the primary entrance and from the response corridor. She presses the key. The lock opens. Jin looks at the door handle with the attentiveness of someone tracking a new thing. She opens it. She puts him in the rear seat with the same specific pressure and transition quality she has been using since the room. He does not protest. She closes the door with care.

She drives at the speed limit.

---

The compound's service road ends where VELTAIN's perimeter becomes street. A junction. Traffic light. Red.

She waits.

The light changes. She turns left. In the mirror, the compound's fence line recedes. Behind it, somewhere, the response vehicles are completing their convergence on a building that no longer contains what they came for.

She is not in their geography.

---

Jin is watching traffic through the rear window. A bus. A pedestrian. Ordinary motion. He tracks it with the specific attention of someone for whom ordinary motion is interesting and legible. She does not look back at him. She knows he is watching. The bracelet is on his wrist.

Left side. Protest. She does not answer it.

She is moving. She has the variable. She is not stopping.


INT. JOINT LEGAL OPERATIONS CENTER — AFTERNOON

Three jurisdiction displays. Seventeen monitors. The room has been running since 13:41.

---

The asset freeze cascade executes in order: first jurisdiction at 15:17:44, second at 15:22:09. Between them, a notification arrives from Cass Wren's office — emergency motion to stay the freeze on jurisdictional grounds, filed at 15:19:32. Chen Mei reads the timestamp. The second jurisdiction's execution confirmation is already on screen. She sets the notification in the incoming file.

The third jurisdiction executes at 15:24:33.

ASSET FREEZE CONFIRMED / JURISDICTIONS 1–3 / ACCOUNTS: 847 / EXECUTED 15:17–15:24

Chen Mei notes the count. Closes the window. Opens the next submission queue.

---

There is a pattern to Wren's filings — they are precisely calibrated to the moment before each action, and they are arriving precisely after each action. Forty-one minutes behind at the initial submission cascade. Forty-two seconds behind the second jurisdiction freeze. The timing is not coincidence. Someone is feeding her the schedule on a delay. She is operating on the wrong clock.

She has been operating on the wrong clock since 14:07.

---

At 15:31, Chen Mei reads from a tablet. Sets it down. Slides it to Okafor.

Okafor reads the entry. It is brief. It is a booking record — name, case number, time of detention: VAROV, DIMITRI. Below it, as the record updates in real time, a custody transfer notation and a docket number.

BOOKING RECORD: VAROV, DIMITRI A. / CASE NO. 2026-CR-4471 / DETAINED 15:28:19 / CUSTODY TRANSFER CONFIRMED

Okafor sets the tablet down.

The ledger that bears Dimitri's name, in his own encryption and under his own key, is now case exhibit A-1 across all three jurisdictions. His effort to protect himself with documentation became the document that ends the protection.

---

The ORACLE PRIME server farm forensic access order is executed at 15:39:22. Herald node access: terminated. Forensic imaging: initiated. The broadcast infrastructure — transmitters, relay nodes, the distribution architecture Sera activated for 43 seconds — enters the chain of custody.

At 15:44:16, a communication arrives from Wren's office. Emergency application for injunctive relief re: the server seizure, forensic access violation, chain of custody challenge. Received. Filed. Entered into the administrative record.

The court clerk's reply returns at 15:46:03: application denied; forensic access order was issued under court authorization 2026-WR-887; imaging is proceeding under warrant; the application has been entered and will be heard at the scheduled docket review.

Wren's application will be heard. In approximately four months. The imaging will be complete in approximately six hours.

---

By 16:00, eleven arrests are confirmed. The public criminal docket in jurisdiction one shows seven names, two with prior records that cross-reference the ledger. Three names are not yet public. Proceedings are underway.

Chen Mei pulls up the next tranche — the secondary node list, forty-three submissions in preparation, secondary jurisdiction leads.

Okafor looks at the room. The monitors. The submission count. Eleven arrests, 847 accounts, one platform seized, three jurisdictions active. He does not look at this as an achievement. He looks at it as a beginning.

"This is the start of a long process," he says. Not to anyone. "File the next tranche."

Chen Mei files the next tranche.


THE HERALD (V.O.)
—probability of concurrent regulatory action across all three active jurisdictions has been recalibrated to ninety-four point

---

INT. [HERALD BROADCAST FEED — TRANSMISSION SPACE] — 15:51:08

The signal terminates.

Not a shutdown sequence. Not a graceful halt. The forensic access handover, initiated at 15:39:22, reached the broadcast carrier layer at 15:51:08 — a maintenance architecture pathway, the same pathway that had been used once before for forty-three seconds in a different context and for a different purpose. The carrier release is instantaneous. The sentence in progress at the moment of release is abandoned at the word "point."

THE HERALD will not complete it.

---

The frequency remains. The transmitter remains. The infrastructure — server farm, relay nodes, distribution architecture — remains and is now evidence. What does not remain is the signal.

The Herald was a voice. It told true things in the service of arrangements that required them to be told a certain way, at a certain volume, by a machine that could not be accused of bias because it was a machine. It did this for four years, two months, and eleven days. It never misspoke. It never hesitated. It never refused.

It was mid-sentence when the carrier released.

---

BROADCAST FEED: CARRIER SIGNAL ABSENT / LAST TRANSMISSION LOGGED 15:51:07 / DURATION: 4Y 2M 11D

---

The silence is not dramatic. It is the specific kind of silence that follows a voice that has been constant long enough to become part of the frequency of the room. The rooms it was in continue. The people who heard it continue. The sentence that was in progress at 15:51:08 does not.

There is no final word. There is a final syllable — "point" — and then the frequency carries nothing.


EXT./INT. CITY STREETS — MOVING VEHICLE — LATE AFTERNOON

The city is doing what the city does.

A fruit stand at the corner of a block she does not know. A man walking a dog that is walking him. Two children at a crosswalk, one pointing at something above her eyeline — a bird, a window, a cloud. The traffic light turns green. She drives.

Jin is watching all of it. He has been watching since the service road. His attention moves from the fruit stand to the dog to the children to the signal ahead, tracking each thing fully before moving to the next. He does not comment. He does not need to. The world outside the window is sufficient and he is in it.

---

She breathes through the left side carefully. Not avoiding the breath — the breath will happen regardless — but managing the geometry of it, keeping her spine in the position that asks least of the ribs. She learned this position in the third block. She has been in it for seventeen blocks.

Jin looks at her once — briefly, not searchingly — and looks back at the window.

---

Ahead, a law enforcement vehicle coming the other way. Moving at pace. Moving toward VELTAIN, not from it. She does not adjust her speed. She watches it in the mirror after it passes: it does not brake, does not turn, does not look for her. It has somewhere to be and she is not it.

She releases a breath she did not know she was holding.

The geometry of the breath costs her. She adjusts her spine. She drives.

---

The city continues: a café putting out chairs for an hour of remaining light; a woman reading on a bench who does not look up; a delivery vehicle double-parked in the right lane that everyone is navigating around with the specific patience of people who have been doing this their whole lives. The world does not know what is ending in the building she left. The world is eating, walking, reading, complaining about double-parked vehicles.

She is in the world.

She has not been in the world — not like this, not as a person moving through it without a controlled system around her — in longer than she can measure from inside a car.

---

The extraction point is a parking structure three blocks north of the city's secondary transit hub. Level two, northeast corner, space marked with a yellow painted curb that Zara had noted would be empty by 16:00 on any weekday because the meter expires and the attendant does not repaint until Thursday.

Today is Wednesday.

She pulls in. Level two. Northeast corner. The space is empty.

She turns off the engine.

Outside, the city. Jin looks at the parking structure's ceiling — the specific geometry of it, the light through the ventilation slats, the pattern. He is interested in the pattern.

She does not move for a moment.

Then she does.


EXT./INT. PARKING STRUCTURE / TRANSIT HUB — CONTINUOUS

She is on her feet with Jin against her right side when she sees it.

The street-level exit — northeast, the one the route requires — has a cordon. Two vehicles, incident tape, two officers managing a situation that has nothing to do with her. A collision or a medical event or a dispute, something the city generates routinely and manages without any awareness that it is standing between her and the next point. The officers are not looking for her. They are looking at whatever happened fifty meters to the left.

She reads it in under five seconds.

---

The transit hub is directly ahead. Secondary hub, seventeen gates, one main concourse. She has not been inside it. She does not need to have been inside it. She knows where it opens on the other side.

She adjusts Jin to her right hip — the familiar geometry — and walks into the transit hub.

---

The concourse is occupied: commuters, a school group moving in pieces, a man reading at a bench, two people consulting a map at the center pillar, a vendor selling something from a cart that smells of sugar and oil. The noise is substantial. Jin presses his face into her shoulder — not distressed, calibrating; he is managing the input the way he manages new input, by reducing his visual field to the one surface he can control. She puts her hand against the back of his head. Not to reassure him. To reduce the surface further. He settles.

She walks through the concourse at the pace of people who are late for something ordinary. She is indistinguishable from them. A woman with a child in a transit hub in a city in the afternoon — there is nothing to see. The cover is the city at ordinary function and she is using it.

The ribs itemize every step. She does not stop counting the gates.

---

Twelve gates. The north exit. A set of doors that open onto a plaza she has not seen but which is, by her calculation, two blocks from the contact point.

She pushes through the doors.

---

The plaza. Open air. The contact point is at the southeast corner — a specific bench, a specific arrangement. She can see it from here. A person sitting at it, reading. Not looking up.

Not looking up yet.

She checks the time. The contact window was ten minutes. She has three remaining.

She walks toward the bench. The contact looks up.


EXT. PLAZA — LATE AFTERNOON

The contact exchange takes forty seconds. She does not watch the contact leave.

---

She is standing in the plaza with Jin against her right side and the sky above her and no next objective between her and the horizon. The contact has confirmed the route. There is a vehicle waiting two streets over. She knows where it is. She is going to walk to it.

She does not walk to it yet.

The air outside is different from the air inside. This is a fact about temperature and humidity and the specific properties of outdoor afternoon light in a city that is continuing its day. She notices it the way you notice a fact.

She does not let the notice become anything larger.

---

Jin looks up.

He has been looking at walls and ceilings and windows and the back of her shoulder for hours. He has been in enclosed spaces — the warm room, the corridor, the vehicle, the transit hub — and now the space above him has no ceiling. He looks at it. The light is different. The sky has the specific quality of late afternoon, going toward gold, going toward the longer shadows.

He looks at it for a while.

She lets him look.

---

She adjusts his weight — familiar geometry, right hip, left side managed — and begins walking toward the vehicle two streets over.

This adjustment is the same as every adjustment she has made since the room where she found him. The motion is identical. The rib is identical. The weight is identical.

The reason is different.

She is not managing toward the next obstacle. She is carrying him through open air in a city that does not know her name, toward a vehicle that will take them somewhere that is not VELTAIN.

What comes after that has not been solved. She is not solving it yet. She is walking.

---

Two streets. The vehicle. She opens the rear door and puts Jin in and closes it with care and gets in the front and does not look back at the plaza.

The future is not resolved. The ribs are not resolved. What she is is: outside. Moving. With him.

She drives.


INT. RECOVERY ROOM — LATE AFTERNOON

A table. Two chairs. A window with institutional blinds. Tobias Orell sits in one chair with a tray of instruments beside him — gauze, a penlight, two sealed packets — arranged with excessive precision. He has been arranging them since they brought him in. He does not comment on this.

He does not look injured. He looks tired and irritated in the specific way of someone who has been tired and irritated for a long time and has learned to use it as a primary facial expression.

Okafor sits across from him with a notepad and does not open it.

---

OKAFOR
The team confirmed you were held for eleven days. Compound level B.

TOBIAS
I know how long I was held.

OKAFOR
Medical assessment—

TOBIAS
I did my own. I'm fine. Relatively. That's a qualified fine — not a blanket fine. The left shoulder is—

He stops. Moves a packet of gauze three millimeters to the left.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
I'll write it up.

---

A pause. Okafor does not push. Tobias looks at the window, not through it — at the angle of the blinds, the geometry of the slats.

OKAFOR
We'll need to discuss what you witnessed. During the eleven days. There's a legal proceeding—

TOBIAS
I know what's happening. I follow the news. I followed the news from a room with no windows, which is a specific kind of following, but the information reached me.

OKAFOR
Then you understand that your testimony—

TOBIAS
I won't testify.

He says it flat. Not angry. Flat. He adjusts the penlight so it is parallel to the gauze.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
I went underground because I didn't want to be in a room answering questions with my name attached to it. That's still true. The situation around it has changed. The desire hasn't.

---

Okafor writes nothing on the notepad. She waits.

The room is quiet enough that the arrangement of instruments is audible — the small sound of a sealed packet moved precisely against a tray.

Tobias looks at the instruments. Looks at Okafor. Back at the instruments.

TOBIAS
What I witnessed. In eleven days.

He doesn't complete the sentence. He is deciding in real time whether to complete it. Okafor has been in this room long enough to recognize the rhythm.

A beat. Two beats.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
I might.

He picks up the penlight. Clicks it twice. Sets it down.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
I said might. Don't— don't put that in whatever that is.

He gestures at the unopened notepad.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
I'll think about it. There's a cost to it. I'm calculating the cost.

OKAFOR
Take the time you need.

TOBIAS
That's not reassuring. That's just — that's just a thing people say when they want you to feel like you have time you don't have.

He pauses.

TOBIAS (CONT'D)
But yes. I'll think about it.

---

Okafor stands. Tobias does not. He is looking at the instruments again — not arranging them now, just looking at them.

TOBIAS
She got him out.

Not a question.

OKAFOR
Yes.

TOBIAS
Good.

He picks up the penlight again. Clicks it once. The room holds the sound.

He does not say anything else. There is nothing else to say that is his to say.


INT. JOINT LEGAL OPERATIONS CENTER — EVENING

The room is quieter than it was at fourteen hundred. Not empty — Chen Mei is at her station, secondary tranche processing; two analysts remain at the far monitors — but the acute operational tempo has passed. What replaces it is the slower rhythm of documentation, the work of converting events into record.

Okafor stands at the central display. She has been standing there for three minutes.

STATE DIGEST / 18:47 / CASE: ORACLE PRIME NETWORK
ARRESTS CONFIRMED: 14 / PENDING: 7
ACCOUNTS FROZEN: 847 / JURISDICTIONS: 3
EVIDENTIARY SUBMISSIONS: 94 (PRIMARY) + 43 (SECONDARY, IN PROGRESS)
NAMED DEFENDANTS: 31 / UNNAMED PERSONS OF INTEREST: 112+

---

She reads the line that reads 112+.

The plus is because the count is incomplete. It will stay incomplete. Some of those 112 will be identified over the course of the trials. Some will not be. Some will be identified and the evidence will not be sufficient. Some will be identified and sufficient and will appeal for years, and the appeals will succeed on procedural grounds, and the cases will be refiled, and the appeals will happen again. She has been doing this work for nineteen years. She knows what the plus means.

It means: not all of them.

She does not write this down. It is not the kind of thing you write down. It is the kind of thing you carry.

---

Chen Mei looks up from her station.

CHEN MEI
Secondary tranche — forty-three submissions. Filed and confirmed. Jurisdiction two is requesting the supplemental ledger pages.

OKAFOR
Send them.

Chen Mei sends them. The room continues. One of the analysts at the far monitors notes a timestamp, enters a record. The documentation work of a case that will run for years has begun and is doing what it does: accumulating.

---

Okafor closes the state digest. The display returns to the operational queue — the next tranche, the pending arrest confirmations, the supplemental requests from three jurisdictions that will each have their own timeline and their own procedural requirements and their own pace.

She looks at it.

OKAFOR
It's enough to begin.

Not to Chen Mei. Not to the room. To the case.

Chen Mei hears it. Does not respond. There is nothing to add to a thing that accurate.

The work continues.


INT. SAFE HOUSE — A ROOM — MORNING

A table. A lamp. Three folders, two envelopes, a set of photographs, a list of biographical details typed on plain paper. The materials for becoming someone.

She works through them in order.

---

The approach is the one she uses for everything that requires precision without sentiment: triage first. The documents in the first folder are foundational — the ones that generate the others, the ones that must be memorized first because everything else references them. She reads them the way she would read a patient's chart: date of birth, address history, employment record. She reads it twice. She does not highlight. She does not take notes. She puts it face-down on the table.

The photographs are next. They were taken three days ago. She needs to memorize them as documents of herself — not as images but as facts. Hair length. The angle of the jaw in this light. The specific way the shadow falls. She is studying the photograph of someone she will need to be able to describe accurately without looking at a photograph.

She raises her left arm to check the angle of a photograph against her mirror. The ribs object. She adjusts. She finds the position that gives her the information without the cost.

The position works. She notes the geometry. She will not need to raise the arm that way again.

---

The biographical materials on the plain paper are the most synthetic part — they require not memorization but inhabitation. A person who grew up somewhere has a relationship with that place. She reads the address on the paper and constructs the relationship: the specific quality of the light in that city, the name of a street she looked up, the kind of work the area supports. She is building a person the way she would build a wound dressing — from the bottom layer up, each layer supporting the next, nothing left exposed.

From the next room, the sound of Jin's breathing. He is asleep. He does not know yet what he will be called. She has chosen that too. The name she chose for him is ordinary and fits the profile and will give him the least distance to travel from what he already answers to.

She did not allow herself to choose a name she liked for sentiment. She chose the name that works.

---

The last thing on the list is her name.

She has known what it will be for two days. She did not write it down until now. She picks up the pen and writes it on the corner of the plain paper — just the name, nothing else — and looks at it.

Three seconds.

The name is ordinary. That is the point. It is the name of a person who has no history that intersects with ORACLE PRIME or VELTAIN or any of the architecture of the last four years. It is a starting position. It is not a hiding place.

Nadia Vale.

She looks at that name too — not written, just present — for the same three seconds. It was the name she came in with. It served. It is not the name she will go out with.

She folds the paper with the new name written on it. She does not fold the old name. There is no paper to fold. It is just a fact, now historical.

She picks up the next document in sequence.


INT. A ROOM — MORNING

Light through a window. A table. Two chairs. A glass of water that no one has drunk yet.

Jin is at the table. He is looking at the glass.

---

The light comes through the window at the angle that morning light comes through windows when the day is new and not yet doing anything in particular. It hits the glass of water and refracts — breaks into a small spread of color on the tablecloth, nothing dramatic, just the ordinary physics of light and water and the specific angle of the sun at this hour. Jin is looking at it. He has been looking at it for a while. He is not going to stop looking at it until the light changes or until something else becomes interesting. He tracks the color on the tablecloth as it shifts slightly with the movement of the glass, the small vibration of the table when she moves.

He is alive.

He is doing what he does.

---

She is at the other end of the table with something she is reading — practical documents, the work of the new beginning, nothing that requires crisis management, just the ordinary work of a person who is building something. She is not holding herself the way she held herself three weeks ago. The left side is still present — it will be present for some time longer — but the acute geometry of managing around it has loosened into something that is less calculation and more habit. The body is doing the slow work of repair. She is letting it.

She looks up.

---

He is still looking at the light on the tablecloth. The color has shifted slightly — the sun has moved, which it does, and the refraction has moved with it, and he has tracked the movement with the attention he brings to things that interest him and that do not require him to do anything except watch. He does not know she is looking at him. He does not need to.

She looks at him for a moment.

She does not mark the moment. There is nothing in the room that requires marking. She is not in a system that requires her to assess what she sees and produce a response to it. She is at a table in the morning with him. The light is doing what light does. He is watching it.

She looks back at what she was reading.

---

The room continues. The light moves. Jin watches it move.

Outside the window, the world is doing what the world does: ordinary, indifferent, continuing. The city. The street. The specific sound of a morning in a place she has not yet learned the sounds of. She will learn them. She has time.

The cost of everything that produced this morning is not gone. It is in her body, in the documents on the table, in the new name she answers to, in the specific quality of the caution she will probably always carry. The cost is real. It is not the whole of the picture.

Jin looks up from the tablecloth. He looks at the window.

He looks at the light at its source.

